* For [[PropertyValue]], it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

inputs.name: valueReference
inputs.help: A secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature or a type of measurement.

Apartment.name: Apartment
Apartment.help: An apartment (in American English) or flat (in British English) is a self-contained housing unit (a type of residential real estate) that occupies only part of a building (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apartment).

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

inputs.name: occupancy
inputs.help:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person

MedicalObservationalStudy.name: MedicalObservationalStudy
MedicalObservationalStudy.help: An observational study is a type of medical study that attempts to infer the possible effect of a treatment through observation of a cohort of subjects over a period of time. In an observational study, the assignment of subjects into treatment groups versus control groups is outside the control of the investigator. This is in contrast with controlled studies, such as the randomized controlled trials represented by MedicalTrial, where each subject is randomly assigned to a treatment group or a control group before the start of the treatment.

inputs.name: studyDesign
inputs.help: Specifics about the observational study design (enumerated).

PriceSpecification.name: PriceSpecification
PriceSpecification.help: A structured value representing a price or price range. Typically, only the subclasses of this type are used for markup. It is recommended to use [[MonetaryAmount]] to describe independent amounts of money such as a salary, credit card limits, etc.

inputs.name: eligibleQuantity
inputs.help: The interval and unit of measurement of ordering quantities for which the offer or price specification is valid. This allows e.g. specifying that a certain freight charge is valid only for a certain quantity.

inputs.name: eligibleTransactionVolume
inputs.help: The transaction volume, in a monetary unit, for which the offer or price specification is valid, e.g. for indicating a minimal purchasing volume, to express free shipping above a certain order volume, or to limit the acceptance of credit cards to purchases to a certain minimal amount.

inputs.name: maxPrice
inputs.help: The highest price if the price is a range.

inputs.name: minPrice
inputs.help: The lowest price if the price is a range.

inputs.name: price
inputs.help:
The offer price of a product, or of a price component when attached to PriceSpecification and its subtypes.

Usage guidelines:

* Use the [[priceCurrency]] property (with standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR") instead of including [ambiguous symbols](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign#Currencies_that_use_the_dollar_or_peso_sign) such as '$' in the value.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.
* Note that both [RDFa](http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml-rdfa-primer/#using-the-content-attribute) and Microdata syntax allow the use of a "content=" attribute for publishing simple machine-readable values alongside more human-friendly formatting.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.

inputs.name: priceCurrency
inputs.help: The currency of the price, or a price component when attached to [[PriceSpecification]] and its subtypes.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: validFrom
inputs.help: The date when the item becomes valid.

inputs.name: validThrough
inputs.help: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

inputs.name: valueAddedTaxIncluded
inputs.help: Specifies whether the applicable value-added tax (VAT) is included in the price specification or not.

EnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.name: EnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
EnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.help: Enumerates energy efficiency levels (also known as "classes" or "ratings") and certifications that are part of several international energy efficiency standards.

PayAction.name: PayAction
PayAction.help: An agent pays a price to a participant.

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

ConfirmAction.name: ConfirmAction
ConfirmAction.help:
The act of notifying someone that a future event/action is going to happen as expected.

Related actions:

* [[CancelAction]]: The antonym of ConfirmAction.

DefinedRegion.name: DefinedRegion
DefinedRegion.help:
A DefinedRegion is a geographic area defined by potentially arbitrary (rather than political, administrative or natural geographical) criteria. Properties are provided for defining a region by reference to sets of postal codes.

Examples: a delivery destination when shopping. Region where regional pricing is configured.

Requirement 1:
Country: US
States: "NY", "CA"

Requirement 2:
Country: US
PostalCode Set: { [94000-94585], [97000, 97999], [13000, 13599]}
{ [12345, 12345], [78945, 78945], }
Region = state, canton, prefecture, autonomous community...

inputs.name: addressCountry
inputs.help: The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1).

inputs.name: addressRegion
inputs.help: The region in which the locality is, and which is in the country. For example, California or another appropriate first-level [Administrative division](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_administrative_divisions_by_country)

inputs.name: postalCode
inputs.help: The postal code. For example, 94043.

inputs.name: postalCodePrefix
inputs.help: A defined range of postal codes indicated by a common textual prefix. Used for non-numeric systems such as UK.

inputs.name: postalCodeRange
inputs.help: A defined range of postal codes.

EnergyStarEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.name: EnergyStarEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration
EnergyStarEnergyEfficiencyEnumeration.help: Used to indicate whether a product is EnergyStar certified.

PerformingArtsTheater.name: PerformingArtsTheater
PerformingArtsTheater.help: A theater or other performing art center.

Number.name: Number
Number.help:
Data type: Number.

Usage guidelines:

* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

Blog.name: Blog
Blog.help: A [blog](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blog), sometimes known as a "weblog". Note that the individual posts ([[BlogPosting]]s) in a [[Blog]] are often colloqually referred to by the same term.

inputs.name: blogPost
inputs.help: A posting that is part of this blog.

inputs.name: blogPosts
inputs.help: Indicates a post that is part of a [[Blog]]. Note that historically, what we term a "Blog" was once known as a "weblog", and that what we term a "BlogPosting" is now often colloquially referred to as a "blog".

inputs.name: issn
inputs.help: The International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) that identifies this serial publication. You can repeat this property to identify different formats of, or the linking ISSN (ISSN-L) for, this serial publication.

ShareAction.name: ShareAction
ShareAction.help: The act of distributing content to people for their amusement or edification.

WorkersUnion.name: WorkersUnion
WorkersUnion.help: A Workers Union (also known as a Labor Union, Labour Union, or Trade Union) is an organization that promotes the interests of its worker members by collectively bargaining with management, organizing, and political lobbying.

inputs.name: feesAndCommissionsSpecification
inputs.help: Description of fees, commissions, and other terms applied either to a class of financial product, or by a financial service organization.

MenuSection.name: MenuSection
MenuSection.help: A sub-grouping of food or drink items in a menu. E.g. courses (such as 'Dinner', 'Breakfast', etc.), specific type of dishes (such as 'Meat', 'Vegan', 'Drinks', etc.), or some other classification made by the menu provider.

inputs.name: hasMenuItem
inputs.help: A food or drink item contained in a menu or menu section.

inputs.name: hasMenuSection
inputs.help: A subgrouping of the menu (by dishes, course, serving time period, etc.).

MusicRecording.name: MusicRecording
MusicRecording.help: A music recording (track), usually a single song.

inputs.name: byArtist
inputs.help: The artist that performed this album or recording.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: inAlbum
inputs.help: The album to which this recording belongs.

inputs.name: inPlaylist
inputs.help: The playlist to which this recording belongs.

inputs.name: isrcCode
inputs.help: The International Standard Recording Code for the recording.

inputs.name: recordingOf
inputs.help: The composition this track is a recording of.

ComicStory.name: ComicStory
ComicStory.help:
The term "story" is any indivisible, re-printable
    	unit of a comic, including the interior stories, covers, and backmatter. Most
    	comics have at least two stories: a cover (ComicCoverArt) and an interior story.

inputs.name: artist
inputs.help:
The primary artist for a work
    	in a medium other than pencils or digital line art--for example, if the
    	primary artwork is done in watercolors or digital paints.

inputs.name: colorist
inputs.help: The individual who adds color to inked drawings.

inputs.name: inker
inputs.help: The individual who traces over the pencil drawings in ink after pencils are complete.

inputs.name: letterer
inputs.help: The individual who adds lettering, including speech balloons and sound effects, to artwork.

inputs.name: penciler
inputs.help: The individual who draws the primary narrative artwork.

CommunicateAction.name: CommunicateAction
CommunicateAction.help: The act of conveying information to another person via a communication medium (instrument) such as speech, email, or telephone conversation.

inputs.name: about
inputs.help: The subject matter of the content.

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: language
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The language used on this action.

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

ScreeningEvent.name: ScreeningEvent
ScreeningEvent.help: A screening of a movie or other video.

inputs.name: subtitleLanguage
inputs.help: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

inputs.name: videoFormat
inputs.help: The type of screening or video broadcast used (e.g. IMAX, 3D, SD, HD, etc.).

inputs.name: workPresented
inputs.help: The movie presented during this event.

MapCategoryType.name: MapCategoryType
MapCategoryType.help: An enumeration of several kinds of Map.

MedicalSpecialty.name: MedicalSpecialty
MedicalSpecialty.help: Any specific branch of medical science or practice. Medical specialities include clinical specialties that pertain to particular organ systems and their respective disease states, as well as allied health specialties. Enumerated type.

MedicalCause.name: MedicalCause
MedicalCause.help: The causative agent(s) that are responsible for the pathophysiologic process that eventually results in a medical condition, symptom or sign. In this schema, unless otherwise specified this is meant to be the proximate cause of the medical condition, symptom or sign. The proximate cause is defined as the causative agent that most directly results in the medical condition, symptom or sign. For example, the HIV virus could be considered a cause of AIDS. Or in a diagnostic context, if a patient fell and sustained a hip fracture and two days later sustained a pulmonary embolism which eventuated in a cardiac arrest, the cause of the cardiac arrest (the proximate cause) would be the pulmonary embolism and not the fall. Medical causes can include cardiovascular, chemical, dermatologic, endocrine, environmental, gastroenterologic, genetic, hematologic, gynecologic, iatrogenic, infectious, musculoskeletal, neurologic, nutritional, obstetric, oncologic, otolaryngologic, pharmacologic, psychiatric, pulmonary, renal, rheumatologic, toxic, traumatic, or urologic causes; medical conditions can be causes as well.

inputs.name: causeOf
inputs.help: The condition, complication, symptom, sign, etc. caused.

MobileApplication.name: MobileApplication
MobileApplication.help: A software application designed specifically to work well on a mobile device such as a telephone.

inputs.name: carrierRequirements
inputs.help: Specifies specific carrier(s) requirements for the application (e.g. an application may only work on a specific carrier network).

Campground.name: Campground
Campground.help:
A camping site, campsite, or [[Campground]] is a place used for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically containing individual [[CampingPitch]] locations. \n\n
In British English a campsite is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground. In American English the term campsite generally means an area where an individual, family, group, or military unit can pitch a tent or park a camper; a campground may contain many campsites (Source: Wikipedia see [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite)).\n\n

See also the dedicated [document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations](/docs/hotels.html).

DigitalDocumentPermissionType.name: DigitalDocumentPermissionType
DigitalDocumentPermissionType.help: A type of permission which can be granted for accessing a digital document.

LiquorStore.name: LiquorStore
LiquorStore.help: A shop that sells alcoholic drinks such as wine, beer, whisky and other spirits.

NonprofitType.name: NonprofitType
NonprofitType.help: NonprofitType enumerates several kinds of official non-profit types of which a non-profit organization can be.

HealthPlanNetwork.name: HealthPlanNetwork
HealthPlanNetwork.help: A US-style health insurance plan network.

inputs.name: healthPlanCostSharing
inputs.help: Whether The costs to the patient for services under this network or formulary.

inputs.name: healthPlanNetworkId
inputs.help: Name or unique ID of network. (Networks are often reused across different insurance plans).

inputs.name: healthPlanNetworkTier
inputs.help: The tier(s) for this network.

MedicalScholarlyArticle.name: MedicalScholarlyArticle
MedicalScholarlyArticle.help: A scholarly article in the medical domain.

inputs.name: publicationType
inputs.help: The type of the medical article, taken from the US NLM MeSH publication type catalog. See also [MeSH documentation](http://www.nlm.nih.gov/mesh/pubtypes.html).

SoftwareSourceCode.name: SoftwareSourceCode
SoftwareSourceCode.help: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

inputs.name: codeRepository
inputs.help: Link to the repository where the un-compiled, human readable code and related code is located (SVN, github, CodePlex).

inputs.name: codeSampleType
inputs.help: What type of code sample: full (compile ready) solution, code snippet, inline code, scripts, template.

inputs.name: programmingLanguage
inputs.help: The computer programming language.

inputs.name: runtime
inputs.help: Runtime platform or script interpreter dependencies (Example - Java v1, Python2.3, .Net Framework 3.0).

inputs.name: runtimePlatform
inputs.help: Runtime platform or script interpreter dependencies (Example - Java v1, Python2.3, .Net Framework 3.0).

inputs.name: sampleType
inputs.help: What type of code sample: full (compile ready) solution, code snippet, inline code, scripts, template.

inputs.name: targetProduct
inputs.help: Target Operating System / Product to which the code applies.  If applies to several versions, just the product name can be used.

PriceTypeEnumeration.name: PriceTypeEnumeration
PriceTypeEnumeration.help: Enumerates different price types, for example list price, invoice price, and sale price.

DefenceEstablishment.name: DefenceEstablishment
DefenceEstablishment.help: A defence establishment, such as an army or navy base.

LocalBusiness.name: LocalBusiness
LocalBusiness.help: A particular physical business or branch of an organization. Examples of LocalBusiness include a restaurant, a particular branch of a restaurant chain, a branch of a bank, a medical practice, a club, a bowling alley, etc.

inputs.name: branchOf
inputs.help: The larger organization that this local business is a branch of, if any. Not to be confused with (anatomical)[[branch]].

inputs.name: currenciesAccepted
inputs.help: The currency accepted.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: openingHours
inputs.help: The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'. * Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: ```Mo```, ```Tu```, ```We```, ```Th```, ```Fr```, ```Sa```, ```Su```. * Times are specified using 24:00 format. For example, 3pm is specified as ```15:00```, 10am as ```10:00```. * Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>. * If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

inputs.name: paymentAccepted
inputs.help: Cash, Credit Card, Cryptocurrency, Local Exchange Tradings System, etc.

inputs.name: priceRange
inputs.help: The price range of the business, for example ```$$$```.

BioChemEntity.name: BioChemEntity
BioChemEntity.help: Any biological, chemical, or biochemical thing. For example: a protein; a gene; a chemical; a synthetic chemical.

inputs.name: associatedDisease
inputs.help: Disease associated to this BioChemEntity. Such disease can be a MedicalCondition or a URL. If you want to add an evidence supporting the association, please use PropertyValue.

inputs.name: bioChemInteraction
inputs.help: A BioChemEntity that is known to interact with this item.

inputs.name: bioChemSimilarity
inputs.help: A similar BioChemEntity, e.g., obtained by fingerprint similarity algorithms.

inputs.name: biologicalRole
inputs.help: A role played by the BioChemEntity within a biological context.

inputs.name: hasBioChemEntityPart
inputs.help: Indicates a BioChemEntity that (in some sense) has this BioChemEntity as a part.

inputs.name: hasMolecularFunction
inputs.help: Molecular function performed by this BioChemEntity; please use PropertyValue if you want to include any evidence.

inputs.name: hasRepresentation
inputs.help: A common representation such as a protein sequence or chemical structure for this entity. For images use schema.org/image.

inputs.name: isEncodedByBioChemEntity
inputs.help: Another BioChemEntity encoding by this one.

inputs.name: isInvolvedInBiologicalProcess
inputs.help: Biological process this BioChemEntity is involved in; please use PropertyValue if you want to include any evidence.

inputs.name: isLocatedInSubcellularLocation
inputs.help: Subcellular location where this BioChemEntity is located; please use PropertyValue if you want to include any evidence.

inputs.name: isPartOfBioChemEntity
inputs.help: Indicates a BioChemEntity that is (in some sense) a part of this BioChemEntity.

inputs.name: taxonomicRange
inputs.help: The taxonomic grouping of the organism that expresses, encodes, or in someway related to the BioChemEntity.

Hostel.name: Hostel
Hostel.help:
A hostel - cheap accommodation, often in shared dormitories.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

inputs.name: calories
inputs.help: The number of calories.

inputs.name: carbohydrateContent
inputs.help: The number of grams of carbohydrates.

inputs.name: cholesterolContent
inputs.help: The number of milligrams of cholesterol.

inputs.name: fatContent
inputs.help: The number of grams of fat.

inputs.name: fiberContent
inputs.help: The number of grams of fiber.

inputs.name: proteinContent
inputs.help: The number of grams of protein.

inputs.name: saturatedFatContent
inputs.help: The number of grams of saturated fat.

inputs.name: servingSize
inputs.help: The serving size, in terms of the number of volume or mass.

inputs.name: sodiumContent
inputs.help: The number of milligrams of sodium.

inputs.name: sugarContent
inputs.help: The number of grams of sugar.

inputs.name: transFatContent
inputs.help: The number of grams of trans fat.

inputs.name: unsaturatedFatContent
inputs.help: The number of grams of unsaturated fat.

EducationalOccupationalProgram.name: EducationalOccupationalProgram
EducationalOccupationalProgram.help: A program offered by an institution which determines the learning progress to achieve an outcome, usually a credential like a degree or certificate. This would define a discrete set of opportunities (e.g., job, courses) that together constitute a program with a clear start, end, set of requirements, and transition to a new occupational opportunity (e.g., a job), or sometimes a higher educational opportunity (e.g., an advanced degree).

inputs.name: applicationDeadline
inputs.help: The date at which the program stops collecting applications for the next enrollment cycle.

inputs.name: applicationStartDate
inputs.help: The date at which the program begins collecting applications for the next enrollment cycle.

inputs.name: dayOfWeek
inputs.help: The day of the week for which these opening hours are valid.

inputs.name: educationalCredentialAwarded
inputs.help: A description of the qualification, award, certificate, diploma or other educational credential awarded as a consequence of successful completion of this course or program.

inputs.name: educationalProgramMode
inputs.help: Similar to courseMode, The medium or means of delivery of the program as a whole. The value may either be a text label (e.g. "online", "onsite" or "blended"; "synchronous" or "asynchronous"; "full-time" or "part-time") or a URL reference to a term from a controlled vocabulary (e.g. https://ceds.ed.gov/element/001311#Asynchronous ).

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: financialAidEligible
inputs.help: A financial aid type or program which students may use to pay for tuition or fees associated with the program.

inputs.name: hasCourse
inputs.help: A course or class that is one of the learning opportunities that constitute an educational / occupational program. No information is implied about whether the course is mandatory or optional; no guarantee is implied about whether the course will be available to everyone on the program.

inputs.name: maximumEnrollment
inputs.help: The maximum number of students who may be enrolled in the program.

inputs.name: numberOfCredits
inputs.help: The number of credits or units awarded by a Course or required to complete an EducationalOccupationalProgram.

inputs.name: occupationalCategory
inputs.help:
A category describing the job, preferably using a term from a taxonomy such as [BLS O*NET-SOC](http://www.onetcenter.org/taxonomy.html), [ISCO-08](https://www.ilo.org/public/english/bureau/stat/isco/isco08/) or similar, with the property repeated for each applicable value. Ideally the taxonomy should be identified, and both the textual label and formal code for the category should be provided.\n
Note: for historical reasons, any textual label and formal code provided as a literal may be assumed to be from O*NET-SOC.

inputs.name: occupationalCredentialAwarded
inputs.help: A description of the qualification, award, certificate, diploma or other occupational credential awarded as a consequence of successful completion of this course or program.

inputs.name: offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: programPrerequisites
inputs.help: Prerequisites for enrolling in the program.

inputs.name: programType
inputs.help: The type of educational or occupational program. For example, classroom, internship, alternance, etc..

inputs.name: provider
inputs.help: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

inputs.name: salaryUponCompletion
inputs.help: The expected salary upon completing the training.

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: termDuration
inputs.help: The amount of time in a term as defined by the institution. A term is a length of time where students take one or more classes. Semesters and quarters are common units for term.

inputs.name: termsPerYear
inputs.help: The number of times terms of study are offered per year. Semesters and quarters are common units for term. For example, if the student can only take 2 semesters for the program in one year, then termsPerYear should be 2.

inputs.name: timeOfDay
inputs.help: The time of day the program normally runs. For example, "evenings".

inputs.name: timeToComplete
inputs.help: The expected length of time to complete the program if attending full-time.

inputs.name: trainingSalary
inputs.help: The estimated salary earned while in the program.

inputs.name: typicalCreditsPerTerm
inputs.help: The number of credits or units a full-time student would be expected to take in 1 term however 'term' is defined by the institution.

RadioClip.name: RadioClip
RadioClip.help: A short radio program or a segment/part of a radio program.

TransferAction.name: TransferAction
TransferAction.help: The act of transferring/moving (abstract or concrete) animate or inanimate objects from one place to another.

inputs.name: fromLocation
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The original location of the object or the agent before the action.

inputs.name: toLocation
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The final location of the object or the agent after the action.

DataFeedItem.name: DataFeedItem
DataFeedItem.help: A single item within a larger data feed.

inputs.name: dateCreated
inputs.help: The date on which the CreativeWork was created or the item was added to a DataFeed.

inputs.name: dateDeleted
inputs.help: The datetime the item was removed from the DataFeed.

inputs.name: dateModified
inputs.help: The date on which the CreativeWork was most recently modified or when the item's entry was modified within a DataFeed.

inputs.name: item
inputs.help: An entity represented by an entry in a list or data feed (e.g. an 'artist' in a list of 'artists')’.

ApprovedIndication.name: ApprovedIndication
ApprovedIndication.help: An indication for a medical therapy that has been formally specified or approved by a regulatory body that regulates use of the therapy; for example, the US FDA approves indications for most drugs in the US.

ExhibitionEvent.name: ExhibitionEvent
ExhibitionEvent.help: Event type: Exhibition event, e.g. at a museum, library, archive, tradeshow, ...

SuspendAction.name: SuspendAction
SuspendAction.help: The act of momentarily pausing a device or application (e.g. pause music playback or pause a timer).

TakeAction.name: TakeAction
TakeAction.help:
The act of gaining ownership of an object from an origin. Reciprocal of GiveAction.

Related actions:

* [[GiveAction]]: The reciprocal of TakeAction.
* [[ReceiveAction]]: Unlike ReceiveAction, TakeAction implies that ownership has been transfered.

BreadcrumbList.name: BreadcrumbList
BreadcrumbList.help: A BreadcrumbList is an ItemList consisting of a chain of linked Web pages, typically described using at least their URL and their name, and typically ending with the current page.\n\nThe [[position]] property is used to reconstruct the order of the items in a BreadcrumbList The convention is that a breadcrumb list has an [[itemListOrder]] of [[ItemListOrderAscending]] (lower values listed first), and that the first items in this list correspond to the "top" or beginning of the breadcrumb trail, e.g. with a site or section homepage. The specific values of 'position' are not assigned meaning for a BreadcrumbList, but they should be integers, e.g. beginning with '1' for the first item in the list.

WearableMeasurementTypeEnumeration.name: WearableMeasurementTypeEnumeration
WearableMeasurementTypeEnumeration.help: Enumerates common types of measurement for wearables products.

AskPublicNewsArticle.name: AskPublicNewsArticle
AskPublicNewsArticle.help: A [[NewsArticle]] expressing an open call by a [[NewsMediaOrganization]] asking the public for input, insights, clarifications, anecdotes, documentation, etc., on an issue, for reporting purposes.

UseAction.name: UseAction
UseAction.help: The act of applying an object to its intended purpose.

SchoolDistrict.name: SchoolDistrict
SchoolDistrict.help: A School District is an administrative area for the administration of schools.

ComicIssue.name: ComicIssue
ComicIssue.help:
Individual comic issues are serially published as
    	part of a larger series. For the sake of consistency, even one-shot issues
    	belong to a series comprised of a single issue. All comic issues can be
    	uniquely identified by: the combination of the name and volume number of the
    	series to which the issue belongs; the issue number; and the variant
    	description of the issue (if any).

inputs.name: artist
inputs.help:
The primary artist for a work
    	in a medium other than pencils or digital line art--for example, if the
    	primary artwork is done in watercolors or digital paints.

inputs.name: colorist
inputs.help: The individual who adds color to inked drawings.

inputs.name: inker
inputs.help: The individual who traces over the pencil drawings in ink after pencils are complete.

inputs.name: letterer
inputs.help: The individual who adds lettering, including speech balloons and sound effects, to artwork.

inputs.name: penciler
inputs.help: The individual who draws the primary narrative artwork.

inputs.name: variantCover
inputs.help:
A description of the variant cover
    	for the issue, if the issue is a variant printing. For example, "Bryan Hitch
    	Variant Cover" or "2nd Printing Variant".

MedicalEnumeration.name: MedicalEnumeration
MedicalEnumeration.help: Enumerations related to health and the practice of medicine: A concept that is used to attribute a quality to another concept, as a qualifier, a collection of items or a listing of all of the elements of a set in medicine practice.

ActionAccessSpecification.name: ActionAccessSpecification
ActionAccessSpecification.help: A set of requirements that a must be fulfilled in order to perform an Action.

inputs.name: availabilityEnds
inputs.help: The end of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

inputs.name: availabilityStarts
inputs.help: The beginning of the availability of the product or service included in the offer.

inputs.name: category
inputs.help: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

inputs.name: eligibleRegion
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.\n\nSee also [[ineligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: expectsAcceptanceOf
inputs.help: An Offer which must be accepted before the user can perform the Action. For example, the user may need to buy a movie before being able to watch it.

inputs.name: ineligibleRegion
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.\n\nSee also [[eligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: requiresSubscription
inputs.help: Indicates if use of the media require a subscription  (either paid or free). Allowed values are ```true``` or ```false``` (note that an earlier version had 'yes', 'no').

WebPageElement.name: WebPageElement
WebPageElement.help: A web page element, like a table or an image.

inputs.name: cssSelector
inputs.help: A CSS selector, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

inputs.name: xpath
inputs.help: An XPath, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

inputs.name: duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: median
inputs.help: The median value.

inputs.name: percentile10
inputs.help: The 10th percentile value.

inputs.name: percentile25
inputs.help: The 25th percentile value.

inputs.name: percentile75
inputs.help: The 75th percentile value.

inputs.name: percentile90
inputs.help: The 90th percentile value.

MedicalWebPage.name: MedicalWebPage
MedicalWebPage.help: A web page that provides medical information.

inputs.name: aspect
inputs.help: An aspect of medical practice that is considered on the page, such as 'diagnosis', 'treatment', 'causes', 'prognosis', 'etiology', 'epidemiology', etc.

inputs.name: medicalAudience
inputs.help: Medical audience for page.

RejectAction.name: RejectAction
RejectAction.help:
The act of rejecting to/adopting an object.

Related actions:

* [[AcceptAction]]: The antonym of RejectAction.

TrainReservation.name: TrainReservation
TrainReservation.help: A reservation for train travel.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].

XPathType.name: XPathType
XPathType.help: Text representing an XPath (typically but not necessarily version 1.0).

MedicalRiskEstimator.name: MedicalRiskEstimator
MedicalRiskEstimator.help: Any rule set or interactive tool for estimating the risk of developing a complication or condition.

inputs.name: estimatesRiskOf
inputs.help: The condition, complication, or symptom whose risk is being estimated.

inputs.name: includedRiskFactor
inputs.help: A modifiable or non-modifiable risk factor included in the calculation, e.g. age, coexisting condition.

EventAttendanceModeEnumeration.name: EventAttendanceModeEnumeration
EventAttendanceModeEnumeration.help: An EventAttendanceModeEnumeration value is one of potentially several modes of organising an event, relating to whether it is online or offline.

Action.name: Action
Action.help: An action performed by a direct agent and indirect participants upon a direct object. Optionally happens at a location with the help of an inanimate instrument. The execution of the action may produce a result. Specific action sub-type documentation specifies the exact expectation of each argument/role.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/04/announcing-schemaorg-actions.html) and [Actions overview document](http://schema.org/docs/actions.html).

inputs.name: actionStatus
inputs.help: Indicates the current disposition of the Action.

inputs.name: agent
inputs.help: The direct performer or driver of the action (animate or inanimate). e.g. *John* wrote a book.

inputs.name: endTime
inputs.help: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: error
inputs.help: For failed actions, more information on the cause of the failure.

inputs.name: instrument
inputs.help: The object that helped the agent perform the action. e.g. John wrote a book with *a pen*.

inputs.name: location
inputs.help: The location of, for example, where an event is happening, where an organization is located, or where an action takes place.

inputs.name: object
inputs.help: The object upon which the action is carried out, whose state is kept intact or changed. Also known as the semantic roles patient, affected or undergoer (which change their state) or theme (which doesn't). e.g. John read *a book*.

inputs.name: participant
inputs.help: Other co-agents that participated in the action indirectly. e.g. John wrote a book with *Steve*.

inputs.name: result
inputs.help: The result produced in the action. e.g. John wrote *a book*.

inputs.name: startTime
inputs.help: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: target
inputs.help: Indicates a target EntryPoint for an Action.

AMRadioChannel.name: AMRadioChannel
AMRadioChannel.help: A radio channel that uses AM.

Vein.name: Vein
Vein.help: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries blood to the heart.

inputs.name: drainsTo
inputs.help: The vasculature that the vein drains into.

inputs.name: regionDrained
inputs.help: The anatomical or organ system drained by this vessel; generally refers to a specific part of an organ.

inputs.name: tributary
inputs.help: The anatomical or organ system that the vein flows into; a larger structure that the vein connects to.

LiveBlogPosting.name: LiveBlogPosting
LiveBlogPosting.help: A [[LiveBlogPosting]] is a [[BlogPosting]] intended to provide a rolling textual coverage of an ongoing event through continuous updates.

inputs.name: coverageEndTime
inputs.help: The time when the live blog will stop covering the Event. Note that coverage may continue after the Event concludes.

inputs.name: coverageStartTime
inputs.help: The time when the live blog will begin covering the Event. Note that coverage may begin before the Event's start time. The LiveBlogPosting may also be created before coverage begins.

inputs.name: liveBlogUpdate
inputs.help: An update to the LiveBlog.

LikeAction.name: LikeAction
LikeAction.help: The act of expressing a positive sentiment about the object. An agent likes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

LegalService.name: LegalService
LegalService.help: A LegalService is a business that provides legally-oriented services, advice and representation, e.g. law firms.\n\nAs a [[LocalBusiness]] it can be described as a [[provider]] of one or more [[Service]]\(s).

ReturnLabelSourceEnumeration.name: ReturnLabelSourceEnumeration
ReturnLabelSourceEnumeration.help: Enumerates several types of return labels for product returns.

MedicalIntangible.name: MedicalIntangible
MedicalIntangible.help: A utility class that serves as the umbrella for a number of 'intangible' things in the medical space.

PaymentCard.name: PaymentCard
PaymentCard.help: A payment method using a credit, debit, store or other card to associate the payment with an account.

inputs.name: cashBack
inputs.help: A cardholder benefit that pays the cardholder a small percentage of their net expenditures.

inputs.name: contactlessPayment
inputs.help: A secure method for consumers to purchase products or services via debit, credit or smartcards by using RFID or NFC technology.

inputs.name: floorLimit
inputs.help: A floor limit is the amount of money above which credit card transactions must be authorized.

inputs.name: monthlyMinimumRepaymentAmount
inputs.help: The minimum payment is the lowest amount of money that one is required to pay on a credit card statement each month.

DayOfWeek.name: DayOfWeek
DayOfWeek.help:
The day of the week, e.g. used to specify to which day the opening hours of an OpeningHoursSpecification refer.

Originally, URLs from [GoodRelations](http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1) were used (for [[Monday]], [[Tuesday]], [[Wednesday]], [[Thursday]], [[Friday]], [[Saturday]], [[Sunday]] plus a special entry for [[PublicHolidays]]); these have now been integrated directly into schema.org.

Organization.name: Organization
Organization.help: An organization such as a school, NGO, corporation, club, etc.

inputs.name: actionableFeedbackPolicy
inputs.help: For a [[NewsMediaOrganization]] or other news-related [[Organization]], a statement about public engagement activities (for news media, the newsroom’s), including involving the public - digitally or otherwise -- in coverage decisions, reporting and activities after publication.

inputs.name: address
inputs.help: Physical address of the item.

inputs.name: aggregateRating
inputs.help: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

inputs.name: alumni
inputs.help: Alumni of an organization.

inputs.name: areaServed
inputs.help: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

inputs.name: award
inputs.help: An award won by or for this item.

inputs.name: awards
inputs.help: Awards won by or for this item.

inputs.name: brand
inputs.help: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

inputs.name: contactPoint
inputs.help: A contact point for a person or organization.

inputs.name: contactPoints
inputs.help: A contact point for a person or organization.

inputs.name: correctionsPolicy
inputs.help: For an [[Organization]] (e.g. [[NewsMediaOrganization]]), a statement describing (in news media, the newsroom’s) disclosure and correction policy for errors.

inputs.name: department
inputs.help: A relationship between an organization and a department of that organization, also described as an organization (allowing different urls, logos, opening hours). For example: a store with a pharmacy, or a bakery with a cafe.

inputs.name: dissolutionDate
inputs.help: The date that this organization was dissolved.

inputs.name: diversityPolicy
inputs.help: Statement on diversity policy by an [[Organization]] e.g. a [[NewsMediaOrganization]]. For a [[NewsMediaOrganization]], a statement describing the newsroom’s diversity policy on both staffing and sources, typically providing staffing data.

inputs.name: diversityStaffingReport
inputs.help: For an [[Organization]] (often but not necessarily a [[NewsMediaOrganization]]), a report on staffing diversity issues. In a news context this might be for example ASNE or RTDNA (US) reports, or self-reported.

inputs.name: duns
inputs.help: The Dun & Bradstreet DUNS number for identifying an organization or business person.

inputs.name: email
inputs.help: Email address.

inputs.name: employee
inputs.help: Someone working for this organization.

inputs.name: employees
inputs.help: People working for this organization.

inputs.name: ethicsPolicy
inputs.help: Statement about ethics policy, e.g. of a [[NewsMediaOrganization]] regarding journalistic and publishing practices, or of a [[Restaurant]], a page describing food source policies. In the case of a [[NewsMediaOrganization]], an ethicsPolicy is typically a statement describing the personal, organizational, and corporate standards of behavior expected by the organization.

inputs.name: event
inputs.help: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

inputs.name: events
inputs.help: Upcoming or past events associated with this place or organization.

inputs.name: faxNumber
inputs.help: The fax number.

inputs.name: founder
inputs.help: A person who founded this organization.

inputs.name: founders
inputs.help: A person who founded this organization.

inputs.name: foundingDate
inputs.help: The date that this organization was founded.

inputs.name: foundingLocation
inputs.help: The place where the Organization was founded.

inputs.name: funder
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

inputs.name: globalLocationNumber
inputs.help: The [Global Location Number](http://www.gs1.org/gln) (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

inputs.name: hasCredential
inputs.help: A credential awarded to the Person or Organization.

inputs.name: hasMerchantReturnPolicy
inputs.help: Specifies a MerchantReturnPolicy that may be applicable.

inputs.name: hasOfferCatalog
inputs.help: Indicates an OfferCatalog listing for this Organization, Person, or Service.

inputs.name: hasPOS
inputs.help: Points-of-Sales operated by the organization or person.

inputs.name: interactionStatistic
inputs.help: The number of interactions for the CreativeWork using the WebSite or SoftwareApplication. The most specific child type of InteractionCounter should be used.

inputs.name: isicV4
inputs.help: The International Standard of Industrial Classification of All Economic Activities (ISIC), Revision 4 code for a particular organization, business person, or place.

inputs.name: knowsAbout
inputs.help: Of a [[Person]], and less typically of an [[Organization]], to indicate a topic that is known about - suggesting possible expertise but not implying it. We do not distinguish skill levels here, or relate this to educational content, events, objectives or [[JobPosting]] descriptions.

inputs.name: knowsLanguage
inputs.help: Of a [[Person]], and less typically of an [[Organization]], to indicate a known language. We do not distinguish skill levels or reading/writing/speaking/signing here. Use language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

inputs.name: legalName
inputs.help: The official name of the organization, e.g. the registered company name.

inputs.name: leiCode
inputs.help: An organization identifier that uniquely identifies a legal entity as defined in ISO 17442.

inputs.name: location
inputs.help: The location of, for example, where an event is happening, where an organization is located, or where an action takes place.

inputs.name: logo
inputs.help: An associated logo.

inputs.name: makesOffer
inputs.help: A pointer to products or services offered by the organization or person.

inputs.name: member
inputs.help: A member of an Organization or a ProgramMembership. Organizations can be members of organizations; ProgramMembership is typically for individuals.

inputs.name: memberOf
inputs.help: An Organization (or ProgramMembership) to which this Person or Organization belongs.

inputs.name: members
inputs.help: A member of this organization.

inputs.name: naics
inputs.help: The North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) code for a particular organization or business person.

inputs.name: nonprofitStatus
inputs.help: nonprofit Status indicates the legal status of a non-profit organization in its primary place of business.

inputs.name: numberOfEmployees
inputs.help: The number of employees in an organization e.g. business.

inputs.name: ownershipFundingInfo
inputs.help: For an [[Organization]] (often but not necessarily a [[NewsMediaOrganization]]), a description of organizational ownership structure; funding and grants. In a news/media setting, this is with particular reference to editorial independence.   Note that the [[funder]] is also available and can be used to make basic funder information machine-readable.

inputs.name: owns
inputs.help: Products owned by the organization or person.

inputs.name: parentOrganization
inputs.help: The larger organization that this organization is a [[subOrganization]] of, if any.

inputs.name: publishingPrinciples
inputs.help:
The publishingPrinciples property indicates (typically via [[URL]]) a document describing the editorial principles of an [[Organization]] (or individual e.g. a [[Person]] writing a blog) that relate to their activities as a publisher, e.g. ethics or diversity policies. When applied to a [[CreativeWork]] (e.g. [[NewsArticle]]) the principles are those of the party primarily responsible for the creation of the [[CreativeWork]].

While such policies are most typically expressed in natural language, sometimes related information (e.g. indicating a [[funder]]) can be expressed using schema.org terminology.

inputs.name: review
inputs.help: A review of the item.

inputs.name: reviews
inputs.help: Review of the item.

inputs.name: seeks
inputs.help: A pointer to products or services sought by the organization or person (demand).

inputs.name: serviceArea
inputs.help: The geographic area where the service is provided.

inputs.name: slogan
inputs.help: A slogan or motto associated with the item.

inputs.name: sponsor
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

inputs.name: subOrganization
inputs.help: A relationship between two organizations where the first includes the second, e.g., as a subsidiary. See also: the more specific 'department' property.

inputs.name: taxID
inputs.help: The Tax / Fiscal ID of the organization or person, e.g. the TIN in the US or the CIF/NIF in Spain.

inputs.name: telephone
inputs.help: The telephone number.

inputs.name: unnamedSourcesPolicy
inputs.help: For an [[Organization]] (typically a [[NewsMediaOrganization]]), a statement about policy on use of unnamed sources and the decision process required.

inputs.name: vatID
inputs.help: The Value-added Tax ID of the organization or person.

MusicRelease.name: MusicRelease
MusicRelease.help: A MusicRelease is a specific release of a music album.

inputs.name: catalogNumber
inputs.help: The catalog number for the release.

inputs.name: creditedTo
inputs.help: The group the release is credited to if different than the byArtist. For example, Red and Blue is credited to "Stefani Germanotta Band", but by Lady Gaga.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: musicReleaseFormat
inputs.help: Format of this release (the type of recording media used, ie. compact disc, digital media, LP, etc.).

inputs.name: recordLabel
inputs.help: The label that issued the release.

inputs.name: releaseOf
inputs.help: The album this is a release of.

ArriveAction.name: ArriveAction
ArriveAction.help: The act of arriving at a place. An agent arrives at a destination from a fromLocation, optionally with participants.

OwnershipInfo.name: OwnershipInfo
OwnershipInfo.help: A structured value providing information about when a certain organization or person owned a certain product.

inputs.name: acquiredFrom
inputs.help: The organization or person from which the product was acquired.

inputs.name: ownedFrom
inputs.help: The date and time of obtaining the product.

inputs.name: ownedThrough
inputs.help: The date and time of giving up ownership on the product.

inputs.name: typeOfGood
inputs.help: The product that this structured value is referring to.

inputs.name: amount
inputs.help: The amount of money.

inputs.name: funder
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

ComicSeries.name: ComicSeries
ComicSeries.help:
A sequential publication of comic stories under a
    	unifying title, for example "The Amazing Spider-Man" or "Groo the
    	Wanderer".

File.name: File
File.help: A media object, such as an image, video, or audio object embedded in a web page or a downloadable dataset i.e. DataDownload. Note that a creative work may have many media objects associated with it on the same web page. For example, a page about a single song (MusicRecording) may have a music video (VideoObject), and a high and low bandwidth audio stream (2 AudioObject's).

inputs.name: associatedArticle
inputs.help: A NewsArticle associated with the Media Object.

inputs.name: bitrate
inputs.help: The bitrate of the media object.

inputs.name: contentSize
inputs.help: File size in (mega/kilo) bytes.

inputs.name: contentUrl
inputs.help: Actual bytes of the media object, for example the image file or video file.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: embedUrl
inputs.help: A URL pointing to a player for a specific video. In general, this is the information in the ```src``` element of an ```embed``` tag and should not be the same as the content of the ```loc``` tag.

inputs.name: encodesCreativeWork
inputs.help: The CreativeWork encoded by this media object.

inputs.name: encodingFormat
inputs.help:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml) and [MDN reference](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Basics_of_HTTP/MIME_types)) e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.).

In cases where a [[CreativeWork]] has several media type representations, [[encoding]] can be used to indicate each [[MediaObject]] alongside particular [[encodingFormat]] information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

inputs.name: endTime
inputs.help: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: height
inputs.help: The height of the item.

inputs.name: ineligibleRegion
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.\n\nSee also [[eligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: interpretedAsClaim
inputs.help: Used to indicate a specific claim contained, implied, translated or refined from the content of a [[MediaObject]] or other [[CreativeWork]]. The interpreting party can be indicated using [[claimInterpreter]].

inputs.name: models#fileOf
inputs.help: Links from a File to its containing Object.

inputs.name: playerType
inputs.help: Player type required—for example, Flash or Silverlight.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: regionsAllowed
inputs.help: The regions where the media is allowed. If not specified, then it's assumed to be allowed everywhere. Specify the countries in [ISO 3166 format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166).

inputs.name: requiresSubscription
inputs.help: Indicates if use of the media require a subscription  (either paid or free). Allowed values are ```true``` or ```false``` (note that an earlier version had 'yes', 'no').

inputs.name: resultOf
inputs.help: Inverse of property result

inputs.name: sha256
inputs.help: The [SHA-2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SHA-2) SHA256 hash of the content of the item. For example, a zero-length input has value 'e3b0c44298fc1c149afbf4c8996fb92427ae41e4649b934ca495991b7852b855'

inputs.name: startTime
inputs.help: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: uploadDate
inputs.help: Date when this media object was uploaded to this site.

inputs.name: width
inputs.help: The width of the item.

inputs.name: caption
inputs.help: The caption for this object. For downloadable machine formats (closed caption, subtitles etc.) use MediaObject and indicate the [[encodingFormat]].

inputs.name: embeddedTextCaption
inputs.help: Represents textual captioning from a [[MediaObject]], e.g. text of a 'meme'.

inputs.name: exifData
inputs.help: exif data for this object.

inputs.name: representativeOfPage
inputs.help: Indicates whether this image is representative of the content of the page.

inputs.name: thumbnail
inputs.help: Thumbnail image for an image or video.

MedicalTestPanel.name: MedicalTestPanel
MedicalTestPanel.help: Any collection of tests commonly ordered together.

inputs.name: subTest
inputs.help: A component test of the panel.

DefinedTermSet.name: DefinedTermSet
DefinedTermSet.help: A set of defined terms for example a set of categories or a classification scheme, a glossary, dictionary or enumeration.

inputs.name: hasDefinedTerm
inputs.help: A Defined Term contained in this term set.

HyperTocEntry.name: HyperTocEntry
HyperTocEntry.help: A HyperToEntry is an item within a [[HyperToc]], which represents a hypertext table of contents for complex media objects, such as [[VideoObject]], [[AudioObject]]. The media object itself is indicated using [[associatedMedia]]. Each section of interest within that content can be described with a [[HyperTocEntry]], with associated [[startOffset]] and [[endOffset]]. When several entries are all from the same file, [[associatedMedia]] is used on the overarching [[HyperTocEntry]]; if the content has been split into multiple files, they can be referenced using [[associatedMedia]] on each [[HyperTocEntry]].

inputs.name: associatedMedia
inputs.help: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for encoding.

inputs.name: tocContinuation
inputs.help: A [[HyperTocEntry]] can have a [[tocContinuation]] indicated, which is another [[HyperTocEntry]] that would be the default next item to play or render.

inputs.name: utterances
inputs.help: Text of an utterances (spoken words, lyrics etc.) that occurs at a certain section of a media object, represented as a [[HyperTocEntry]].

WatchAction.name: WatchAction
WatchAction.help: The act of consuming dynamic/moving visual content.

Report.name: Report
Report.help: A Report generated by governmental or non-governmental organization.

inputs.name: reportNumber
inputs.help: The number or other unique designator assigned to a Report by the publishing organization.

MedicalIndication.name: MedicalIndication
MedicalIndication.help: A condition or factor that indicates use of a medical therapy, including signs, symptoms, risk factors, anatomical states, etc.

Specialty.name: Specialty
Specialty.help: Any branch of a field in which people typically develop specific expertise, usually after significant study, time, and effort.

QuantitativeValue.name: QuantitativeValue
QuantitativeValue.help: A point value or interval for product characteristics and other purposes.

inputs.name: additionalProperty
inputs.help: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

inputs.name: maxValue
inputs.help: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

inputs.name: minValue
inputs.help: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

inputs.name: unitCode
inputs.help: The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.

inputs.name: unitText
inputs.help: A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for unitCode.

inputs.name: value
inputs.help:
The value of the quantitative value or property value node.

* For [[QuantitativeValue]] and [[MonetaryAmount]], the recommended type for values is 'Number'.
* For [[PropertyValue]], it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

inputs.name: valueReference
inputs.help: A secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature or a type of measurement.

TVSeries.name: TVSeries
TVSeries.help: CreativeWorkSeries dedicated to TV broadcast and associated online delivery.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: actors
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: containsSeason
inputs.help: A season that is part of the media series.

inputs.name: countryOfOrigin
inputs.help:
The country of origin of something, including products as well as creative  works such as movie and TV content.

In the case of TV and movie, this would be the country of the principle offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie. For other kinds of [[CreativeWork]] it is difficult to provide fully general guidance, and properties such as [[contentLocation]] and [[locationCreated]] may be more applicable.

In the case of products, the country of origin of the product. The exact interpretation of this may vary by context and product type, and cannot be fully enumerated here.

inputs.name: director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: directors
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: episode
inputs.help: An episode of a tv, radio or game media within a series or season.

inputs.name: episodes
inputs.help: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

inputs.name: musicBy
inputs.help: The composer of the soundtrack.

inputs.name: numberOfEpisodes
inputs.help: The number of episodes in this season or series.

inputs.name: numberOfSeasons
inputs.help: The number of seasons in this series.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: season
inputs.help: A season in a media series.

inputs.name: seasons
inputs.help: A season in a media series.

inputs.name: trailer
inputs.help: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

InformAction.name: InformAction
InformAction.help: The act of notifying someone of information pertinent to them, with no expectation of a response.

inputs.name: event
inputs.help: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

AnatomicalStructure.name: AnatomicalStructure
AnatomicalStructure.help: Any part of the human body, typically a component of an anatomical system. Organs, tissues, and cells are all anatomical structures.

inputs.name: associatedPathophysiology
inputs.help: If applicable, a description of the pathophysiology associated with the anatomical system, including potential abnormal changes in the mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions of the system.

inputs.name: bodyLocation
inputs.help: Location in the body of the anatomical structure.

inputs.name: connectedTo
inputs.help: Other anatomical structures to which this structure is connected.

inputs.name: diagram
inputs.help: An image containing a diagram that illustrates the structure and/or its component substructures and/or connections with other structures.

inputs.name: partOfSystem
inputs.help: The anatomical or organ system that this structure is part of.

inputs.name: relatedCondition
inputs.help: A medical condition associated with this anatomy.

inputs.name: relatedTherapy
inputs.help: A medical therapy related to this anatomy.

inputs.name: subStructure
inputs.help: Component (sub-)structure(s) that comprise this anatomical structure.

QAPage.name: QAPage
QAPage.help: A QAPage is a WebPage focussed on a specific Question and its Answer(s), e.g. in a question answering site or documenting Frequently Asked Questions (FAQs).

RentalCarReservation.name: RentalCarReservation
RentalCarReservation.help: A reservation for a rental car.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

inputs.name: dropoffLocation
inputs.help: Where a rental car can be dropped off.

inputs.name: dropoffTime
inputs.help: When a rental car can be dropped off.

inputs.name: pickupLocation
inputs.help: Where a taxi will pick up a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.

inputs.name: pickupTime
inputs.help: When a taxi will pickup a passenger or a rental car can be picked up.

MedicalSignOrSymptom.name: MedicalSignOrSymptom
MedicalSignOrSymptom.help: Any feature associated or not with a medical condition. In medicine a symptom is generally subjective while a sign is objective.

inputs.name: possibleTreatment
inputs.help: A possible treatment to address this condition, sign or symptom.

EmployerReview.name: EmployerReview
EmployerReview.help: An [[EmployerReview]] is a review of an [[Organization]] regarding its role as an employer, written by a current or former employee of that organization.

inputs.name: dataset
inputs.help: A dataset contained in this catalog.

inputs.name: measurementTechnique
inputs.help:
A technique or technology used in a [[Dataset]] (or [[DataDownload]], [[DataCatalog]]),
corresponding to the method used for measuring the corresponding variable(s) (described using [[variableMeasured]]). This is oriented towards scientific and scholarly dataset publication but may have broader applicability; it is not intended as a full representation of measurement, but rather as a high level summary for dataset discovery.

For example, if [[variableMeasured]] is: molecule concentration, [[measurementTechnique]] could be: "mass spectrometry" or "nmr spectroscopy" or "colorimetry" or "immunofluorescence".

If the [[variableMeasured]] is "depression rating", the [[measurementTechnique]] could be "Zung Scale" or "HAM-D" or "Beck Depression Inventory".

If there are several [[variableMeasured]] properties recorded for some given data object, use a [[PropertyValue]] for each [[variableMeasured]] and attach the corresponding [[measurementTechnique]].

NewsArticle.name: NewsArticle
NewsArticle.help:
A NewsArticle is an article whose content reports news, or provides background context and supporting materials for understanding the news.

A more detailed overview of [schema.org News markup](/docs/news.html) is also available.

inputs.name: dateline
inputs.help:
A [dateline](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dateline) is a brief piece of text included in news articles that describes where and when the story was written or filed though the date is often omitted. Sometimes only a placename is provided.

Structured representations of dateline-related information can also be expressed more explicitly using [[locationCreated]] (which represents where a work was created e.g. where a news report was written).  For location depicted or described in the content, use [[contentLocation]].

Dateline summaries are oriented more towards human readers than towards automated processing, and can vary substantially. Some examples: "BEIRUT, Lebanon, June 2.", "Paris, France", "December 19, 2017 11:43AM Reporting from Washington", "Beijing/Moscow", "QUEZON CITY, Philippines".

inputs.name: printColumn
inputs.help: The number of the column in which the NewsArticle appears in the print edition.

inputs.name: printEdition
inputs.help: The edition of the print product in which the NewsArticle appears.

inputs.name: printPage
inputs.help: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the name of the page on which the article is found. Please note that this field is intended for the exact page name (e.g. A5, B18).

inputs.name: printSection
inputs.help: If this NewsArticle appears in print, this field indicates the print section in which the article appeared.

RefundTypeEnumeration.name: RefundTypeEnumeration
RefundTypeEnumeration.help: Enumerates several kinds of product return refund types.

SportsOrganization.name: SportsOrganization
SportsOrganization.help: Represents the collection of all sports organizations, including sports teams, governing bodies, and sports associations.

inputs.name: sport
inputs.help: A type of sport (e.g. Baseball).

TaxiService.name: TaxiService
TaxiService.help: A service for a vehicle for hire with a driver for local travel. Fares are usually calculated based on distance traveled.

HowToSection.name: HowToSection
HowToSection.help: A sub-grouping of steps in the instructions for how to achieve a result (e.g. steps for making a pie crust within a pie recipe).

inputs.name: steps
inputs.help: A single step item (as HowToStep, text, document, video, etc.) or a HowToSection (originally misnamed 'steps'; 'step' is preferred).

EngineSpecification.name: EngineSpecification
EngineSpecification.help: Information about the engine of the vehicle. A vehicle can have multiple engines represented by multiple engine specification entities.

inputs.name: engineDisplacement
inputs.help:
The volume swept by all of the pistons inside the cylinders of an internal combustion engine in a single movement. 

Typical unit code(s): CMQ for cubic centimeter, LTR for liters, INQ for cubic inches
* Note 1: You can link to information about how the given value has been determined using the [[valueReference]] property.
* Note 2: You can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: enginePower
inputs.help:
The power of the vehicle's engine.
    Typical unit code(s): KWT for kilowatt, BHP for brake horsepower, N12 for metric horsepower (PS, with 1 PS = 735,49875 W)

* Note 1: There are many different ways of measuring an engine's power. For an overview, see  [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horsepower#Engine_power_test_codes](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horsepower#Engine_power_test_codes).
* Note 2: You can link to information about how the given value has been determined using the [[valueReference]] property.
* Note 3: You can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

inputs.name: engineType
inputs.help: The type of engine or engines powering the vehicle.

inputs.name: fuelType
inputs.help: The type of fuel suitable for the engine or engines of the vehicle. If the vehicle has only one engine, this property can be attached directly to the vehicle.

inputs.name: torque
inputs.help:
The torque (turning force) of the vehicle's engine.

Typical unit code(s): NU for newton metre (N m), F17 for pound-force per foot, or F48 for pound-force per inch

* Note 1: You can link to information about how the given value has been determined (e.g. reference RPM) using the [[valueReference]] property.
* Note 2: You can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

Product.name: Product
Product.help: Any offered product or service. For example: a pair of shoes; a concert ticket; the rental of a car; a haircut; or an episode of a TV show streamed online.

inputs.name: additionalProperty
inputs.help: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

inputs.name: aggregateRating
inputs.help: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

inputs.name: audience
inputs.help: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

inputs.name: award
inputs.help: An award won by or for this item.

inputs.name: awards
inputs.help: Awards won by or for this item.

inputs.name: brand
inputs.help: The brand(s) associated with a product or service, or the brand(s) maintained by an organization or business person.

inputs.name: category
inputs.help: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

inputs.name: color
inputs.help: The color of the product.

inputs.name: countryOfAssembly
inputs.help: The place where the product was assembled.

inputs.name: countryOfLastProcessing
inputs.help: The place where the item (typically [[Product]]) was last processed and tested before importation.

inputs.name: countryOfOrigin
inputs.help:
The country of origin of something, including products as well as creative  works such as movie and TV content.

In the case of TV and movie, this would be the country of the principle offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie. For other kinds of [[CreativeWork]] it is difficult to provide fully general guidance, and properties such as [[contentLocation]] and [[locationCreated]] may be more applicable.

In the case of products, the country of origin of the product. The exact interpretation of this may vary by context and product type, and cannot be fully enumerated here.

inputs.name: depth
inputs.help: The depth of the item.

inputs.name: gtin
inputs.help: A Global Trade Item Number ([GTIN](https://www.gs1.org/standards/id-keys/gtin)). GTINs identify trade items, including products and services, using numeric identification codes. The [[gtin]] property generalizes the earlier [[gtin8]], [[gtin12]], [[gtin13]], and [[gtin14]] properties. The GS1 [digital link specifications](https://www.gs1.org/standards/Digital-Link/) express GTINs as URLs. A correct [[gtin]] value should be a valid GTIN, which means that it should be an all-numeric string of either 8, 12, 13 or 14 digits, or a "GS1 Digital Link" URL based on such a string. The numeric component should also have a [valid GS1 check digit](https://www.gs1.org/services/check-digit-calculator) and meet the other rules for valid GTINs. See also [GS1's GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) and [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Global_Trade_Item_Number) for more details. Left-padding of the gtin values is not required or encouraged.

inputs.name: gtin12
inputs.help: The GTIN-12 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. The GTIN-12 is the 12-digit GS1 Identification Key composed of a U.P.C. Company Prefix, Item Reference, and Check Digit used to identify trade items. See [GS1 GTIN Summary](http://www.gs1.org/barcodes/technical/idkeys/gtin) for more details.

inputs.name: gtin13
inputs.help: The GTIN-13 code of the product, or the product to which the offer refers. This is equivalent to 13-digit ISBN codes and EAN UCC-13.
