PaymentMethod.help:
A payment method is a standardized procedure for transferring the monetary amount for a purchase. Payment methods are characterized by the legal and technical structures used, and by the organization or group carrying out the transaction.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByBankTransferInAdvance
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ByInvoice
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Cash
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#CheckInAdvance
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#COD
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DirectDebit
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#GoogleCheckout
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PayPal
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PaySwarm

UserPlusOnes.name: UserPlusOnes
UserPlusOnes.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

WPHeader.name: WPHeader
WPHeader.help: The header section of the page.

UserInteraction.name: UserInteraction
UserInteraction.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

CreativeWork.name: CreativeWork
CreativeWork.help: The most generic kind of creative work, including books, movies, photographs, software programs, etc.

inputs.name: about
inputs.help: The subject matter of the content.

inputs.name: abstract
inputs.help: An abstract is a short description that summarizes a [[CreativeWork]].

inputs.name: accessMode
inputs.help: The human sensory perceptual system or cognitive faculty through which a person may process or perceive information. Expected values include: auditory, tactile, textual, visual, colorDependent, chartOnVisual, chemOnVisual, diagramOnVisual, mathOnVisual, musicOnVisual, textOnVisual.

inputs.name: accessModeSufficient
inputs.help: A list of single or combined accessModes that are sufficient to understand all the intellectual content of a resource. Expected values include:  auditory, tactile, textual, visual.

inputs.name: accessibilityAPI
inputs.help: Indicates that the resource is compatible with the referenced accessibility API ([WebSchemas wiki lists possible values](http://www.w3.org/wiki/WebSchemas/Accessibility)).

inputs.name: accessibilityControl
inputs.help: Identifies input methods that are sufficient to fully control the described resource ([WebSchemas wiki lists possible values](http://www.w3.org/wiki/WebSchemas/Accessibility)).

inputs.name: accessibilityFeature
inputs.help: Content features of the resource, such as accessible media, alternatives and supported enhancements for accessibility ([WebSchemas wiki lists possible values](http://www.w3.org/wiki/WebSchemas/Accessibility)).

inputs.name: accessibilityHazard
inputs.help: A characteristic of the described resource that is physiologically dangerous to some users. Related to WCAG 2.0 guideline 2.3 ([WebSchemas wiki lists possible values](http://www.w3.org/wiki/WebSchemas/Accessibility)).

inputs.name: accessibilitySummary
inputs.help: A human-readable summary of specific accessibility features or deficiencies, consistent with the other accessibility metadata but expressing subtleties such as "short descriptions are present but long descriptions will be needed for non-visual users" or "short descriptions are present and no long descriptions are needed."

inputs.name: accountablePerson
inputs.help: Specifies the Person that is legally accountable for the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: acquireLicensePage
inputs.help: Indicates a page documenting how licenses can be purchased or otherwise acquired, for the current item.

inputs.name: aggregateRating
inputs.help: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

inputs.name: alternativeHeadline
inputs.help: A secondary title of the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: archivedAt
inputs.help: Indicates a page or other link involved in archival of a [[CreativeWork]]. In the case of [[MediaReview]], the items in a [[MediaReviewItem]] may often become inaccessible, but be archived by archival, journalistic, activist, or law enforcement organizations. In such cases, the referenced page may not directly publish the content.

inputs.name: assesses
inputs.help: The item being described is intended to assess the competency or learning outcome defined by the referenced term.

inputs.name: associatedMedia
inputs.help: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for encoding.

inputs.name: audience
inputs.help: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

inputs.name: audio
inputs.help: An embedded audio object.

inputs.name: author
inputs.help: The author of this content or rating. Please note that author is special in that HTML 5 provides a special mechanism for indicating authorship via the rel tag. That is equivalent to this and may be used interchangeably.

inputs.name: award
inputs.help: An award won by or for this item.

inputs.name: awards
inputs.help: Awards won by or for this item.

inputs.name: character
inputs.help: Fictional person connected with a creative work.

inputs.name: citation
inputs.help: A citation or reference to another creative work, such as another publication, web page, scholarly article, etc.

inputs.name: comment
inputs.help: Comments, typically from users.

inputs.name: commentCount
inputs.help: The number of comments this CreativeWork (e.g. Article, Question or Answer) has received. This is most applicable to works published in Web sites with commenting system; additional comments may exist elsewhere.

inputs.name: conditionsOfAccess
inputs.help: Conditions that affect the availability of, or method(s) of access to, an item. Typically used for real world items such as an [[ArchiveComponent]] held by an [[ArchiveOrganization]]. This property is not suitable for use as a general Web access control mechanism. It is expressed only in natural language.\n\nFor example "Available by appointment from the Reading Room" or "Accessible only from logged-in accounts ".

inputs.name: contentLocation
inputs.help: The location depicted or described in the content. For example, the location in a photograph or painting.

inputs.name: contentRating
inputs.help: Official rating of a piece of content—for example,'MPAA PG-13'.

inputs.name: contentReferenceTime
inputs.help: The specific time described by a creative work, for works (e.g. articles, video objects etc.) that emphasise a particular moment within an Event.

inputs.name: contributor
inputs.help: A secondary contributor to the CreativeWork or Event.

inputs.name: copyrightHolder
inputs.help: The party holding the legal copyright to the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: copyrightNotice
inputs.help: Text of a notice appropriate for describing the copyright aspects of this Creative Work, ideally indicating the owner of the copyright for the Work.

inputs.name: copyrightYear
inputs.help: The year during which the claimed copyright for the CreativeWork was first asserted.

inputs.name: correction
inputs.help: Indicates a correction to a [[CreativeWork]], either via a [[CorrectionComment]], textually or in another document.

inputs.name: countryOfOrigin
inputs.help:
The country of origin of something, including products as well as creative  works such as movie and TV content.

In the case of TV and movie, this would be the country of the principle offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie. For other kinds of [[CreativeWork]] it is difficult to provide fully general guidance, and properties such as [[contentLocation]] and [[locationCreated]] may be more applicable.

In the case of products, the country of origin of the product. The exact interpretation of this may vary by context and product type, and cannot be fully enumerated here.

inputs.name: creativeWorkStatus
inputs.help: The status of a creative work in terms of its stage in a lifecycle. Example terms include Incomplete, Draft, Published, Obsolete. Some organizations define a set of terms for the stages of their publication lifecycle.

inputs.name: creator
inputs.help: The creator/author of this CreativeWork. This is the same as the Author property for CreativeWork.

inputs.name: creditText
inputs.help: Text that can be used to credit person(s) and/or organization(s) associated with a published Creative Work.

inputs.name: dateCreated
inputs.help: The date on which the CreativeWork was created or the item was added to a DataFeed.

inputs.name: dateModified
inputs.help: The date on which the CreativeWork was most recently modified or when the item's entry was modified within a DataFeed.

inputs.name: datePublished
inputs.help: Date of first broadcast/publication.

inputs.name: discussionUrl
inputs.help: A link to the page containing the comments of the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: editEIDR
inputs.help:
An [EIDR](https://eidr.org/) (Entertainment Identifier Registry) [[identifier]] representing a specific edit / edition for a work of film or television.

For example, the motion picture known as "Ghostbusters" whose [[titleEIDR]] is "10.5240/7EC7-228A-510A-053E-CBB8-J", has several edits e.g. "10.5240/1F2A-E1C5-680A-14C6-E76B-I" and "10.5240/8A35-3BEE-6497-5D12-9E4F-3".

Since schema.org types like [[Movie]] and [[TVEpisode]] can be used for both works and their multiple expressions, it is possible to use [[titleEIDR]] alone (for a general description), or alongside [[editEIDR]] for a more edit-specific description.

inputs.name: editor
inputs.help: Specifies the Person who edited the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: educationalAlignment
inputs.help:
An alignment to an established educational framework.

This property should not be used where the nature of the alignment can be described using a simple property, for example to express that a resource [[teaches]] or [[assesses]] a competency.

inputs.name: educationalLevel
inputs.help: The level in terms of progression through an educational or training context. Examples of educational levels include 'beginner', 'intermediate' or 'advanced', and formal sets of level indicators.

inputs.name: educationalUse
inputs.help: The purpose of a work in the context of education; for example, 'assignment', 'group work'.

inputs.name: encoding
inputs.help: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork. This property is a synonym for associatedMedia.

inputs.name: encodingFormat
inputs.help:
Media type typically expressed using a MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml) and [MDN reference](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Basics_of_HTTP/MIME_types)) e.g. application/zip for a SoftwareApplication binary, audio/mpeg for .mp3 etc.).

In cases where a [[CreativeWork]] has several media type representations, [[encoding]] can be used to indicate each [[MediaObject]] alongside particular [[encodingFormat]] information.

Unregistered or niche encoding and file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia/Wikidata entry.

inputs.name: encodings
inputs.help: A media object that encodes this CreativeWork.

inputs.name: exampleOfWork
inputs.help: A creative work that this work is an example/instance/realization/derivation of.

inputs.name: expires
inputs.help: Date the content expires and is no longer useful or available. For example a [[VideoObject]] or [[NewsArticle]] whose availability or relevance is time-limited, or a [[ClaimReview]] fact check whose publisher wants to indicate that it may no longer be relevant (or helpful to highlight) after some date.

inputs.name: fileFormat
inputs.help: Media type, typically MIME format (see [IANA site](http://www.iana.org/assignments/media-types/media-types.xhtml)) of the content e.g. application/zip of a SoftwareApplication binary. In cases where a CreativeWork has several media type representations, 'encoding' can be used to indicate each MediaObject alongside particular fileFormat information. Unregistered or niche file formats can be indicated instead via the most appropriate URL, e.g. defining Web page or a Wikipedia entry.

inputs.name: funder
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

inputs.name: genre
inputs.help: Genre of the creative work, broadcast channel or group.

inputs.name: hasPart
inputs.help: Indicates an item or CreativeWork that is part of this item, or CreativeWork (in some sense).

inputs.name: headline
inputs.help: Headline of the article.

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: interactionStatistic
inputs.help: The number of interactions for the CreativeWork using the WebSite or SoftwareApplication. The most specific child type of InteractionCounter should be used.

inputs.name: interactivityType
inputs.help: The predominant mode of learning supported by the learning resource. Acceptable values are 'active', 'expositive', or 'mixed'.

inputs.name: interpretedAsClaim
inputs.help: Used to indicate a specific claim contained, implied, translated or refined from the content of a [[MediaObject]] or other [[CreativeWork]]. The interpreting party can be indicated using [[claimInterpreter]].

inputs.name: isAccessibleForFree
inputs.help: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

inputs.name: isBasedOn
inputs.help: A resource from which this work is derived or from which it is a modification or adaption.

inputs.name: isBasedOnUrl
inputs.help: A resource that was used in the creation of this resource. This term can be repeated for multiple sources. For example, http://example.com/great-multiplication-intro.html.

inputs.name: isFamilyFriendly
inputs.help: Indicates whether this content is family friendly.

inputs.name: isPartOf
inputs.help: Indicates an item or CreativeWork that this item, or CreativeWork (in some sense), is part of.

inputs.name: keywords
inputs.help: Keywords or tags used to describe this content. Multiple entries in a keywords list are typically delimited by commas.

inputs.name: learningResourceType
inputs.help: The predominant type or kind characterizing the learning resource. For example, 'presentation', 'handout'.

inputs.name: license
inputs.help: A license document that applies to this content, typically indicated by URL.

inputs.name: locationCreated
inputs.help: The location where the CreativeWork was created, which may not be the same as the location depicted in the CreativeWork.

inputs.name: mainEntity
inputs.help: Indicates the primary entity described in some page or other CreativeWork.

inputs.name: maintainer
inputs.help: A maintainer of a [[Dataset]], software package ([[SoftwareApplication]]), or other [[Project]]. A maintainer is a [[Person]] or [[Organization]] that manages contributions to, and/or publication of, some (typically complex) artifact. It is common for distributions of software and data to be based on "upstream" sources. When [[maintainer]] is applied to a specific version of something e.g. a particular version or packaging of a [[Dataset]], it is always  possible that the upstream source has a different maintainer. The [[isBasedOn]] property can be used to indicate such relationships between datasets to make the different maintenance roles clear. Similarly in the case of software, a package may have dedicated maintainers working on integration into software distributions such as Ubuntu, as well as upstream maintainers of the underlying work.

inputs.name: material
inputs.help: A material that something is made from, e.g. leather, wool, cotton, paper.

inputs.name: materialExtent
inputs.help: The quantity of the materials being described or an expression of the physical space they occupy.

inputs.name: mentions
inputs.help: Indicates that the CreativeWork contains a reference to, but is not necessarily about a concept.

inputs.name: offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: pattern
inputs.help: A pattern that something has, for example 'polka dot', 'striped', 'Canadian flag'. Values are typically expressed as text, although links to controlled value schemes are also supported.

inputs.name: position
inputs.help: The position of an item in a series or sequence of items.

inputs.name: producer
inputs.help: The person or organization who produced the work (e.g. music album, movie, tv/radio series etc.).

inputs.name: provider
inputs.help: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

inputs.name: publication
inputs.help: A publication event associated with the item.

inputs.name: publisher
inputs.help: The publisher of the creative work.

inputs.name: publisherImprint
inputs.help: The publishing division which published the comic.

inputs.name: publishingPrinciples
inputs.help:
The publishingPrinciples property indicates (typically via [[URL]]) a document describing the editorial principles of an [[Organization]] (or individual e.g. a [[Person]] writing a blog) that relate to their activities as a publisher, e.g. ethics or diversity policies. When applied to a [[CreativeWork]] (e.g. [[NewsArticle]]) the principles are those of the party primarily responsible for the creation of the [[CreativeWork]].

While such policies are most typically expressed in natural language, sometimes related information (e.g. indicating a [[funder]]) can be expressed using schema.org terminology.

inputs.name: recordedAt
inputs.help: The Event where the CreativeWork was recorded. The CreativeWork may capture all or part of the event.

inputs.name: releasedEvent
inputs.help: The place and time the release was issued, expressed as a PublicationEvent.

inputs.name: review
inputs.help: A review of the item.

inputs.name: reviews
inputs.help: Review of the item.

inputs.name: schemaVersion
inputs.help:
Indicates (by URL or string) a particular version of a schema used in some CreativeWork. This property was created primarily to
    indicate the use of a specific schema.org release, e.g. ```10.0``` as a simple string, or more explicitly via URL, ```http://schema.org/docs/releases.html#v10.0```. There may be situations in which other schemas might usefully be referenced this way, e.g. ```http://dublincore.org/specifications/dublin-core/dces/1999-07-02/``` but this has not been carefully explored in the community.

inputs.name: sdDatePublished
inputs.help: Indicates the date on which the current structured data was generated / published. Typically used alongside [[sdPublisher]]

inputs.name: sdLicense
inputs.help: A license document that applies to this structured data, typically indicated by URL.

inputs.name: sdPublisher
inputs.help:
Indicates the party responsible for generating and publishing the current structured data markup, typically in cases where the structured data is derived automatically from existing published content but published on a different site. For example, student projects and open data initiatives often re-publish existing content with more explicitly structured metadata. The
[[sdPublisher]] property helps make such practices more explicit.

inputs.name: size
inputs.help: A standardized size of a product or creative work, specified either through a simple textual string (for example 'XL', '32Wx34L'), a  QuantitativeValue with a unitCode, or a comprehensive and structured [[SizeSpecification]]; in other cases, the [[width]], [[height]], [[depth]] and [[weight]] properties may be more applicable.

inputs.name: sourceOrganization
inputs.help: The Organization on whose behalf the creator was working.

inputs.name: spatial
inputs.help:
The "spatial" property can be used in cases when more specific properties
(e.g. [[locationCreated]], [[spatialCoverage]], [[contentLocation]]) are not known to be appropriate.

inputs.name: spatialCoverage
inputs.help:
The spatialCoverage of a CreativeWork indicates the place(s) which are the focus of the content. It is a subproperty of
      contentLocation intended primarily for more technical and detailed materials. For example with a Dataset, it indicates
      areas that the dataset describes: a dataset of New York weather would have spatialCoverage which was the place: the state of New York.

inputs.name: sponsor
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

inputs.name: teaches
inputs.help: The item being described is intended to help a person learn the competency or learning outcome defined by the referenced term.

inputs.name: temporal
inputs.help:
The "temporal" property can be used in cases where more specific properties
(e.g. [[temporalCoverage]], [[dateCreated]], [[dateModified]], [[datePublished]]) are not known to be appropriate.

inputs.name: temporalCoverage
inputs.help:
The temporalCoverage of a CreativeWork indicates the period that the content applies to, i.e. that it describes, either as a DateTime or as a textual string indicating a time period in [ISO 8601 time interval format](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601#Time_intervals). In
      the case of a Dataset it will typically indicate the relevant time period in a precise notation (e.g. for a 2011 census dataset, the year 2011 would be written "2011/2012"). Other forms of content e.g. ScholarlyArticle, Book, TVSeries or TVEpisode may indicate their temporalCoverage in broader terms - textually or via well-known URL.
      Written works such as books may sometimes have precise temporal coverage too, e.g. a work set in 1939 - 1945 can be indicated in ISO 8601 interval format format via "1939/1945".

Open-ended date ranges can be written with ".." in place of the end date. For example, "2015-11/.." indicates a range beginning in November 2015 and with no specified final date. This is tentative and might be updated in future when ISO 8601 is officially updated.

inputs.name: text
inputs.help: The textual content of this CreativeWork.

inputs.name: thumbnailUrl
inputs.help: A thumbnail image relevant to the Thing.

inputs.name: timeRequired
inputs.help: Approximate or typical time it takes to work with or through this learning resource for the typical intended target audience, e.g. 'PT30M', 'PT1H25M'.

inputs.name: translationOfWork
inputs.help: The work that this work has been translated from. e.g. 物种起源 is a translationOf “On the Origin of Species”

inputs.name: translator
inputs.help: Organization or person who adapts a creative work to different languages, regional differences and technical requirements of a target market, or that translates during some event.

inputs.name: typicalAgeRange
inputs.help: The typical expected age range, e.g. '7-9', '11-'.

inputs.name: usageInfo
inputs.help:
The schema.org [[usageInfo]] property indicates further information about a [[CreativeWork]]. This property is applicable both to works that are freely available and to those that require payment or other transactions. It can reference additional information e.g. community expectations on preferred linking and citation conventions, as well as purchasing details. For something that can be commercially licensed, usageInfo can provide detailed, resource-specific information about licensing options.

This property can be used alongside the license property which indicates license(s) applicable to some piece of content. The usageInfo property can provide information about other licensing options, e.g. acquiring commercial usage rights for an image that is also available under non-commercial creative commons licenses.

inputs.name: version
inputs.help: The version of the CreativeWork embodied by a specified resource.

inputs.name: video
inputs.help: An embedded video object.

inputs.name: workExample
inputs.help: Example/instance/realization/derivation of the concept of this creative work. eg. The paperback edition, first edition, or eBook.

inputs.name: workTranslation
inputs.help: A work that is a translation of the content of this work. e.g. 西遊記 has an English workTranslation “Journey to the West”,a German workTranslation “Monkeys Pilgerfahrt” and a Vietnamese  translation Tây du ký bình khảo.

Quotation.name: Quotation
Quotation.help: A quotation. Often but not necessarily from some written work, attributable to a real world author and - if associated with a fictional character - to any fictional Person. Use [[isBasedOn]] to link to source/origin. The [[recordedIn]] property can be used to reference a Quotation from an [[Event]].

inputs.name: spokenByCharacter
inputs.help: The (e.g. fictional) character, Person or Organization to whom the quotation is attributed within the containing CreativeWork.

EventSeries.name: EventSeries
EventSeries.help:
A series of [[Event]]s. Included events can relate with the series using the [[superEvent]] property.

An EventSeries is a collection of events that share some unifying characteristic. For example, "The Olympic Games" is a series, which
is repeated regularly. The "2012 London Olympics" can be presented both as an [[Event]] in the series "Olympic Games", and as an
[[EventSeries]] that included a number of sporting competitions as Events.

The nature of the association between the events in an [[EventSeries]] can vary, but typical examples could
include a thematic event series (e.g. topical meetups or classes), or a series of regular events that share a location, attendee group and/or organizers.

EventSeries has been defined as a kind of Event to make it easy for publishers to use it in an Event context without
worrying about which kinds of series are really event-like enough to call an Event. In general an EventSeries
may seem more Event-like when the period of time is compact and when aspects such as location are fixed, but
it may also sometimes prove useful to describe a longer-term series as an Event.

LegalForceStatus.name: LegalForceStatus
LegalForceStatus.help: A list of possible statuses for the legal force of a legislation.

MedicalRiskFactor.name: MedicalRiskFactor
MedicalRiskFactor.help: A risk factor is anything that increases a person's likelihood of developing or contracting a disease, medical condition, or complication.

inputs.name: increasesRiskOf
inputs.help: The condition, complication, etc. influenced by this factor.

inputs.name: aircraft
inputs.help: The kind of aircraft (e.g., "Boeing 747").

inputs.name: arrivalAirport
inputs.help: The airport where the flight terminates.

inputs.name: arrivalGate
inputs.help: Identifier of the flight's arrival gate.

inputs.name: arrivalTerminal
inputs.help: Identifier of the flight's arrival terminal.

inputs.name: boardingPolicy
inputs.help: The type of boarding policy used by the airline (e.g. zone-based or group-based).

inputs.name: carrier
inputs.help: 'carrier' is an out-dated term indicating the 'provider' for parcel delivery and flights.

inputs.name: departureAirport
inputs.help: The airport where the flight originates.

inputs.name: departureGate
inputs.help: Identifier of the flight's departure gate.

inputs.name: departureTerminal
inputs.help: Identifier of the flight's departure terminal.

inputs.name: estimatedFlightDuration
inputs.help: The estimated time the flight will take.

inputs.name: flightDistance
inputs.help: The distance of the flight.

inputs.name: flightNumber
inputs.help: The unique identifier for a flight including the airline IATA code. For example, if describing United flight 110, where the IATA code for United is 'UA', the flightNumber is 'UA110'.

inputs.name: mealService
inputs.help: Description of the meals that will be provided or available for purchase.

inputs.name: seller
inputs.help: An entity which offers (sells / leases / lends / loans) the services / goods.  A seller may also be a provider.

inputs.name: webCheckinTime
inputs.help: The time when a passenger can check into the flight online.

ContactPointOption.name: ContactPointOption
ContactPointOption.help: Enumerated options related to a ContactPoint.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: actors
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: countryOfOrigin
inputs.help:
The country of origin of something, including products as well as creative  works such as movie and TV content.

In the case of TV and movie, this would be the country of the principle offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie. For other kinds of [[CreativeWork]] it is difficult to provide fully general guidance, and properties such as [[contentLocation]] and [[locationCreated]] may be more applicable.

In the case of products, the country of origin of the product. The exact interpretation of this may vary by context and product type, and cannot be fully enumerated here.

inputs.name: director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: directors
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: musicBy
inputs.help: The composer of the soundtrack.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: subtitleLanguage
inputs.help: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

inputs.name: titleEIDR
inputs.help:
An [EIDR](https://eidr.org/) (Entertainment Identifier Registry) [[identifier]] representing at the most general/abstract level, a work of film or television.

For example, the motion picture known as "Ghostbusters" has a titleEIDR of  "10.5240/7EC7-228A-510A-053E-CBB8-J". This title (or work) may have several variants, which EIDR calls "edits". See [[editEIDR]].

Since schema.org types like [[Movie]] and [[TVEpisode]] can be used for both works and their multiple expressions, it is possible to use [[titleEIDR]] alone (for a general description), or alongside [[editEIDR]] for a more edit-specific description.

inputs.name: trailer
inputs.help: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

Newspaper.name: Newspaper
Newspaper.help: A publication containing information about varied topics that are pertinent to general information, a geographic area, or a specific subject matter (i.e. business, culture, education). Often published daily.

BankAccount.name: BankAccount
BankAccount.help: A product or service offered by a bank whereby one may deposit, withdraw or transfer money and in some cases be paid interest.

inputs.name: accountMinimumInflow
inputs.help: A minimum amount that has to be paid in every month.

inputs.name: accountOverdraftLimit
inputs.help: An overdraft is an extension of credit from a lending institution when an account reaches zero. An overdraft allows the individual to continue withdrawing money even if the account has no funds in it. Basically the bank allows people to borrow a set amount of money.

inputs.name: bankAccountType
inputs.help: The type of a bank account.

LearningResource.name: LearningResource
LearningResource.help:
The LearningResource type can be used to indicate [[CreativeWork]]s (whether physical or digital) that have a particular and explicit orientation towards learning, education, skill acquisition, and other educational purposes.

[[LearningResource]] is expected to be used as an addition to a primary type such as [[Book]], [[VideoObject]], [[Product]] etc.

[[EducationEvent]] serves a similar purpose for event-like things (e.g. a [[Trip]]). A [[LearningResource]] may be created as a result of an [[EducationEvent]], for example by recording one.

inputs.name: assesses
inputs.help: The item being described is intended to assess the competency or learning outcome defined by the referenced term.

inputs.name: competencyRequired
inputs.help: Knowledge, skill, ability or personal attribute that must be demonstrated by a person or other entity in order to do something such as earn an Educational Occupational Credential or understand a LearningResource.

inputs.name: educationalAlignment
inputs.help:
An alignment to an established educational framework.

This property should not be used where the nature of the alignment can be described using a simple property, for example to express that a resource [[teaches]] or [[assesses]] a competency.

inputs.name: educationalLevel
inputs.help: The level in terms of progression through an educational or training context. Examples of educational levels include 'beginner', 'intermediate' or 'advanced', and formal sets of level indicators.

inputs.name: educationalUse
inputs.help: The purpose of a work in the context of education; for example, 'assignment', 'group work'.

inputs.name: learningResourceType
inputs.help: The predominant type or kind characterizing the learning resource. For example, 'presentation', 'handout'.

inputs.name: teaches
inputs.help: The item being described is intended to help a person learn the competency or learning outcome defined by the referenced term.

LeaveAction.name: LeaveAction
LeaveAction.help:
An agent leaves an event / group with participants/friends at a location.

Related actions:

* [[JoinAction]]: The antonym of LeaveAction.
* [[UnRegisterAction]]: Unlike UnRegisterAction, LeaveAction implies leaving a group/team of people rather than a service.

inputs.name: event
inputs.help: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

inputs.name: composer
inputs.help: The person or organization who wrote a composition, or who is the composer of a work performed at some event.

inputs.name: firstPerformance
inputs.help: The date and place the work was first performed.

inputs.name: includedComposition
inputs.help: Smaller compositions included in this work (e.g. a movement in a symphony).

inputs.name: iswcCode
inputs.help: The International Standard Musical Work Code for the composition.

inputs.name: lyricist
inputs.help: The person who wrote the words.

inputs.name: lyrics
inputs.help: The words in the song.

inputs.name: musicArrangement
inputs.help: An arrangement derived from the composition.

inputs.name: musicCompositionForm
inputs.help: The type of composition (e.g. overture, sonata, symphony, etc.).

inputs.name: musicalKey
inputs.help: The key, mode, or scale this composition uses.

inputs.name: recordedAs
inputs.help: An audio recording of the work.

DiagnosticLab.name: DiagnosticLab
DiagnosticLab.help: A medical laboratory that offers on-site or off-site diagnostic services.

inputs.name: availableTest
inputs.help: A diagnostic test or procedure offered by this lab.

UpdateAction.name: UpdateAction
UpdateAction.help: The act of managing by changing/editing the state of the object.

inputs.name: collection
inputs.help: A sub property of object. The collection target of the action.

inputs.name: targetCollection
inputs.help: A sub property of object. The collection target of the action.

FAQPage.name: FAQPage
FAQPage.help: A [[FAQPage]] is a [[WebPage]] presenting one or more "[Frequently asked questions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FAQ)" (see also [[QAPage]]).

MedicalDevicePurpose.name: MedicalDevicePurpose
MedicalDevicePurpose.help: Categories of medical devices, organized by the purpose or intended use of the device.

Joint.name: Joint
Joint.help: The anatomical location at which two or more bones make contact.

inputs.name: biomechnicalClass
inputs.help: The biomechanical properties of the bone.

inputs.name: functionalClass
inputs.help: The degree of mobility the joint allows.

inputs.name: structuralClass
inputs.help: The name given to how bone physically connects to each other.

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: phoneticText
inputs.help: Representation of a text [[textValue]] using the specified [[speechToTextMarkup]]. For example the city name of Houston in IPA: /ˈhjuːstən/.

inputs.name: speechToTextMarkup
inputs.help: Form of markup used. eg. [SSML](https://www.w3.org/TR/speech-synthesis11) or [IPA](https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Property:P898).

inputs.name: textValue
inputs.help: Text value being annotated.

DrugLegalStatus.name: DrugLegalStatus
DrugLegalStatus.help: The legal availability status of a medical drug.

inputs.name: applicableLocation
inputs.help: The location in which the status applies.

SearchAction.name: SearchAction
SearchAction.help:
The act of searching for an object.

Related actions:

* [[FindAction]]: SearchAction generally leads to a FindAction, but not necessarily.

inputs.name: query
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The query used on this action.

SuperficialAnatomy.name: SuperficialAnatomy
SuperficialAnatomy.help: Anatomical features that can be observed by sight (without dissection), including the form and proportions of the human body as well as surface landmarks that correspond to deeper subcutaneous structures. Superficial anatomy plays an important role in sports medicine, phlebotomy, and other medical specialties as underlying anatomical structures can be identified through surface palpation. For example, during back surgery, superficial anatomy can be used to palpate and count vertebrae to find the site of incision. Or in phlebotomy, superficial anatomy can be used to locate an underlying vein; for example, the median cubital vein can be located by palpating the borders of the cubital fossa (such as the epicondyles of the humerus) and then looking for the superficial signs of the vein, such as size, prominence, ability to refill after depression, and feel of surrounding tissue support. As another example, in a subluxation (dislocation) of the glenohumeral joint, the bony structure becomes pronounced with the deltoid muscle failing to cover the glenohumeral joint allowing the edges of the scapula to be superficially visible. Here, the superficial anatomy is the visible edges of the scapula, implying the underlying dislocation of the joint (the related anatomical structure).

inputs.name: associatedPathophysiology
inputs.help: If applicable, a description of the pathophysiology associated with the anatomical system, including potential abnormal changes in the mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions of the system.

inputs.name: relatedAnatomy
inputs.help: Anatomical systems or structures that relate to the superficial anatomy.

inputs.name: relatedCondition
inputs.help: A medical condition associated with this anatomy.

inputs.name: relatedTherapy
inputs.help: A medical therapy related to this anatomy.

inputs.name: significance
inputs.help: The significance associated with the superficial anatomy; as an example, how characteristics of the superficial anatomy can suggest underlying medical conditions or courses of treatment.

SolveMathAction.name: SolveMathAction
SolveMathAction.help: The action that takes in a math expression and directs users to a page potentially capable of solving/simplifying that expression.

inputs.name: eduQuestionType
inputs.help: For questions that are part of learning resources (e.g. Quiz), eduQuestionType indicates the format of question being given. Example: "Multiple choice", "Open ended", "Flashcard".

Taxon.name: Taxon
Taxon.help: A set of organisms asserted to represent a natural cohesive biological unit.

inputs.name: childTaxon
inputs.help: Closest child taxa of the taxon in question.

inputs.name: hasDefinedTerm
inputs.help: A Defined Term contained in this term set.

inputs.name: parentTaxon
inputs.help: Closest parent taxon of the taxon in question.

inputs.name: taxonRank
inputs.help: The taxonomic rank of this taxon given preferably as a URI from a controlled vocabulary – (typically the ranks from TDWG TaxonRank ontology or equivalent Wikidata URIs).

CreditCard.name: CreditCard
CreditCard.help:
A card payment method of a particular brand or name.  Used to mark up a particular payment method and/or the financial product/service that supplies the card account.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#AmericanExpress
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#DinersClub
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Discover
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#JCB
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#MasterCard
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#VISA

DefinedTerm.name: DefinedTerm
DefinedTerm.help: A word, name, acronym, phrase, etc. with a formal definition. Often used in the context of category or subject classification, glossaries or dictionaries, product or creative work types, etc. Use the name property for the term being defined, use termCode if the term has an alpha-numeric code allocated, use description to provide the definition of the term.

inputs.name: inDefinedTermSet
inputs.help: A [[DefinedTermSet]] that contains this term.

inputs.name: termCode
inputs.help: A code that identifies this [[DefinedTerm]] within a [[DefinedTermSet]]

inputs.name: alumni
inputs.help: Alumni of an organization.

PerformingGroup.name: PerformingGroup
PerformingGroup.help: A performance group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a circus.

Game.name: Game
Game.help: The Game type represents things which are games. These are typically rule-governed recreational activities, e.g. role-playing games in which players assume the role of characters in a fictional setting.

inputs.name: characterAttribute
inputs.help: A piece of data that represents a particular aspect of a fictional character (skill, power, character points, advantage, disadvantage).

inputs.name: gameItem
inputs.help: An item is an object within the game world that can be collected by a player or, occasionally, a non-player character.

inputs.name: gameLocation
inputs.help: Real or fictional location of the game (or part of game).

inputs.name: numberOfPlayers
inputs.help: Indicate how many people can play this game (minimum, maximum, or range).

inputs.name: quest
inputs.help: The task that a player-controlled character, or group of characters may complete in order to gain a reward.

AssessAction.name: AssessAction
AssessAction.help: The act of forming one's opinion, reaction or sentiment.

PaymentStatusType.name: PaymentStatusType
PaymentStatusType.help: A specific payment status. For example, PaymentDue, PaymentComplete, etc.

DiagnosticProcedure.name: DiagnosticProcedure
DiagnosticProcedure.help: A medical procedure intended primarily for diagnostic, as opposed to therapeutic, purposes.

ReturnFeesEnumeration.name: ReturnFeesEnumeration
ReturnFeesEnumeration.help: Enumerates several kinds of policies for product return fees.

Car.name: Car
Car.help: A car is a wheeled, self-powered motor vehicle used for transportation.

inputs.name: acrissCode
inputs.help: The ACRISS Car Classification Code is a code used by many car rental companies, for classifying vehicles. ACRISS stands for Association of Car Rental Industry Systems and Standards.

inputs.name: roofLoad
inputs.help:
The permitted total weight of cargo and installations (e.g. a roof rack) on top of the vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

* Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]] node.
* Note 2: You may also link to a [[QualitativeValue]] node that provides additional information using [[valueReference]]
* Note 3: Note that you can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

VideoGameClip.name: VideoGameClip
VideoGameClip.help: A short segment/part of a video game.

DeliveryChargeSpecification.name: DeliveryChargeSpecification
DeliveryChargeSpecification.help: The price for the delivery of an offer using a particular delivery method.

inputs.name: appliesToDeliveryMethod
inputs.help: The delivery method(s) to which the delivery charge or payment charge specification applies.

inputs.name: areaServed
inputs.help: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

inputs.name: eligibleRegion
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is valid.\n\nSee also [[ineligibleRegion]].

inputs.name: ineligibleRegion
inputs.help: The ISO 3166-1 (ISO 3166-1 alpha-2) or ISO 3166-2 code, the place, or the GeoShape for the geo-political region(s) for which the offer or delivery charge specification is not valid, e.g. a region where the transaction is not allowed.\n\nSee also [[eligibleRegion]].

FoodEstablishmentReservation.name: FoodEstablishmentReservation
FoodEstablishmentReservation.help: A reservation to dine at a food-related business.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations.

inputs.name: endTime
inputs.help: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: partySize
inputs.help: Number of people the reservation should accommodate.

inputs.name: startTime
inputs.help: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

RadioChannel.name: RadioChannel
RadioChannel.help: A unique instance of a radio BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

inputs.name: actionAccessibilityRequirement
inputs.help: A set of requirements that a must be fulfilled in order to perform an Action. If more than one value is specied, fulfilling one set of requirements will allow the Action to be performed.

inputs.name: expectsAcceptanceOf
inputs.help: An Offer which must be accepted before the user can perform the Action. For example, the user may need to buy a movie before being able to watch it.

CompleteDataFeed.name: CompleteDataFeed
CompleteDataFeed.help:
A [[CompleteDataFeed]] is a [[DataFeed]] whose standard representation includes content for every item currently in the feed.

This is the equivalent of Atom's element as defined in Feed Paging and Archiving [RFC 5005](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc5005), For example (and as defined for Atom), when using data from a feed that represents a collection of items that varies over time (e.g. "Top Twenty Records") there is no need to have newer entries mixed in alongside older, obsolete entries. By marking this feed as a CompleteDataFeed, old entries can be safely discarded when the feed is refreshed, since we can assume the feed has provided descriptions for all current items.

DiscussionForumPosting.name: DiscussionForumPosting
DiscussionForumPosting.help: A posting to a discussion forum.

MedicalProcedureType.name: MedicalProcedureType
MedicalProcedureType.help: An enumeration that describes different types of medical procedures.

Distance.name: Distance
Distance.help: Properties that take Distances as values are of the form '<Number> <Length unit of measure>'. E.g., '7 ft'.

UKNonprofitType.name: UKNonprofitType
UKNonprofitType.help: UKNonprofitType: Non-profit organization type originating from the United Kingdom.

Airline.name: Airline
Airline.help: An organization that provides flights for passengers.

inputs.name: boardingPolicy
inputs.help: The type of boarding policy used by the airline (e.g. zone-based or group-based).

inputs.name: iataCode
inputs.help: IATA identifier for an airline or airport.

MedicalConditionStage.name: MedicalConditionStage
MedicalConditionStage.help: A stage of a medical condition, such as 'Stage IIIa'.

inputs.name: stageAsNumber
inputs.help: The stage represented as a number, e.g. 3.

inputs.name: subStageSuffix
inputs.help: The substage, e.g. 'a' for Stage IIIa.

GeospatialGeometry.name: GeospatialGeometry
GeospatialGeometry.help: (Eventually to be defined as) a supertype of GeoShape designed to accommodate definitions from Geo-Spatial best practices.

inputs.name: geoContains
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a containing geometry to a contained geometry. "a contains b iff no points of b lie in the exterior of a, and at least one point of the interior of b lies in the interior of a". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoCoveredBy
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that covers it. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoCovers
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a covering geometry to a covered geometry. "Every point of b is a point of (the interior or boundary of) a". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoCrosses
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that crosses it: "a crosses b: they have some but not all interior points in common, and the dimension of the intersection is less than that of at least one of them". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoDisjoint
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically disjoint: they have no point in common. They form a set of disconnected geometries." (a symmetric relationship, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM))

inputs.name: geoEquals
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically equal, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM). "Two geometries are topologically equal if their interiors intersect and no part of the interior or boundary of one geometry intersects the exterior of the other" (a symmetric relationship)

inputs.name: geoIntersects
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) have at least one point in common. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoOverlaps
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that geospatially overlaps it, i.e. they have some but not all points in common. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoTouches
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) touch: they have at least one boundary point in common, but no interior points." (a symmetric relationship, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM) )

inputs.name: geoWithin
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to one that contains it, i.e. it is inside (i.e. within) its interior. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

Muscle.name: Muscle
Muscle.help: A muscle is an anatomical structure consisting of a contractile form of tissue that animals use to effect movement.

inputs.name: antagonist
inputs.help: The muscle whose action counteracts the specified muscle.

inputs.name: bloodSupply
inputs.help: The blood vessel that carries blood from the heart to the muscle.

inputs.name: insertion
inputs.help: The place of attachment of a muscle, or what the muscle moves.

inputs.name: muscleAction
inputs.help: The movement the muscle generates.

inputs.name: nerve
inputs.help: The underlying innervation associated with the muscle.

OpinionNewsArticle.name: OpinionNewsArticle
OpinionNewsArticle.help: An [[OpinionNewsArticle]] is a [[NewsArticle]] that primarily expresses opinions rather than journalistic reporting of news and events. For example, a [[NewsArticle]] consisting of a column or [[Blog]]/[[BlogPosting]] entry in the Opinions section of a news publication.

StatusEnumeration.name: StatusEnumeration
StatusEnumeration.help: Lists or enumerations dealing with status types.

HowToTool.name: HowToTool
HowToTool.help: A tool used (but not consumed) when performing instructions for how to achieve a result.

BodyMeasurementTypeEnumeration.name: BodyMeasurementTypeEnumeration
BodyMeasurementTypeEnumeration.help: Enumerates types (or dimensions) of a person's body measurements, for example for fitting of clothes.

BusOrCoach.name: BusOrCoach
BusOrCoach.help: A bus (also omnibus or autobus) is a road vehicle designed to carry passengers. Coaches are luxury busses, usually in service for long distance travel.

inputs.name: acrissCode
inputs.help: The ACRISS Car Classification Code is a code used by many car rental companies, for classifying vehicles. ACRISS stands for Association of Car Rental Industry Systems and Standards.

inputs.name: roofLoad
inputs.help:
The permitted total weight of cargo and installations (e.g. a roof rack) on top of the vehicle.

Typical unit code(s): KGM for kilogram, LBR for pound

* Note 1: You can indicate additional information in the [[name]] of the [[QuantitativeValue]] node.
* Note 2: You may also link to a [[QualitativeValue]] node that provides additional information using [[valueReference]]
* Note 3: Note that you can use [[minValue]] and [[maxValue]] to indicate ranges.

DepositAccount.name: DepositAccount
DepositAccount.help: A type of Bank Account with a main purpose of depositing funds to gain interest or other benefits.

ParkingFacility.name: ParkingFacility
ParkingFacility.help: A parking lot or other parking facility.

Thing.name: Thing
Thing.help: The most generic type of item.

inputs.name: additionalType
inputs.help: An additional type for the item, typically used for adding more specific types from external vocabularies in microdata syntax. This is a relationship between something and a class that the thing is in. In RDFa syntax, it is better to use the native RDFa syntax - the 'typeof' attribute - for multiple types. Schema.org tools may have only weaker understanding of extra types, in particular those defined externally.

inputs.name: alternateName
inputs.help: An alias for the item.

inputs.name: description
inputs.help: A description of the item.

inputs.name: disambiguatingDescription
inputs.help: A sub property of description. A short description of the item used to disambiguate from other, similar items. Information from other properties (in particular, name) may be necessary for the description to be useful for disambiguation.

inputs.name: identifier
inputs.help: The identifier property represents any kind of identifier for any kind of [[Thing]], such as ISBNs, GTIN codes, UUIDs etc. Schema.org provides dedicated properties for representing many of these, either as textual strings or as URL (URI) links. See [background notes](/docs/datamodel.html#identifierBg) for more details.

inputs.name: image
inputs.help: An image of the item. This can be a [[URL]] or a fully described [[ImageObject]].

inputs.name: mainEntityOfPage
inputs.help: Indicates a page (or other CreativeWork) for which this thing is the main entity being described. See [background notes](/docs/datamodel.html#mainEntityBackground) for details.

inputs.name: name
inputs.help: The name of the item.

inputs.name: potentialAction
inputs.help: Indicates a potential Action, which describes an idealized action in which this thing would play an 'object' role.

inputs.name: sameAs
inputs.help: URL of a reference Web page that unambiguously indicates the item's identity. E.g. the URL of the item's Wikipedia page, Wikidata entry, or official website.

inputs.name: subjectOf
inputs.help: A CreativeWork or Event about this Thing.

inputs.name: url
inputs.help: URL of the item.

HowToTip.name: HowToTip
HowToTip.help: An explanation in the instructions for how to achieve a result. It provides supplementary information about a technique, supply, author's preference, etc. It can explain what could be done, or what should not be done, but doesn't specify what should be done (see HowToDirection).

Event.name: Event
Event.help: An event happening at a certain time and location, such as a concert, lecture, or festival. Ticketing information may be added via the [[offers]] property. Repeated events may be structured as separate Event objects.

inputs.name: about
inputs.help: The subject matter of the content.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: aggregateRating
inputs.help: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

inputs.name: attendee
inputs.help: A person or organization attending the event.

inputs.name: attendees
inputs.help: A person attending the event.

inputs.name: audience
inputs.help: An intended audience, i.e. a group for whom something was created.

inputs.name: composer
inputs.help: The person or organization who wrote a composition, or who is the composer of a work performed at some event.

inputs.name: contributor
inputs.help: A secondary contributor to the CreativeWork or Event.

inputs.name: director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: doorTime
inputs.help: The time admission will commence.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: eventAttendanceMode
inputs.help: The eventAttendanceMode of an event indicates whether it occurs online, offline, or a mix.

inputs.name: eventSchedule
inputs.help:
Associates an [[Event]] with a [[Schedule]]. There are circumstances where it is preferable to share a schedule for a series of
      repeating events rather than data on the individual events themselves. For example, a website or application might prefer to publish a schedule for a weekly
      gym class rather than provide data on every event. A schedule could be processed by applications to add forthcoming events to a calendar. An [[Event]] that
      is associated with a [[Schedule]] using this property should not have [[startDate]] or [[endDate]] properties. These are instead defined within the associated
      [[Schedule]], this avoids any ambiguity for clients using the data. The property might have repeated values to specify different schedules, e.g. for different months
      or seasons.

inputs.name: eventStatus
inputs.help: An eventStatus of an event represents its status; particularly useful when an event is cancelled or rescheduled.

inputs.name: funder
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports (sponsors) something through some kind of financial contribution.

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: isAccessibleForFree
inputs.help: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

inputs.name: location
inputs.help: The location of, for example, where an event is happening, where an organization is located, or where an action takes place.

inputs.name: maximumAttendeeCapacity
inputs.help: The total number of individuals that may attend an event or venue.

inputs.name: maximumPhysicalAttendeeCapacity
inputs.help: The maximum physical attendee capacity of an [[Event]] whose [[eventAttendanceMode]] is [[OfflineEventAttendanceMode]] (or the offline aspects, in the case of a [[MixedEventAttendanceMode]]).

inputs.name: maximumVirtualAttendeeCapacity
inputs.help: The maximum physical attendee capacity of an [[Event]] whose [[eventAttendanceMode]] is [[OnlineEventAttendanceMode]] (or the online aspects, in the case of a [[MixedEventAttendanceMode]]).

inputs.name: offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: organizer
inputs.help: An organizer of an Event.

inputs.name: performer
inputs.help: A performer at the event—for example, a presenter, musician, musical group or actor.

inputs.name: performers
inputs.help: The main performer or performers of the event—for example, a presenter, musician, or actor.

inputs.name: previousStartDate
inputs.help: Used in conjunction with eventStatus for rescheduled or cancelled events. This property contains the previously scheduled start date. For rescheduled events, the startDate property should be used for the newly scheduled start date. In the (rare) case of an event that has been postponed and rescheduled multiple times, this field may be repeated.

inputs.name: recordedIn
inputs.help: The CreativeWork that captured all or part of this Event.

inputs.name: remainingAttendeeCapacity
inputs.help: The number of attendee places for an event that remain unallocated.

inputs.name: review
inputs.help: A review of the item.

inputs.name: sponsor
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: subEvent
inputs.help: An Event that is part of this event. For example, a conference event includes many presentations, each of which is a subEvent of the conference.

inputs.name: subEvents
inputs.help: Events that are a part of this event. For example, a conference event includes many presentations, each subEvents of the conference.

inputs.name: superEvent
inputs.help: An event that this event is a part of. For example, a collection of individual music performances might each have a music festival as their superEvent.

inputs.name: translator
inputs.help: Organization or person who adapts a creative work to different languages, regional differences and technical requirements of a target market, or that translates during some event.

inputs.name: typicalAgeRange
inputs.help: The typical expected age range, e.g. '7-9', '11-'.

inputs.name: workFeatured
inputs.help:
A work featured in some event, e.g. exhibited in an ExhibitionEvent.
       Specific subproperties are available for workPerformed (e.g. a play), or a workPresented (a Movie at a ScreeningEvent).

inputs.name: workPerformed
inputs.help: A work performed in some event, for example a play performed in a TheaterEvent.

VideoGame.name: VideoGame
VideoGame.help: A video game is an electronic game that involves human interaction with a user interface to generate visual feedback on a video device.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: actors
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: cheatCode
inputs.help: Cheat codes to the game.

inputs.name: director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: directors
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: gamePlatform
inputs.help: The electronic systems used to play video games.

inputs.name: gameServer
inputs.help: The server on which  it is possible to play the game.

inputs.name: gameTip
inputs.help: Links to tips, tactics, etc.

inputs.name: musicBy
inputs.help: The composer of the soundtrack.

inputs.name: playMode
inputs.help: Indicates whether this game is multi-player, co-op or single-player.  The game can be marked as multi-player, co-op and single-player at the same time.

inputs.name: trailer
inputs.help: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

RentAction.name: RentAction
RentAction.help: The act of giving money in return for temporary use, but not ownership, of an object such as a vehicle or property. For example, an agent rents a property from a landlord in exchange for a periodic payment.

inputs.name: landlord
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The owner of the real estate property.

inputs.name: realEstateAgent
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The real estate agent involved in the action.

CoverArt.name: CoverArt
CoverArt.help: The artwork on the outer surface of a CreativeWork.

CivicStructure.name: CivicStructure
CivicStructure.help: A public structure, such as a town hall or concert hall.

inputs.name: openingHours
inputs.help: The general opening hours for a business. Opening hours can be specified as a weekly time range, starting with days, then times per day. Multiple days can be listed with commas ',' separating each day. Day or time ranges are specified using a hyphen '-'. * Days are specified using the following two-letter combinations: ```Mo```, ```Tu```, ```We```, ```Th```, ```Fr```, ```Sa```, ```Su```. * Times are specified using 24:00 format. For example, 3pm is specified as ```15:00```, 10am as ```10:00```. * Here is an example: <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Tu,Th 16:00-20:00">Tuesdays and Thursdays 4-8pm</time>. * If a business is open 7 days a week, then it can be specified as <time itemprop="openingHours" datetime="Mo-Su">Monday through Sunday, all day</time>.

TVSeason.name: TVSeason
TVSeason.help: Season dedicated to TV broadcast and associated online delivery.

inputs.name: countryOfOrigin
inputs.help:
The country of origin of something, including products as well as creative  works such as movie and TV content.

In the case of TV and movie, this would be the country of the principle offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie. For other kinds of [[CreativeWork]] it is difficult to provide fully general guidance, and properties such as [[contentLocation]] and [[locationCreated]] may be more applicable.

In the case of products, the country of origin of the product. The exact interpretation of this may vary by context and product type, and cannot be fully enumerated here.

inputs.name: partOfTVSeries
inputs.help: The TV series to which this episode or season belongs.

BusTrip.name: BusTrip
BusTrip.help: A trip on a commercial bus line.

inputs.name: arrivalBusStop
inputs.help: The stop or station from which the bus arrives.

inputs.name: busName
inputs.help: The name of the bus (e.g. Bolt Express).

inputs.name: busNumber
inputs.help: The unique identifier for the bus.

inputs.name: departureBusStop
inputs.help: The stop or station from which the bus departs.

Time.name: Time
Time.help: A point in time recurring on multiple days in the form hh:mm:ss[Z|(+|-)hh:mm] (see [XML schema for details](http://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/#time)).

BedDetails.name: BedDetails
BedDetails.help: An entity holding detailed information about the available bed types, e.g. the quantity of twin beds for a hotel room. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you can use bed directly with a text. See also [[BedType]] (under development).

inputs.name: numberOfBeds
inputs.help: The quantity of the given bed type available in the HotelRoom, Suite, House, or Apartment.

inputs.name: typeOfBed
inputs.help: The type of bed to which the BedDetail refers, i.e. the type of bed available in the quantity indicated by quantity.

Suite.name: Suite
Suite.help:
A suite in a hotel or other public accommodation, denotes a class of luxury accommodations, the key feature of which is multiple rooms (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Suite_(hotel)).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

inputs.name: bed
inputs.help:
The type of bed or beds included in the accommodation. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you use bed directly with a text.
      If you want to indicate the quantity of a certain kind of bed, use an instance of BedDetails. For more detailed information, use the amenityFeature property.

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

inputs.name: occupancy
inputs.help:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person

CategoryCodeSet.name: CategoryCodeSet
CategoryCodeSet.help: A set of Category Code values.

inputs.name: hasCategoryCode
inputs.help: A Category code contained in this code set.

ProfessionalService.name: ProfessionalService
ProfessionalService.help:
Original definition: "provider of professional services."\n\nThe general [[ProfessionalService]] type for local businesses was deprecated due to confusion with [[Service]]. For reference, the types that it included were: [[Dentist]],
        [[AccountingService]], [[Attorney]], [[Notary]], as well as types for several kinds of [[HomeAndConstructionBusiness]]: [[Electrician]], [[GeneralContractor]],
        [[HousePainter]], [[Locksmith]], [[Plumber]], [[RoofingContractor]]. [[LegalService]] was introduced as a more inclusive supertype of [[Attorney]].

WebContent.name: WebContent
WebContent.help: WebContent is a type representing all [[WebPage]], [[WebSite]] and [[WebPageElement]] content. It is sometimes the case that detailed distinctions between Web pages, sites and their parts is not always important or obvious. The  [[WebContent]] type makes it easier to describe Web-addressable content without requiring such distinctions to always be stated. (The intent is that the existing types [[WebPage]], [[WebSite]] and [[WebPageElement]] will eventually be declared as subtypes of [[WebContent]]).

VideoGallery.name: VideoGallery
VideoGallery.help: Web page type: Video gallery page.

DrawAction.name: DrawAction
DrawAction.help: The act of producing a visual/graphical representation of an object, typically with a pen/pencil and paper as instruments.

TVClip.name: TVClip
TVClip.help: A short TV program or a segment/part of a TV program.

inputs.name: partOfTVSeries
inputs.help: The TV series to which this episode or season belongs.

TouristAttraction.name: TouristAttraction
TouristAttraction.help: A tourist attraction.  In principle any Thing can be a [[TouristAttraction]], from a [[Mountain]] and [[LandmarksOrHistoricalBuildings]] to a [[LocalBusiness]].  This Type can be used on its own to describe a general [[TouristAttraction]], or be used as an [[additionalType]] to add tourist attraction properties to any other type.  (See examples below)

inputs.name: availableLanguage
inputs.help: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]]

inputs.name: touristType
inputs.help: Attraction suitable for type(s) of tourist. eg. Children, visitors from a particular country, etc.

MediaSubscription.name: MediaSubscription
MediaSubscription.help: A subscription which allows a user to access media including audio, video, books, etc.

inputs.name: authenticator
inputs.help: The Organization responsible for authenticating the user's subscription. For example, many media apps require a cable/satellite provider to authenticate your subscription before playing media.

inputs.name: expectsAcceptanceOf
inputs.help: An Offer which must be accepted before the user can perform the Action. For example, the user may need to buy a movie before being able to watch it.

OrganizationRole.name: OrganizationRole
OrganizationRole.help: A subclass of Role used to describe roles within organizations.

inputs.name: numberedPosition
inputs.help: A number associated with a role in an organization, for example, the number on an athlete's jersey.

inputs.name: availableService
inputs.help: A medical service available from this provider.

inputs.name: healthcareReportingData
inputs.help: Indicates data describing a hospital, e.g. a CDC [[CDCPMDRecord]] or as some kind of [[Dataset]].

inputs.name: medicalSpecialty
inputs.help: A medical specialty of the provider.

AggregateRating.name: AggregateRating
AggregateRating.help: The average rating based on multiple ratings or reviews.

inputs.name: itemReviewed
inputs.help: The item that is being reviewed/rated.

inputs.name: ratingCount
inputs.help: The count of total number of ratings.

inputs.name: reviewCount
inputs.help: The count of total number of reviews.

WearAction.name: WearAction
WearAction.help: The act of dressing oneself in clothing.

WPSideBar.name: WPSideBar
WPSideBar.help: A sidebar section of the page.

OccupationalTherapy.name: OccupationalTherapy
OccupationalTherapy.help: A treatment of people with physical, emotional, or social problems, using purposeful activity to help them overcome or learn to deal with their problems.

MusicAlbumProductionType.name: MusicAlbumProductionType
MusicAlbumProductionType.help: Classification of the album by it's type of content: soundtrack, live album, studio album, etc.

BefriendAction.name: BefriendAction
BefriendAction.help:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone (object) mutually/bidirectionally/symmetrically.

Related actions:

* [[FollowAction]]: Unlike FollowAction, BefriendAction implies that the connection is reciprocal.

FilmAction.name: FilmAction
FilmAction.help: The act of capturing sound and moving images on film, video, or digitally.

RsvpResponseType.name: RsvpResponseType
RsvpResponseType.help: RsvpResponseType is an enumeration type whose instances represent responding to an RSVP request.

MobilePhoneStore.name: MobilePhoneStore
MobilePhoneStore.help: A store that sells mobile phones and related accessories.

Continent.name: Continent
Continent.help: One of the continents (for example, Europe or Africa).

MedicalBusiness.name: MedicalBusiness
MedicalBusiness.help: A particular physical or virtual business of an organization for medical purposes. Examples of MedicalBusiness include differents business run by health professionals.

VitalSign.name: VitalSign
VitalSign.help: Vital signs are measures of various physiological functions in order to assess the most basic body functions.

UserTweets.name: UserTweets
UserTweets.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

Observation.name: Observation
Observation.help:
Instances of the class [[Observation]] are used to specify observations about an entity (which may or may not be an instance of a [[StatisticalPopulation]]), at a particular time. The principal properties of an [[Observation]] are [[observedNode]], [[measuredProperty]], [[measuredValue]] (or [[median]], etc.) and [[observationDate]] ([[measuredProperty]] properties can, but need not always, be W3C RDF Data Cube "measure properties", as in the [lifeExpectancy example](https://www.w3.org/TR/vocab-data-cube/#dsd-example)).
See also [[StatisticalPopulation]], and the [data and datasets](/docs/data-and-datasets.html) overview for more details.

inputs.name: marginOfError
inputs.help: A marginOfError for an [[Observation]].

inputs.name: measuredProperty
inputs.help: The measuredProperty of an [[Observation]], either a schema.org property, a property from other RDF-compatible systems e.g. W3C RDF Data Cube, or schema.org extensions such as [GS1's](https://www.gs1.org/voc/?show=properties).

inputs.name: measuredValue
inputs.help: The measuredValue of an [[Observation]].

inputs.name: observationDate
inputs.help: The observationDate of an [[Observation]].

inputs.name: observedNode
inputs.help: The observedNode of an [[Observation]], often a [[StatisticalPopulation]].

RadioBroadcastService.name: RadioBroadcastService
RadioBroadcastService.help: A delivery service through which radio content is provided via broadcast over the air or online.

Legislation.name: Legislation
Legislation.help: A legal document such as an act, decree, bill, etc. (enforceable or not) or a component of a legal act (like an article).

inputs.name: jurisdiction
inputs.help: Indicates a legal jurisdiction, e.g. of some legislation, or where some government service is based.

inputs.name: legislationApplies
