inputs.help: Indicates that this legislation (or part of a legislation) somehow transfers another legislation in a different legislative context. This is an informative link, and it has no legal value. For legally-binding links of transposition, use the legislationTransposes property. For example an informative consolidated law of a European Union's member state "applies" the consolidated version of the European Directive implemented in it.

inputs.name: legislationChanges
inputs.help: Another legislation that this legislation changes. This encompasses the notions of amendment, replacement, correction, repeal, or other types of change. This may be a direct change (textual or non-textual amendment) or a consequential or indirect change. The property is to be used to express the existence of a change relationship between two acts rather than the existence of a consolidated version of the text that shows the result of the change. For consolidation relationships, use the legislationConsolidates property.

inputs.name: legislationConsolidates
inputs.help: Indicates another legislation taken into account in this consolidated legislation (which is usually the product of an editorial process that revises the legislation). This property should be used multiple times to refer to both the original version or the previous consolidated version, and to the legislations making the change.

inputs.name: legislationDate
inputs.help: The date of adoption or signature of the legislation. This is the date at which the text is officially aknowledged to be a legislation, even though it might not even be published or in force.

inputs.name: legislationDateVersion
inputs.help: The point-in-time at which the provided description of the legislation is valid (e.g. : when looking at the law on the 2016-04-07 (= dateVersion), I get the consolidation of 2015-04-12 of the "National Insurance Contributions Act 2015")

inputs.name: legislationIdentifier
inputs.help: An identifier for the legislation. This can be either a string-based identifier, like the CELEX at EU level or the NOR in France, or a web-based, URL/URI identifier, like an ELI (European Legislation Identifier) or an URN-Lex.

inputs.name: legislationJurisdiction
inputs.help: The jurisdiction from which the legislation originates.

inputs.name: legislationLegalForce
inputs.help: Whether the legislation is currently in force, not in force, or partially in force.

inputs.name: legislationPassedBy
inputs.help: The person or organization that originally passed or made the law : typically parliament (for primary legislation) or government (for secondary legislation). This indicates the "legal author" of the law, as opposed to its physical author.

inputs.name: legislationResponsible
inputs.help: An individual or organization that has some kind of responsibility for the legislation. Typically the ministry who is/was in charge of elaborating the legislation, or the adressee for potential questions about the legislation once it is published.

inputs.name: legislationTransposes
inputs.help: Indicates that this legislation (or part of legislation) fulfills the objectives set by another legislation, by passing appropriate implementation measures. Typically, some legislations of European Union's member states or regions transpose European Directives. This indicates a legally binding link between the 2 legislations.

inputs.name: legislationType
inputs.help: The type of the legislation. Examples of values are "law", "act", "directive", "decree", "regulation", "statutory instrument", "loi organique", "règlement grand-ducal", etc., depending on the country.

Episode.name: Episode
Episode.help: A media episode (e.g. TV, radio, video game) which can be part of a series or season.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: actors
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: directors
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: episodeNumber
inputs.help: Position of the episode within an ordered group of episodes.

inputs.name: musicBy
inputs.help: The composer of the soundtrack.

inputs.name: partOfSeason
inputs.help: The season to which this episode belongs.

inputs.name: partOfSeries
inputs.help: The series to which this episode or season belongs.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: trailer
inputs.help: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

DrugClass.name: DrugClass
DrugClass.help: A class of medical drugs, e.g., statins. Classes can represent general pharmacological class, common mechanisms of action, common physiological effects, etc.

inputs.name: drug
inputs.help: Specifying a drug or medicine used in a medication procedure.

Motorcycle.name: Motorcycle
Motorcycle.help: A motorcycle or motorbike is a single-track, two-wheeled motor vehicle.

PhysicalExam.name: PhysicalExam
PhysicalExam.help: A type of physical examination of a patient performed by a physician.

RestrictedDiet.name: RestrictedDiet
RestrictedDiet.help: A diet restricted to certain foods or preparations for cultural, religious, health or lifestyle reasons.

MedicalStudy.name: MedicalStudy
MedicalStudy.help: A medical study is an umbrella type covering all kinds of research studies relating to human medicine or health, including observational studies and interventional trials and registries, randomized, controlled or not. When the specific type of study is known, use one of the extensions of this type, such as MedicalTrial or MedicalObservationalStudy. Also, note that this type should be used to mark up data that describes the study itself; to tag an article that publishes the results of a study, use MedicalScholarlyArticle. Note: use the code property of MedicalEntity to store study IDs, e.g. clinicaltrials.gov ID.

inputs.name: healthCondition
inputs.help: Specifying the health condition(s) of a patient, medical study, or other target audience.

inputs.name: sponsor
inputs.help: A person or organization that supports a thing through a pledge, promise, or financial contribution. e.g. a sponsor of a Medical Study or a corporate sponsor of an event.

inputs.name: status
inputs.help: The status of the study (enumerated).

inputs.name: studyLocation
inputs.help: The location in which the study is taking/took place.

inputs.name: studySubject
inputs.help: A subject of the study, i.e. one of the medical conditions, therapies, devices, drugs, etc. investigated by the study.

MovieClip.name: MovieClip
MovieClip.help: A short segment/part of a movie.

LymphaticVessel.name: LymphaticVessel
LymphaticVessel.help: A type of blood vessel that specifically carries lymph fluid unidirectionally toward the heart.

inputs.name: originatesFrom
inputs.help: The vasculature the lymphatic structure originates, or afferents, from.

inputs.name: regionDrained
inputs.help: The anatomical or organ system drained by this vessel; generally refers to a specific part of an organ.

inputs.name: runsTo
inputs.help: The vasculature the lymphatic structure runs, or efferents, to.

FundingAgency.name: FundingAgency
FundingAgency.help:
A FundingAgency is an organization that implements one or more [[FundingScheme]]s and manages
    the granting process (via [[Grant]]s, typically [[MonetaryGrant]]s).
    A funding agency is not always required for grant funding, e.g. philanthropic giving, corporate sponsorship etc.
    
Examples of funding agencies include ERC, REA, NIH, Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation...

MortgageLoan.name: MortgageLoan
MortgageLoan.help: A loan in which property or real estate is used as collateral. (A loan securitized against some real estate).

inputs.name: domiciledMortgage
inputs.help: Whether borrower is a resident of the jurisdiction where the property is located.

inputs.name: loanMortgageMandateAmount
inputs.help: Amount of mortgage mandate that can be converted into a proper mortgage at a later stage.

SpeakableSpecification.name: SpeakableSpecification
SpeakableSpecification.help: A SpeakableSpecification indicates (typically via [[xpath]] or [[cssSelector]]) sections of a document that are highlighted as particularly [[speakable]]. Instances of this type are expected to be used primarily as values of the [[speakable]] property.

inputs.name: cssSelector
inputs.help: A CSS selector, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

inputs.name: xpath
inputs.help: An XPath, e.g. of a [[SpeakableSpecification]] or [[WebPageElement]]. In the latter case, multiple matches within a page can constitute a single conceptual "Web page element".

ServiceChannel.name: ServiceChannel
ServiceChannel.help: A means for accessing a service, e.g. a government office location, web site, or phone number.

inputs.name: availableLanguage
inputs.help: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]]

inputs.name: processingTime
inputs.help: Estimated processing time for the service using this channel.

inputs.name: providesService
inputs.help: The service provided by this channel.

inputs.name: serviceLocation
inputs.help: The location (e.g. civic structure, local business, etc.) where a person can go to access the service.

inputs.name: servicePhone
inputs.help: The phone number to use to access the service.

inputs.name: servicePostalAddress
inputs.help: The address for accessing the service by mail.

inputs.name: serviceSmsNumber
inputs.help: The number to access the service by text message.

inputs.name: serviceUrl
inputs.help: The website to access the service.

ImageGallery.name: ImageGallery
ImageGallery.help: Web page type: Image gallery page.

TypeAndQuantityNode.name: TypeAndQuantityNode
TypeAndQuantityNode.help: A structured value indicating the quantity, unit of measurement, and business function of goods included in a bundle offer.

inputs.name: amountOfThisGood
inputs.help: The quantity of the goods included in the offer.

inputs.name: businessFunction
inputs.help: The business function (e.g. sell, lease, repair, dispose) of the offer or component of a bundle (TypeAndQuantityNode). The default is http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.

inputs.name: typeOfGood
inputs.help: The product that this structured value is referring to.

inputs.name: unitCode
inputs.help: The unit of measurement given using the UN/CEFACT Common Code (3 characters) or a URL. Other codes than the UN/CEFACT Common Code may be used with a prefix followed by a colon.

inputs.name: unitText
inputs.help: A string or text indicating the unit of measurement. Useful if you cannot provide a standard unit code for unitCode.

CommentAction.name: CommentAction
CommentAction.help: The act of generating a comment about a subject.

inputs.name: resultComment
inputs.help: A sub property of result. The Comment created or sent as a result of this action.

GeoCoordinates.name: GeoCoordinates
GeoCoordinates.help: The geographic coordinates of a place or event.

inputs.name: address
inputs.help: Physical address of the item.

inputs.name: addressCountry
inputs.help: The country. For example, USA. You can also provide the two-letter [ISO 3166-1 alpha-2 country code](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1).

inputs.name: elevation
inputs.help: The elevation of a location ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)). Values may be of the form 'NUMBER UNIT_OF_MEASUREMENT' (e.g., '1,000 m', '3,200 ft') while numbers alone should be assumed to be a value in meters.

inputs.name: latitude
inputs.help: The latitude of a location. For example ```37.42242``` ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).

inputs.name: longitude
inputs.help: The longitude of a location. For example ```-122.08585``` ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).

inputs.name: postalCode
inputs.help: The postal code. For example, 94043.

inputs.name: downPayment
inputs.help: a type of payment made in cash during the onset of the purchase of an expensive good/service. The payment typically represents only a percentage of the full purchase price.

inputs.name: earlyPrepaymentPenalty
inputs.help: The amount to be paid as a penalty in the event of early payment of the loan.

inputs.name: loanPaymentAmount
inputs.help: The amount of money to pay in a single payment.

inputs.name: loanPaymentFrequency
inputs.help: Frequency of payments due, i.e. number of months between payments. This is defined as a frequency, i.e. the reciprocal of a period of time.

inputs.name: numberOfLoanPayments
inputs.help: The number of payments contractually required at origination to repay the loan. For monthly paying loans this is the number of months from the contractual first payment date to the maturity date.

Motel.name: Motel
Motel.help:
A motel.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

ReportageNewsArticle.name: ReportageNewsArticle
ReportageNewsArticle.help:
The [[ReportageNewsArticle]] type is a subtype of [[NewsArticle]] representing
 news articles which are the result of journalistic news reporting conventions.

In practice many news publishers produce a wide variety of article types, many of which might be considered a [[NewsArticle]] but not a [[ReportageNewsArticle]]. For example, opinion pieces, reviews, analysis, sponsored or satirical articles, or articles that combine several of these elements.

The [[ReportageNewsArticle]] type is based on a stricter ideal for "news" as a work of journalism, with articles based on factual information either observed or verified by the author, or reported and verified from knowledgeable sources.  This often includes perspectives from multiple viewpoints on a particular issue (distinguishing news reports from public relations or propaganda).  News reports in the [[ReportageNewsArticle]] sense de-emphasize the opinion of the author, with commentary and value judgements typically expressed elsewhere.

A [[ReportageNewsArticle]] which goes deeper into analysis can also be marked with an additional type of [[AnalysisNewsArticle]].

EventReservation.name: EventReservation
EventReservation.help: A reservation for an event like a concert, sporting event, or lecture.\n\nNote: This type is for information about actual reservations, e.g. in confirmation emails or HTML pages with individual confirmations of reservations. For offers of tickets, use [[Offer]].

QuoteAction.name: QuoteAction
QuoteAction.help: An agent quotes/estimates/appraises an object/product/service with a price at a location/store.

PublicationVolume.name: PublicationVolume
PublicationVolume.help: A part of a successively published publication such as a periodical or multi-volume work, often numbered. It may represent a time span, such as a year.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

inputs.name: pageEnd
inputs.help: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

inputs.name: pageStart
inputs.help: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

inputs.name: pagination
inputs.help: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

inputs.name: volumeNumber
inputs.help: Identifies the volume of publication or multi-part work; for example, "iii" or "2".

RVPark.name: RVPark
RVPark.help: A place offering space for "Recreational Vehicles", Caravans, mobile homes and the like.

AgreeAction.name: AgreeAction
AgreeAction.help: The act of expressing a consistency of opinion with the object. An agent agrees to/about an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

Ligament.name: Ligament
Ligament.help: A short band of tough, flexible, fibrous connective tissue that functions to connect multiple bones, cartilages, and structurally support joints.

SpecialAnnouncement.name: SpecialAnnouncement
SpecialAnnouncement.help:
A SpecialAnnouncement combines a simple date-stamped textual information update
      with contextualized Web links and other structured data.  It represents an information update made by a
      locally-oriented organization, for example schools, pharmacies, healthcare providers,  community groups, police,
      local government.

For work in progress guidelines on Coronavirus-related markup see [this doc](https://docs.google.com/document/d/14ikaGCKxo50rRM7nvKSlbUpjyIk2WMQd3IkB1lItlrM/edit#).

The motivating scenario for SpecialAnnouncement is the [Coronavirus pandemic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_coronavirus_pandemic), and the initial vocabulary is oriented to this urgent situation. Schema.org
expect to improve the markup iteratively as it is deployed and as feedback emerges from use. In addition to our
usual [Github entry](https://github.com/schemaorg/schemaorg/issues/2490), feedback comments can also be provided in [this document](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1fpdFFxk8s87CWwACs53SGkYv3aafSxz_DTtOQxMrBJQ/edit#).


While this schema is designed to communicate urgent crisis-related information, it is not the same as an emergency warning technology like [CAP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_Alerting_Protocol), although there may be overlaps. The intent is to cover
the kinds of everyday practical information being posted to existing websites during an emergency situation.

Several kinds of information can be provided:

We encourage the provision of "name", "text", "datePosted", "expires" (if appropriate), "category" and
"url" as a simple baseline. It is important to provide a value for "category" where possible, most ideally as a well known
URL from Wikipedia or Wikidata. In the case of the 2019-2020 Coronavirus pandemic, this should be "https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=2019-20\_coronavirus\_pandemic" or "https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q81068910".

For many of the possible properties, values can either be simple links or an inline description, depending on whether a summary is available. For a link, provide just the URL of the appropriate page as the property's value. For an inline description, use a [[WebContent]] type, and provide the url as a property of that, alongside at least a simple "[[text]]" summary of the page. It is
unlikely that a single SpecialAnnouncement will need all of the possible properties simultaneously.

We expect that in many cases the page referenced might contain more specialized structured data, e.g. contact info, [[openingHours]], [[Event]], [[FAQPage]] etc. By linking to those pages from a [[SpecialAnnouncement]] you can help make it clearer that the events are related to the situation (e.g. Coronavirus) indicated by the [[category]] property of the [[SpecialAnnouncement]].

Many [[SpecialAnnouncement]]s will relate to particular regions and to identifiable local organizations. Use [[spatialCoverage]] for the region, and [[announcementLocation]] to indicate specific [[LocalBusiness]]es and [[CivicStructure]]s. If the announcement affects both a particular region and a specific location (for example, a library closure that serves an entire region), use both [[spatialCoverage]] and [[announcementLocation]].

The [[about]] property can be used to indicate entities that are the focus of the announcement. We now recommend using [[about]] only
for representing non-location entities (e.g. a [[Course]] or a [[RadioStation]]). For places, use [[announcementLocation]] and [[spatialCoverage]]. Consumers of this markup should be aware that the initial design encouraged the use of /about for locations too.

The basic content of [[SpecialAnnouncement]] is similar to that of an [RSS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RSS) or [Atom](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atom_(Web_standard)) feed. For publishers without such feeds, basic feed-like information can be shared by posting
[[SpecialAnnouncement]] updates in a page, e.g. using JSON-LD. For sites with Atom/RSS functionality, you can point to a feed
with the [[webFeed]] property. This can be a simple URL, or an inline [[DataFeed]] object, with [[encodingFormat]] providing
media type information e.g. "application/rss+xml" or "application/atom+xml".

inputs.name: announcementLocation
inputs.help: Indicates a specific [[CivicStructure]] or [[LocalBusiness]] associated with the SpecialAnnouncement. For example, a specific testing facility or business with special opening hours. For a larger geographic region like a quarantine of an entire region, use [[spatialCoverage]].

inputs.name: category
inputs.help: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

inputs.name: datePosted
inputs.help: Publication date of an online listing.

inputs.name: diseasePreventionInfo
inputs.help: Information about disease prevention.

inputs.name: diseaseSpreadStatistics
inputs.help:
Statistical information about the spread of a disease, either as [[WebContent]], or
  described directly as a [[Dataset]], or the specific [[Observation]]s in the dataset. When a [[WebContent]] URL is
  provided, the page indicated might also contain more such markup.

inputs.name: gettingTestedInfo
inputs.help: Information about getting tested (for a [[MedicalCondition]]), e.g. in the context of a pandemic.

inputs.name: governmentBenefitsInfo
inputs.help: governmentBenefitsInfo provides information about government benefits associated with a SpecialAnnouncement.

inputs.name: newsUpdatesAndGuidelines
inputs.help: Indicates a page with news updates and guidelines. This could often be (but is not required to be) the main page containing [[SpecialAnnouncement]] markup on a site.

inputs.name: publicTransportClosuresInfo
inputs.help: Information about public transport closures.

inputs.name: quarantineGuidelines
inputs.help: Guidelines about quarantine rules, e.g. in the context of a pandemic.

inputs.name: schoolClosuresInfo
inputs.help: Information about school closures.

inputs.name: travelBans
inputs.help: Information about travel bans, e.g. in the context of a pandemic.

inputs.name: webFeed
inputs.help: The URL for a feed, e.g. associated with a podcast series, blog, or series of date-stamped updates. This is usually RSS or Atom.

ReturnAction.name: ReturnAction
ReturnAction.help: The act of returning to the origin that which was previously received (concrete objects) or taken (ownership).

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

Atlas.name: Atlas
Atlas.help: A collection or bound volume of maps, charts, plates or tables, physical or in media form illustrating any subject.

MerchantReturnEnumeration.name: MerchantReturnEnumeration
MerchantReturnEnumeration.help: Enumerates several kinds of product return policies.

Drawing.name: Drawing
Drawing.help: A picture or diagram made with a pencil, pen, or crayon rather than paint.

ChemicalSubstance.name: ChemicalSubstance
ChemicalSubstance.help: A chemical substance is 'a portion of matter of constant composition, composed of molecular entities of the same type or of different types' (source: [ChEBI:59999](https://www.ebi.ac.uk/chebi/searchId.do?chebiId=59999)).

inputs.name: chemicalComposition
inputs.help: The chemical composition describes the identity and relative ratio of the chemical elements that make up the substance.

inputs.name: chemicalRole
inputs.help: A role played by the BioChemEntity within a chemical context.

inputs.name: potentialUse
inputs.help: Intended use of the BioChemEntity by humans.

ProductGroup.name: ProductGroup
ProductGroup.help:
A ProductGroup represents a group of [[Product]]s that vary only in certain well-described ways, such as by [[size]], [[color]], [[material]] etc.

While a ProductGroup itself is not directly offered for sale, the various varying products that it represents can be. The ProductGroup serves as a prototype or template, standing in for all of the products who have an [[isVariantOf]] relationship to it. As such, properties (including additional types) can be applied to the ProductGroup to represent characteristics shared by each of the (possibly very many) variants. Properties that reference a ProductGroup are not included in this mechanism; neither are the following specific properties [[variesBy]], [[hasVariant]], [[url]].

inputs.name: hasVariant
inputs.help: Indicates a [[Product]] that is a member of this [[ProductGroup]] (or [[ProductModel]]).

inputs.name: productGroupID
inputs.help: Indicates a textual identifier for a ProductGroup.

inputs.name: variesBy
inputs.help: Indicates the property or properties by which the variants in a [[ProductGroup]] vary, e.g. their size, color etc. Schema.org properties can be referenced by their short name e.g. "color"; terms defined elsewhere can be referenced with their URIs.

ShippingDeliveryTime.name: ShippingDeliveryTime
ShippingDeliveryTime.help: ShippingDeliveryTime provides various pieces of information about delivery times for shipping.

inputs.name: businessDays
inputs.help: Days of the week when the merchant typically operates, indicated via opening hours markup.

inputs.name: cutoffTime
inputs.help: Order cutoff time allows merchants to describe the time after which they will no longer process orders received on that day. For orders processed after cutoff time, one day gets added to the delivery time estimate. This property is expected to be most typically used via the [[ShippingRateSettings]] publication pattern. The time is indicated using the ISO-8601 Time format, e.g. "23:30:00-05:00" would represent 6:30 pm Eastern Standard Time (EST) which is 5 hours behind Coordinated Universal Time (UTC).

inputs.name: handlingTime
inputs.help: The typical delay between the receipt of the order and the goods either leaving the warehouse or being prepared for pickup, in case the delivery method is on site pickup. Typical properties: minValue, maxValue, unitCode (d for DAY).  This is by common convention assumed to mean business days (if a unitCode is used, coded as "d"), i.e. only counting days when the business normally operates.

inputs.name: transitTime
inputs.help: The typical delay the order has been sent for delivery and the goods reach the final customer. Typical properties: minValue, maxValue, unitCode (d for DAY).

Table.name: Table
Table.help: A table on a Web page.

DrugPrescriptionStatus.name: DrugPrescriptionStatus
DrugPrescriptionStatus.help: Indicates whether this drug is available by prescription or over-the-counter.

CarUsageType.name: CarUsageType
CarUsageType.help: A value indicating a special usage of a car, e.g. commercial rental, driving school, or as a taxi.

BorrowAction.name: BorrowAction
BorrowAction.help:
The act of obtaining an object under an agreement to return it at a later date. Reciprocal of LendAction.

Related actions:

* [[LendAction]]: Reciprocal of BorrowAction.

inputs.name: lender
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The person that lends the object being borrowed.

ReviewNewsArticle.name: ReviewNewsArticle
ReviewNewsArticle.help: A [[NewsArticle]] and [[CriticReview]] providing a professional critic's assessment of a service, product, performance, or artistic or literary work.

HotelRoom.name: HotelRoom
HotelRoom.help:
A hotel room is a single room in a hotel.

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

inputs.name: bed
inputs.help:
The type of bed or beds included in the accommodation. For the single case of just one bed of a certain type, you use bed directly with a text.
      If you want to indicate the quantity of a certain kind of bed, use an instance of BedDetails. For more detailed information, use the amenityFeature property.

inputs.name: occupancy
inputs.help:
The allowed total occupancy for the accommodation in persons (including infants etc). For individual accommodations, this is not necessarily the legal maximum but defines the permitted usage as per the contractual agreement (e.g. a double room used by a single person).
Typical unit code(s): C62 for person

ArchiveOrganization.name: ArchiveOrganization
ArchiveOrganization.help: An organization with archival holdings. An organization which keeps and preserves archival material and typically makes it accessible to the public.

inputs.name: archiveHeld
inputs.help: Collection, [fonds](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fonds), or item held, kept or maintained by an [[ArchiveOrganization]].

Claim.name: Claim
Claim.help:
A [[Claim]] in Schema.org represents a specific, factually-oriented claim that could be the [[itemReviewed]] in a [[ClaimReview]]. The content of a claim can be summarized with the [[text]] property. Variations on well known claims can have their common identity indicated via [[sameAs]] links, and summarized with a [[name]]. Ideally, a [[Claim]] description includes enough contextual information to minimize the risk of ambiguity or inclarity. In practice, many claims are better understood in the context in which they appear or the interpretations provided by claim reviews.

  Beyond [[ClaimReview]], the Claim type can be associated with related creative works - for example a [[ScholarlyArticle]] or [[Question]] might be [[about]] some [[Claim]].

  At this time, Schema.org does not define any types of relationship between claims. This is a natural area for future exploration.

inputs.name: appearance
inputs.help: Indicates an occurence of a [[Claim]] in some [[CreativeWork]].

inputs.name: claimInterpreter
inputs.help:
For a [[Claim]] interpreted from [[MediaObject]] content
    sed to indicate a claim contained, implied or refined from the content of a [[MediaObject]].

inputs.name: firstAppearance
inputs.help: Indicates the first known occurence of a [[Claim]] in some [[CreativeWork]].

ProgramMembership.name: ProgramMembership
ProgramMembership.help: Used to describe membership in a loyalty programs (e.g. "StarAliance"), traveler clubs (e.g. "AAA"), purchase clubs ("Safeway Club"), etc.

inputs.name: hostingOrganization
inputs.help: The organization (airline, travelers' club, etc.) the membership is made with.

inputs.name: member
inputs.help: A member of an Organization or a ProgramMembership. Organizations can be members of organizations; ProgramMembership is typically for individuals.

inputs.name: members
inputs.help: A member of this organization.

inputs.name: membershipNumber
inputs.help: A unique identifier for the membership.

inputs.name: membershipPointsEarned
inputs.help: The number of membership points earned by the member. If necessary, the unitText can be used to express the units the points are issued in. (e.g. stars, miles, etc.)

inputs.name: programName
inputs.help: The program providing the membership.

PhysicalActivity.name: PhysicalActivity
PhysicalActivity.help: Any bodily activity that enhances or maintains physical fitness and overall health and wellness. Includes activity that is part of daily living and routine, structured exercise, and exercise prescribed as part of a medical treatment or recovery plan.

inputs.name: associatedAnatomy
inputs.help: The anatomy of the underlying organ system or structures associated with this entity.

inputs.name: category
inputs.help: A category for the item. Greater signs or slashes can be used to informally indicate a category hierarchy.

inputs.name: epidemiology
inputs.help: The characteristics of associated patients, such as age, gender, race etc.

inputs.name: pathophysiology
inputs.help: Changes in the normal mechanical, physical, and biochemical functions that are associated with this activity or condition.

ContactPoint.name: ContactPoint
ContactPoint.help: A contact point—for example, a Customer Complaints department.

inputs.name: areaServed
inputs.help: The geographic area where a service or offered item is provided.

inputs.name: availableLanguage
inputs.help: A language someone may use with or at the item, service or place. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[inLanguage]]

inputs.name: contactOption
inputs.help: An option available on this contact point (e.g. a toll-free number or support for hearing-impaired callers).

inputs.name: contactType
inputs.help: A person or organization can have different contact points, for different purposes. For example, a sales contact point, a PR contact point and so on. This property is used to specify the kind of contact point.

inputs.name: email
inputs.help: Email address.

inputs.name: faxNumber
inputs.help: The fax number.

inputs.name: hoursAvailable
inputs.help: The hours during which this service or contact is available.

inputs.name: productSupported
inputs.help: The product or service this support contact point is related to (such as product support for a particular product line). This can be a specific product or product line (e.g. "iPhone") or a general category of products or services (e.g. "smartphones").

inputs.name: serviceArea
inputs.help: The geographic area where the service is provided.

inputs.name: telephone
inputs.help: The telephone number.

Barcode.name: Barcode
Barcode.help: An image of a visual machine-readable code such as a barcode or QR code.

BroadcastService.name: BroadcastService
BroadcastService.help: A delivery service through which content is provided via broadcast over the air or online.

inputs.name: area
inputs.help: The area within which users can expect to reach the broadcast service.

inputs.name: broadcastAffiliateOf
inputs.help: The media network(s) whose content is broadcast on this station.

inputs.name: broadcastDisplayName
inputs.help: The name displayed in the channel guide. For many US affiliates, it is the network name.

inputs.name: broadcastFrequency
inputs.help: The frequency used for over-the-air broadcasts. Numeric values or simple ranges e.g. 87-99. In addition a shortcut idiom is supported for frequences of AM and FM radio channels, e.g. "87 FM".

inputs.name: broadcastTimezone
inputs.help: The timezone in [ISO 8601 format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601) for which the service bases its broadcasts

inputs.name: broadcaster
inputs.help: The organization owning or operating the broadcast service.

inputs.name: callSign
inputs.help: A [callsign](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Call_sign), as used in broadcasting and radio communications to identify people, radio and TV stations, or vehicles.

inputs.name: hasBroadcastChannel
inputs.help: A broadcast channel of a broadcast service.

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: parentService
inputs.help: A broadcast service to which the broadcast service may belong to such as regional variations of a national channel.

inputs.name: videoFormat
inputs.help: The type of screening or video broadcast used (e.g. IMAX, 3D, SD, HD, etc.).

DatedMoneySpecification.name: DatedMoneySpecification
DatedMoneySpecification.help: A DatedMoneySpecification represents monetary values with optional start and end dates. For example, this could represent an employee's salary over a specific period of time. __Note:__ This type has been superseded by [[MonetaryAmount]] use of that type is recommended

inputs.name: amount
inputs.help: The amount of money.

inputs.name: currency
inputs.help: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

OnDemandEvent.name: OnDemandEvent
OnDemandEvent.help: A publication event e.g. catch-up TV or radio podcast, during which a program is available on-demand.

OrderItem.name: OrderItem
OrderItem.help: An order item is a line of an order. It includes the quantity and shipping details of a bought offer.

inputs.name: orderDelivery
inputs.help: The delivery of the parcel related to this order or order item.

inputs.name: orderItemNumber
inputs.help: The identifier of the order item.

inputs.name: orderItemStatus
inputs.help: The current status of the order item.

inputs.name: orderQuantity
inputs.help: The number of the item ordered. If the property is not set, assume the quantity is one.

inputs.name: orderedItem
inputs.help: The item ordered.

HowToSupply.name: HowToSupply
HowToSupply.help: A supply consumed when performing the instructions for how to achieve a result.

inputs.name: estimatedCost
inputs.help: The estimated cost of the supply or supplies consumed when performing instructions.

PsychologicalTreatment.name: PsychologicalTreatment
PsychologicalTreatment.help: A process of care relying upon counseling, dialogue and communication  aimed at improving a mental health condition without use of drugs.

GiveAction.name: GiveAction
GiveAction.help:
The act of transferring ownership of an object to a destination. Reciprocal of TakeAction.

Related actions:

* [[TakeAction]]: Reciprocal of GiveAction.
* [[SendAction]]: Unlike SendAction, GiveAction implies that ownership is being transferred (e.g. I may send my laptop to you, but that doesn't mean I'm giving it to you).

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

ResearchOrganization.name: ResearchOrganization
ResearchOrganization.help: A Research Organization (e.g. scientific institute, research company).

EndorsementRating.name: EndorsementRating
EndorsementRating.help:
An EndorsementRating is a rating that expresses some level of endorsement, for example inclusion in a "critic's pick" blog, a
"Like" or "+1" on a social network. It can be considered the [[result]] of an [[EndorseAction]] in which the [[object]] of the action is rated positively by
some [[agent]]. As is common elsewhere in schema.org, it is sometimes more useful to describe the results of such an action without explicitly describing the [[Action]].

An [[EndorsementRating]] may be part of a numeric scale or organized system, but this is not required: having an explicit type for indicating a positive,
endorsement rating is particularly useful in the absence of numeric scales as it helps consumers understand that the rating is broadly positive.

RiverBodyOfWater.name: RiverBodyOfWater
RiverBodyOfWater.help: A river (for example, the broad majestic Shannon).

BookFormatType.name: BookFormatType
BookFormatType.help: The publication format of the book.

TextDigitalDocument.name: TextDigitalDocument
TextDigitalDocument.help: A file composed primarily of text.

DislikeAction.name: DislikeAction
DislikeAction.help: The act of expressing a negative sentiment about the object. An agent dislikes an object (a proposition, topic or theme) with participants.

VoteAction.name: VoteAction
VoteAction.help: The act of expressing a preference from a fixed/finite/structured set of choices/options.

inputs.name: candidate
inputs.help: A sub property of object. The candidate subject of this action.

PawnShop.name: PawnShop
PawnShop.help: A shop that will buy, or lend money against the security of, personal possessions.

OrganizeAction.name: OrganizeAction
OrganizeAction.help: The act of manipulating/administering/supervising/controlling one or more objects.

LegislationObject.name: LegislationObject
LegislationObject.help: A specific object or file containing a Legislation. Note that the same Legislation can be published in multiple files. For example, a digitally signed PDF, a plain PDF and an HTML version.

inputs.name: legislationLegalValue
inputs.help: The legal value of this legislation file. The same legislation can be written in multiple files with different legal values. Typically a digitally signed PDF have a "stronger" legal value than the HTML file of the same act.

OfferItemCondition.name: OfferItemCondition
OfferItemCondition.help: A list of possible conditions for the item.

RealEstateListing.name: RealEstateListing
RealEstateListing.help:
A [[RealEstateListing]] is a listing that describes one or more real-estate [[Offer]]s (whose [[businessFunction]] is typically to lease out, or to sell).
  The [[RealEstateListing]] type itself represents the overall listing, as manifested in some [[WebPage]].

inputs.name: datePosted
inputs.help: Publication date of an online listing.

inputs.name: leaseLength
inputs.help: Length of the lease for some [[Accommodation]], either particular to some [[Offer]] or in some cases intrinsic to the property.

HowToItem.name: HowToItem
HowToItem.help: An item used as either a tool or supply when performing the instructions for how to to achieve a result.

inputs.name: requiredQuantity
inputs.help: The required quantity of the item(s).

MedicalOrganization.name: MedicalOrganization
MedicalOrganization.help: A medical organization (physical or not), such as hospital, institution or clinic.

inputs.name: healthPlanNetworkId
inputs.help: Name or unique ID of network. (Networks are often reused across different insurance plans).

inputs.name: isAcceptingNewPatients
inputs.help: Whether the provider is accepting new patients.

inputs.name: medicalSpecialty
inputs.help: A medical specialty of the provider.

MedicalTherapy.name: MedicalTherapy
MedicalTherapy.help: Any medical intervention designed to prevent, treat, and cure human diseases and medical conditions, including both curative and palliative therapies. Medical therapies are typically processes of care relying upon pharmacotherapy, behavioral therapy, supportive therapy (with fluid or nutrition for example), or detoxification (e.g. hemodialysis) aimed at improving or preventing a health condition.

inputs.name: contraindication
inputs.help: A contraindication for this therapy.

inputs.name: duplicateTherapy
inputs.help: A therapy that duplicates or overlaps this one.

inputs.name: seriousAdverseOutcome
inputs.help: A possible serious complication and/or serious side effect of this therapy. Serious adverse outcomes include those that are life-threatening; result in death, disability, or permanent damage; require hospitalization or prolong existing hospitalization; cause congenital anomalies or birth defects; or jeopardize the patient and may require medical or surgical intervention to prevent one of the outcomes in this definition.

inputs.name: educationalRole
inputs.help: An educationalRole of an EducationalAudience.

PriceComponentTypeEnumeration.name: PriceComponentTypeEnumeration
PriceComponentTypeEnumeration.help: Enumerates different price components that together make up the total price for an offered product.

SizeSpecification.name: SizeSpecification
SizeSpecification.help: Size related properties of a product, typically a size code ([[name]]) and optionally a [[sizeSystem]], [[sizeGroup]], and product measurements ([[hasMeasurement]]). In addition, the intended audience can be defined through [[suggestedAge]], [[suggestedGender]], and suggested body measurements ([[suggestedMeasurement]]).

inputs.name: hasMeasurement
inputs.help: A product measurement, for example the inseam of pants, the wheel size of a bicycle, or the gauge of a screw. Usually an exact measurement, but can also be a range of measurements for adjustable products, for example belts and ski bindings.

inputs.name: sizeGroup
inputs.help: The size group (also known as "size type") for a product's size. Size groups are common in the fashion industry to define size segments and suggested audiences for wearable products. Multiple values can be combined, for example "men's big and tall", "petite maternity" or "regular"

inputs.name: sizeSystem
inputs.help: The size system used to identify a product's size. Typically either a standard (for example, "GS1" or "ISO-EN13402"), country code (for example "US" or "JP"), or a measuring system (for example "Metric" or "Imperial").

inputs.name: suggestedAge
inputs.help: The age or age range for the intended audience or person, for example 3-12 months for infants, 1-5 years for toddlers.

inputs.name: suggestedGender
inputs.help: The suggested gender of the intended person or audience, for example "male", "female", or "unisex".

inputs.name: suggestedMeasurement
inputs.help: A suggested range of body measurements for the intended audience or person, for example inseam between 32 and 34 inches or height between 170 and 190 cm. Typically found on a size chart for wearable products.

Chapter.name: Chapter
Chapter.help: One of the sections into which a book is divided. A chapter usually has a section number or a name.

inputs.name: pageEnd
inputs.help: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

inputs.name: pageStart
inputs.help: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

inputs.name: pagination
inputs.help: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

VideoObjectSnapshot.name: VideoObjectSnapshot
VideoObjectSnapshot.help: A specific and exact (byte-for-byte) version of a [[VideoObject]]. Two byte-for-byte identical files, for the purposes of this type, considered identical. If they have different embedded metadata the files will differ. Different external facts about the files, e.g. creator or dateCreated that aren't represented in their actual content, do not affect this notion of identity.

VirtualLocation.name: VirtualLocation
VirtualLocation.help: An online or virtual location for attending events. For example, one may attend an online seminar or educational event. While a virtual location may be used as the location of an event, virtual locations should not be confused with physical locations in the real world.

UserCheckins.name: UserCheckins
UserCheckins.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

PeopleAudience.name: PeopleAudience
PeopleAudience.help: A set of characteristics belonging to people, e.g. who compose an item's target audience.

inputs.name: healthCondition
inputs.help: Specifying the health condition(s) of a patient, medical study, or other target audience.

inputs.name: requiredGender
inputs.help: Audiences defined by a person's gender.

inputs.name: requiredMaxAge
inputs.help: Audiences defined by a person's maximum age.

inputs.name: requiredMinAge
inputs.help: Audiences defined by a person's minimum age.

inputs.name: suggestedAge
inputs.help: The age or age range for the intended audience or person, for example 3-12 months for infants, 1-5 years for toddlers.

inputs.name: suggestedGender
inputs.help: The suggested gender of the intended person or audience, for example "male", "female", or "unisex".

inputs.name: suggestedMaxAge
inputs.help: Maximum recommended age in years for the audience or user.

inputs.name: suggestedMeasurement
inputs.help: A suggested range of body measurements for the intended audience or person, for example inseam between 32 and 34 inches or height between 170 and 190 cm. Typically found on a size chart for wearable products.

inputs.name: suggestedMinAge
inputs.help: Minimum recommended age in years for the audience or user.

Audience.name: Audience
Audience.help: Intended audience for an item, i.e. the group for whom the item was created.

inputs.name: audienceType
inputs.help: The target group associated with a given audience (e.g. veterans, car owners, musicians, etc.).

inputs.name: geographicArea
inputs.help: The geographic area associated with the audience.

LifestyleModification.name: LifestyleModification
LifestyleModification.help: A process of care involving exercise, changes to diet, fitness routines, and other lifestyle changes aimed at improving a health condition.

SeaBodyOfWater.name: SeaBodyOfWater
SeaBodyOfWater.help: A sea (for example, the Caspian sea).

LoanOrCredit.name: LoanOrCredit
LoanOrCredit.help: A financial product for the loaning of an amount of money, or line of credit, under agreed terms and charges.

inputs.name: amount
inputs.help: The amount of money.

inputs.name: currency
inputs.help: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: gracePeriod
inputs.help: The period of time after any due date that the borrower has to fulfil its obligations before a default (failure to pay) is deemed to have occurred.

inputs.name: loanRepaymentForm
inputs.help: A form of paying back money previously borrowed from a lender. Repayment usually takes the form of periodic payments that normally include part principal plus interest in each payment.

inputs.name: loanTerm
inputs.help: The duration of the loan or credit agreement.

inputs.name: loanType
inputs.help: The type of a loan or credit.

inputs.name: recourseLoan
inputs.help: The only way you get the money back in the event of default is the security. Recourse is where you still have the opportunity to go back to the borrower for the rest of the money.

inputs.name: renegotiableLoan
inputs.help: Whether the terms for payment of interest can be renegotiated during the life of the loan.

inputs.name: requiredCollateral
inputs.help: Assets required to secure loan or credit repayments. It may take form of third party pledge, goods, financial instruments (cash, securities, etc.)

HealthInsurancePlan.name: HealthInsurancePlan
HealthInsurancePlan.help: A US-style health insurance plan, including PPOs, EPOs, and HMOs.

inputs.name: benefitsSummaryUrl
inputs.help: The URL that goes directly to the summary of benefits and coverage for the specific standard plan or plan variation.

inputs.name: contactPoint
inputs.help: A contact point for a person or organization.

inputs.name: healthPlanDrugOption
inputs.help: TODO.

inputs.name: healthPlanDrugTier
inputs.help: The tier(s) of drugs offered by this formulary or insurance plan.

inputs.name: healthPlanId
inputs.help: The 14-character, HIOS-generated Plan ID number. (Plan IDs must be unique, even across different markets.)

inputs.name: healthPlanMarketingUrl
inputs.help: The URL that goes directly to the plan brochure for the specific standard plan or plan variation.

inputs.name: includesHealthPlanFormulary
inputs.help: Formularies covered by this plan.

inputs.name: includesHealthPlanNetwork
inputs.help: Networks covered by this plan.

inputs.name: usesHealthPlanIdStandard
inputs.help: The standard for interpreting thePlan ID. The preferred is "HIOS". See the Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services for more details.

USNonprofitType.name: USNonprofitType
USNonprofitType.help: USNonprofitType: Non-profit organization type originating from the United States.

House.name: House
House.help: A house is a building or structure that has the ability to be occupied for habitation by humans or other creatures (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/House).

inputs.name: numberOfRooms
inputs.help:
The number of rooms (excluding bathrooms and closets) of the accommodation or lodging business.
Typical unit code(s): ROM for room or C62 for no unit. The type of room can be put in the unitText property of the QuantitativeValue.

CollegeOrUniversity.name: CollegeOrUniversity
CollegeOrUniversity.help: A college, university, or other third-level educational institution.

ResumeAction.name: ResumeAction
ResumeAction.help: The act of resuming a device or application which was formerly paused (e.g. resume music playback or resume a timer).

CheckAction.name: CheckAction
CheckAction.help: An agent inspects, determines, investigates, inquires, or examines an object's accuracy, quality, condition, or state.

Article.name: Article
Article.help: An article, such as a news article or piece of investigative report. Newspapers and magazines have articles of many different types and this is intended to cover them all.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

inputs.name: articleBody
inputs.help: The actual body of the article.

inputs.name: articleSection
inputs.help: Articles may belong to one or more 'sections' in a magazine or newspaper, such as Sports, Lifestyle, etc.

inputs.name: backstory
inputs.help: For an [[Article]], typically a [[NewsArticle]], the backstory property provides a textual summary giving a brief explanation of why and how an article was created. In a journalistic setting this could include information about reporting process, methods, interviews, data sources, etc.

inputs.name: pageEnd
inputs.help: The page on which the work ends; for example "138" or "xvi".

inputs.name: pageStart
inputs.help: The page on which the work starts; for example "135" or "xiii".

inputs.name: pagination
inputs.help: Any description of pages that is not separated into pageStart and pageEnd; for example, "1-6, 9, 55" or "10-12, 46-49".

inputs.name: speakable
inputs.help:
Indicates sections of a Web page that are particularly 'speakable' in the sense of being highlighted as being especially appropriate for text-to-speech conversion. Other sections of a page may also be usefully spoken in particular circumstances; the 'speakable' property serves to indicate the parts most likely to be generally useful for speech.

The *speakable* property can be repeated an arbitrary number of times, with three kinds of possible 'content-locator' values:

1.) *id-value* URL references - uses *id-value* of an element in the page being annotated. The simplest use of *speakable* has (potentially relative) URL values, referencing identified sections of the document concerned.

2.) CSS Selectors - addresses content in the annotated page, eg. via class attribute. Use the [[cssSelector]] property.

3.)  XPaths - addresses content via XPaths (assuming an XML view of the content). Use the [[xpath]] property.


For more sophisticated markup of speakable sections beyond simple ID references, either CSS selectors or XPath expressions to pick out document section(s) as speakable. For this
we define a supporting type, [[SpeakableSpecification]]  which is defined to be a possible value of the *speakable* property.

inputs.name: wordCount
inputs.help: The number of words in the text of the Article.

StatisticalPopulation.name: StatisticalPopulation
StatisticalPopulation.help:
A StatisticalPopulation is a set of instances of a certain given type that satisfy some set of constraints. The property [[populationType]] is used to specify the type. Any property that can be used on instances of that type can appear on the statistical population. For example, a [[StatisticalPopulation]] representing all [[Person]]s with a [[homeLocation]] of East Podunk California, would be described by applying the appropriate [[homeLocation]] and [[populationType]] properties to a [[StatisticalPopulation]] item that stands for that set of people.
The properties [[numConstraints]] and [[constrainingProperty]] are used to specify which of the populations properties are used to specify the population. Note that the sense of "population" used here is the general sense of a statistical
population, and does not imply that the population consists of people. For example, a [[populationType]] of [[Event]] or [[NewsArticle]] could be used. See also [[Observation]], and the [data and datasets](/docs/data-and-datasets.html) overview for more details.

inputs.name: constrainingProperty
inputs.help:
Indicates a property used as a constraint to define a [[StatisticalPopulation]] with respect to the set of entities
  corresponding to an indicated type (via [[populationType]]).

inputs.name: numConstraints
inputs.help: Indicates the number of constraints (not counting [[populationType]]) defined for a particular [[StatisticalPopulation]]. This helps applications understand if they have access to a sufficiently complete description of a [[StatisticalPopulation]].

inputs.name: populationType
inputs.help: Indicates the populationType common to all members of a [[StatisticalPopulation]].

State.name: State
State.help: A state or province of a country.

PodcastEpisode.name: PodcastEpisode
PodcastEpisode.help: A single episode of a podcast series.

UserLikes.name: UserLikes
UserLikes.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

WPAdBlock.name: WPAdBlock
WPAdBlock.help: An advertising section of the page.

TouristDestination.name: TouristDestination
TouristDestination.help:
A tourist destination. In principle any [[Place]] can be a [[TouristDestination]] from a [[City]], Region or [[Country]] to an [[AmusementPark]] or [[Hotel]]. This Type can be used on its own to describe a general [[TouristDestination]], or be used as an [[additionalType]] to add tourist relevant properties to any other [[Place]].  A [[TouristDestination]] is defined as a [[Place]] that contains, or is colocated with, one or more [[TouristAttraction]]s, often linked by a similar theme or interest to a particular [[touristType]]. The [UNWTO](http://www2.unwto.org/) defines Destination (main destination of a tourism trip) as the place visited that is central to the decision to take the trip.
  (See examples below).

inputs.name: includesAttraction
inputs.help: Attraction located at destination.

inputs.name: touristType
inputs.help: Attraction suitable for type(s) of tourist. eg. Children, visitors from a particular country, etc.

MedicalTrialDesign.name: MedicalTrialDesign
MedicalTrialDesign.help: Design models for medical trials. Enumerated type.

CampingPitch.name: CampingPitch
CampingPitch.help:
A [[CampingPitch]] is an individual place for overnight stay in the outdoors, typically being part of a larger camping site, or [[Campground]].\n\n
In British English a campsite, or campground, is an area, usually divided into a number of pitches, where people can camp overnight using tents or camper vans or caravans; this British English use of the word is synonymous with the American English expression campground. In American English the term campsite generally means an area where an individual, family, group, or military unit can pitch a tent or park a camper; a campground may contain many campsites.
(Source: Wikipedia see [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campsite)).\n\n
See also the dedicated [document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations](/docs/hotels.html).

Place.name: Place
Place.help: Entities that have a somewhat fixed, physical extension.

inputs.name: additionalProperty
inputs.help: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

inputs.name: address
inputs.help: Physical address of the item.

inputs.name: aggregateRating
inputs.help: The overall rating, based on a collection of reviews or ratings, of the item.

inputs.name: amenityFeature
inputs.help: An amenity feature (e.g. a characteristic or service) of the Accommodation. This generic property does not make a statement about whether the feature is included in an offer for the main accommodation or available at extra costs.

inputs.name: branchCode
inputs.help: A short textual code (also called "store code") that uniquely identifies a place of business. The code is typically assigned by the parentOrganization and used in structured URLs.\n\nFor example, in the URL http://www.starbucks.co.uk/store-locator/etc/detail/3047 the code "3047" is a branchCode for a particular branch.

inputs.name: containedIn
inputs.help: The basic containment relation between a place and one that contains it.

inputs.name: containedInPlace
inputs.help: The basic containment relation between a place and one that contains it.

inputs.name: containsPlace
inputs.help: The basic containment relation between a place and another that it contains.

inputs.name: event
inputs.help: Upcoming or past event associated with this place, organization, or action.

inputs.name: events
inputs.help: Upcoming or past events associated with this place or organization.

inputs.name: faxNumber
inputs.help: The fax number.

inputs.name: geo
inputs.help: The geo coordinates of the place.

inputs.name: geoContains
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a containing geometry to a contained geometry. "a contains b iff no points of b lie in the exterior of a, and at least one point of the interior of b lies in the interior of a". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoCoveredBy
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that covers it. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoCovers
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a covering geometry to a covered geometry. "Every point of b is a point of (the interior or boundary of) a". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoCrosses
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that crosses it: "a crosses b: they have some but not all interior points in common, and the dimension of the intersection is less than that of at least one of them". As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoDisjoint
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically disjoint: they have no point in common. They form a set of disconnected geometries." (a symmetric relationship, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM))

inputs.name: geoEquals
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) are topologically equal, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM). "Two geometries are topologically equal if their interiors intersect and no part of the interior or boundary of one geometry intersects the exterior of the other" (a symmetric relationship)

inputs.name: geoIntersects
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) have at least one point in common. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoOverlaps
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to another that geospatially overlaps it, i.e. they have some but not all points in common. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: geoTouches
inputs.help: Represents spatial relations in which two geometries (or the places they represent) touch: they have at least one boundary point in common, but no interior points." (a symmetric relationship, as defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM) )

inputs.name: geoWithin
inputs.help: Represents a relationship between two geometries (or the places they represent), relating a geometry to one that contains it, i.e. it is inside (i.e. within) its interior. As defined in [DE-9IM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DE-9IM).

inputs.name: globalLocationNumber
inputs.help: The [Global Location Number](http://www.gs1.org/gln) (GLN, sometimes also referred to as International Location Number or ILN) of the respective organization, person, or place. The GLN is a 13-digit number used to identify parties and physical locations.

inputs.name: hasDriveThroughService
inputs.help: Indicates whether some facility (e.g. [[FoodEstablishment]], [[CovidTestingFacility]]) offers a service that can be used by driving through in a car. In the case of [[CovidTestingFacility]] such facilities could potentially help with social distancing from other potentially-infected users.

inputs.name: hasMap
inputs.help: A URL to a map of the place.

inputs.name: isAccessibleForFree
inputs.help: A flag to signal that the item, event, or place is accessible for free.

inputs.name: isicV4
inputs.help: The International Standard of Industrial Classification of All Economic Activities (ISIC), Revision 4 code for a particular organization, business person, or place.

inputs.name: latitude
inputs.help: The latitude of a location. For example ```37.42242``` ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).

inputs.name: logo
inputs.help: An associated logo.

inputs.name: longitude
inputs.help: The longitude of a location. For example ```-122.08585``` ([WGS 84](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Geodetic_System)).

inputs.name: map
inputs.help: A URL to a map of the place.

inputs.name: maps
inputs.help: A URL to a map of the place.

inputs.name: maximumAttendeeCapacity
inputs.help: The total number of individuals that may attend an event or venue.

inputs.name: openingHoursSpecification
inputs.help: The opening hours of a certain place.

inputs.name: photo
inputs.help: A photograph of this place.

inputs.name: photos
inputs.help: Photographs of this place.

inputs.name: publicAccess
inputs.help: A flag to signal that the [[Place]] is open to public visitors.  If this property is omitted there is no assumed default boolean value

inputs.name: review
inputs.help: A review of the item.

inputs.name: reviews
inputs.help: Review of the item.

inputs.name: slogan
inputs.help: A slogan or motto associated with the item.

inputs.name: smokingAllowed
inputs.help: Indicates whether it is allowed to smoke in the place, e.g. in the restaurant, hotel or hotel room.

inputs.name: specialOpeningHoursSpecification
inputs.help: The special opening hours of a certain place.\n\nUse this to explicitly override general opening hours brought in scope by [[openingHoursSpecification]] or [[openingHours]].

inputs.name: telephone
inputs.help: The telephone number.

inputs.name: tourBookingPage
inputs.help: A page providing information on how to book a tour of some [[Place]], such as an [[Accommodation]] or [[ApartmentComplex]] in a real estate setting, as well as other kinds of tours as appropriate.

TieAction.name: TieAction
TieAction.help: The act of reaching a draw in a competitive activity.

MedicalRiskScore.name: MedicalRiskScore
MedicalRiskScore.help: A simple system that adds up the number of risk factors to yield a score that is associated with prognosis, e.g. CHAD score, TIMI risk score.

inputs.name: algorithm
inputs.help: The algorithm or rules to follow to compute the score.

PreOrderAction.name: PreOrderAction
PreOrderAction.help: An agent orders a (not yet released) object/product/service to be delivered/sent.

NoteDigitalDocument.name: NoteDigitalDocument
NoteDigitalDocument.help: A file containing a note, primarily for the author.

WarrantyScope.name: WarrantyScope
WarrantyScope.help:
A range of of services that will be provided to a customer free of charge in case of a defect or malfunction of a product.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Labor-BringIn
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PartsAndLabor-BringIn
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#PartsAndLabor-PickUp

BoardingPolicyType.name: BoardingPolicyType
BoardingPolicyType.help: A type of boarding policy used by an airline.

PodcastSeries.name: PodcastSeries
PodcastSeries.help: A podcast is an episodic series of digital audio or video files which a user can download and listen to.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: webFeed
inputs.help: The URL for a feed, e.g. associated with a podcast series, blog, or series of date-stamped updates. This is usually RSS or Atom.

Property.name: Property
Property.help: A property, used to indicate attributes and relationships of some Thing; equivalent to rdf:Property.

inputs.name: domainIncludes
inputs.help: Relates a property to a class that is (one of) the type(s) the property is expected to be used on.

inputs.name: inverseOf
inputs.help: Relates a property to a property that is its inverse. Inverse properties relate the same pairs of items to each other, but in reversed direction. For example, the 'alumni' and 'alumniOf' properties are inverseOf each other. Some properties don't have explicit inverses; in these situations RDFa and JSON-LD syntax for reverse properties can be used.

inputs.name: rangeIncludes
inputs.help: Relates a property to a class that constitutes (one of) the expected type(s) for values of the property.

inputs.name: supersededBy
inputs.help: Relates a term (i.e. a property, class or enumeration) to one that supersedes it.

PublicToilet.name: PublicToilet
PublicToilet.help: A public toilet is a room or small building containing one or more toilets (and possibly also urinals) which is available for use by the general public, or by customers or employees of certain businesses.

MedicalAudience.name: MedicalAudience
MedicalAudience.help: Target audiences for medical web pages.

BroadcastChannel.name: BroadcastChannel
BroadcastChannel.help: A unique instance of a BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

inputs.name: broadcastChannelId
inputs.help: The unique address by which the BroadcastService can be identified in a provider lineup. In US, this is typically a number.

inputs.name: broadcastFrequency
inputs.help: The frequency used for over-the-air broadcasts. Numeric values or simple ranges e.g. 87-99. In addition a shortcut idiom is supported for frequences of AM and FM radio channels, e.g. "87 FM".

inputs.name: broadcastServiceTier
inputs.help: The type of service required to have access to the channel (e.g. Standard or Premium).

inputs.name: genre
inputs.help: Genre of the creative work, broadcast channel or group.

inputs.name: inBroadcastLineup
inputs.help: The CableOrSatelliteService offering the channel.

inputs.name: providesBroadcastService
inputs.help: The BroadcastService offered on this channel.

ReplyAction.name: ReplyAction
ReplyAction.help:
The act of responding to a question/message asked/sent by the object. Related to [[AskAction]]

Related actions:

* [[AskAction]]: Appears generally as an origin of a ReplyAction.

inputs.name: resultComment
inputs.help: A sub property of result. The Comment created or sent as a result of this action.

VisualArtwork.name: VisualArtwork
VisualArtwork.help: A work of art that is primarily visual in character.

inputs.name: artEdition
inputs.help: The number of copies when multiple copies of a piece of artwork are produced - e.g. for a limited edition of 20 prints, 'artEdition' refers to the total number of copies (in this example "20").

inputs.name: artMedium
inputs.help: The material used. (e.g. Oil, Watercolour, Acrylic, Linoprint, Marble, Cyanotype, Digital, Lithograph, DryPoint, Intaglio, Pastel, Woodcut, Pencil, Mixed Media, etc.)

inputs.name: artform
inputs.help: e.g. Painting, Drawing, Sculpture, Print, Photograph, Assemblage, Collage, etc.

inputs.name: artist
inputs.help:
The primary artist for a work
    	in a medium other than pencils or digital line art--for example, if the
    	primary artwork is done in watercolors or digital paints.

inputs.name: artworkSurface
inputs.help: The supporting materials for the artwork, e.g. Canvas, Paper, Wood, Board, etc.

inputs.name: colorist
inputs.help: The individual who adds color to inked drawings.

inputs.name: depth
inputs.help: The depth of the item.

inputs.name: height
inputs.help: The height of the item.

inputs.name: inker
inputs.help: The individual who traces over the pencil drawings in ink after pencils are complete.

inputs.name: letterer
inputs.help: The individual who adds lettering, including speech balloons and sound effects, to artwork.

inputs.name: penciler
inputs.help: The individual who draws the primary narrative artwork.

inputs.name: surface
inputs.help: A material used as a surface in some artwork, e.g. Canvas, Paper, Wood, Board, etc.

inputs.name: width
inputs.help: The width of the item.

UserPageVisits.name: UserPageVisits
UserPageVisits.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

GovernmentBenefitsType.name: GovernmentBenefitsType
GovernmentBenefitsType.help: GovernmentBenefitsType enumerates several kinds of government benefits to support the COVID-19 situation. Note that this structure may not capture all benefits offered.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: actors
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: caption
inputs.help: The caption for this object. For downloadable machine formats (closed caption, subtitles etc.) use MediaObject and indicate the [[encodingFormat]].

inputs.name: director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: directors
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video games etc. content. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: embeddedTextCaption
inputs.help: Represents textual captioning from a [[MediaObject]], e.g. text of a 'meme'.

inputs.name: musicBy
inputs.help: The composer of the soundtrack.

inputs.name: thumbnail
inputs.help: Thumbnail image for an image or video.

inputs.name: transcript
inputs.help: If this MediaObject is an AudioObject or VideoObject, the transcript of that object.

inputs.name: videoFrameSize
inputs.help: The frame size of the video.

inputs.name: videoQuality
inputs.help: The quality of the video.

ReplaceAction.name: ReplaceAction
ReplaceAction.help: The act of editing a recipient by replacing an old object with a new object.

inputs.name: replacee
inputs.help: A sub property of object. The object that is being replaced.

inputs.name: replacer
inputs.help: A sub property of object. The object that replaces.

ApplyAction.name: ApplyAction
ApplyAction.help:
The act of registering to an organization/service without the guarantee to receive it.

Related actions:

* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, ApplyAction has no guarantees that the application will be accepted.

MusicGroup.name: MusicGroup
MusicGroup.help: A musical group, such as a band, an orchestra, or a choir. Can also be a solo musician.

inputs.name: album
inputs.help: A music album.

inputs.name: albums
inputs.help: A collection of music albums.

inputs.name: genre
inputs.help: Genre of the creative work, broadcast channel or group.

inputs.name: musicGroupMember
inputs.help: A member of a music group—for example, John, Paul, George, or Ringo.

inputs.name: track
inputs.help: A music recording (track)—usually a single song. If an ItemList is given, the list should contain items of type MusicRecording.

inputs.name: tracks
inputs.help: A music recording (track)—usually a single song.

ItemPage.name: ItemPage
ItemPage.help: A page devoted to a single item, such as a particular product or hotel.

MedicalRiskCalculator.name: MedicalRiskCalculator
MedicalRiskCalculator.help: A complex mathematical calculation requiring an online calculator, used to assess prognosis. Note: use the url property of Thing to record any URLs for online calculators.

AudioObjectSnapshot.name: AudioObjectSnapshot
AudioObjectSnapshot.help: A specific and exact (byte-for-byte) version of an [[AudioObject]]. Two byte-for-byte identical files, for the purposes of this type, considered identical. If they have different embedded metadata the files will differ. Different external facts about the files, e.g. creator or dateCreated that aren't represented in their actual content, do not affect this notion of identity.

SeekToAction.name: SeekToAction
SeekToAction.help: This is the [[Action]] of navigating to a specific [[startOffset]] timestamp within a [[VideoObject]], typically represented with a URL template structure.

inputs.name: startOffset
inputs.help: The start time of the clip expressed as the number of seconds from the beginning of the work.

MedicalGuidelineRecommendation.name: MedicalGuidelineRecommendation
MedicalGuidelineRecommendation.help: A guideline recommendation that is regarded as efficacious and where quality of the data supporting the recommendation is sound.

inputs.name: recommendationStrength
inputs.help: Strength of the guideline's recommendation (e.g. 'class I').

DonateAction.name: DonateAction
DonateAction.help: The act of providing goods, services, or money without compensation, often for philanthropic reasons.

inputs.name: recipient
inputs.help: A sub property of participant. The participant who is at the receiving end of the action.

Guide.name: Guide
Guide.help: [[Guide]] is a page or article that recommend specific products or services, or aspects of a thing for a user to consider. A [[Guide]] may represent a Buying Guide and detail aspects of products or services for a user to consider. A [[Guide]] may represent a Product Guide and recommend specific products or services.
