inputs.help: Indicates the aspect or aspects specifically addressed in some [[HealthTopicContent]]. For example, that the content is an overview, or that it talks about treatment, self-care, treatments or their side-effects.

OrderAction.name: OrderAction
OrderAction.help: An agent orders an object/product/service to be delivered/sent.

inputs.name: deliveryMethod
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The method of delivery.

Class.name: Class
Class.help: A class, also often called a 'Type'; equivalent to rdfs:Class.

inputs.name: supersededBy
inputs.help: Relates a term (i.e. a property, class or enumeration) to one that supersedes it.

QualitativeValue.name: QualitativeValue
QualitativeValue.help: A predefined value for a product characteristic, e.g. the power cord plug type 'US' or the garment sizes 'S', 'M', 'L', and 'XL'.

inputs.name: additionalProperty
inputs.help: A property-value pair representing an additional characteristics of the entitity, e.g. a product feature or another characteristic for which there is no matching property in schema.org.\n\nNote: Publishers should be aware that applications designed to use specific schema.org properties (e.g. http://schema.org/width, http://schema.org/color, http://schema.org/gtin13, ...) will typically expect such data to be provided using those properties, rather than using the generic property/value mechanism.

inputs.name: equal
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is equal to the object.

inputs.name: greater
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is greater than the object.

inputs.name: greaterOrEqual
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is greater than or equal to the object.

inputs.name: lesser
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is lesser than the object.

inputs.name: lesserOrEqual
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is lesser than or equal to the object.

inputs.name: nonEqual
inputs.help: This ordering relation for qualitative values indicates that the subject is not equal to the object.

inputs.name: valueReference
inputs.help: A secondary value that provides additional information on the original value, e.g. a reference temperature or a type of measurement.

ReadAction.name: ReadAction
ReadAction.help: The act of consuming written content.

inputs.name: athlete
inputs.help: A person that acts as performing member of a sports team; a player as opposed to a coach.

inputs.name: coach
inputs.help: A person that acts in a coaching role for a sports team.

inputs.name: gender
inputs.help: Gender of something, typically a [[Person]], but possibly also fictional characters, animals, etc. While http://schema.org/Male and http://schema.org/Female may be used, text strings are also acceptable for people who do not identify as a binary gender. The [[gender]] property can also be used in an extended sense to cover e.g. the gender of sports teams. As with the gender of individuals, we do not try to enumerate all possibilities. A mixed-gender [[SportsTeam]] can be indicated with a text value of "Mixed".

SearchResultsPage.name: SearchResultsPage
SearchResultsPage.help: Web page type: Search results page.

Journal.name: Journal
Journal.help: A publication in any medium issued in successive parts bearing numerical or chronological designations and intended, such as a magazine, scholarly journal, or newspaper to continue indefinitely.\n\nSee also [blog post](http://blog.schema.org/2014/09/schemaorg-support-for-bibliographic_2.html).

inputs.name: codeValue
inputs.help: A short textual code that uniquely identifies the value.

inputs.name: inCodeSet
inputs.help: A [[CategoryCodeSet]] that contains this category code.

WriteAction.name: WriteAction
WriteAction.help: The act of authoring written creative content.

inputs.name: inLanguage
inputs.help: The language of the content or performance or used in an action. Please use one of the language codes from the [IETF BCP 47 standard](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47). See also [[availableLanguage]].

inputs.name: language
inputs.help: A sub property of instrument. The language used on this action.

PerformAction.name: PerformAction
PerformAction.help: The act of participating in performance arts.

inputs.name: entertainmentBusiness
inputs.help: A sub property of location. The entertainment business where the action occurred.

Trip.name: Trip
Trip.help: A trip or journey. An itinerary of visits to one or more places.

inputs.name: arrivalTime
inputs.help: The expected arrival time.

inputs.name: departureTime
inputs.help: The expected departure time.

inputs.name: itinerary
inputs.help: Destination(s) ( [[Place]] ) that make up a trip. For a trip where destination order is important use [[ItemList]] to specify that order (see examples).

inputs.name: offers
inputs.help: An offer to provide this item—for example, an offer to sell a product, rent the DVD of a movie, perform a service, or give away tickets to an event. Use [[businessFunction]] to indicate the kind of transaction offered, i.e. sell, lease, etc. This property can also be used to describe a [[Demand]]. While this property is listed as expected on a number of common types, it can be used in others. In that case, using a second type, such as Product or a subtype of Product, can clarify the nature of the offer.

inputs.name: partOfTrip
inputs.help: Identifies that this [[Trip]] is a subTrip of another Trip.  For example Day 1, Day 2, etc. of a multi-day trip.

inputs.name: provider
inputs.help: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

inputs.name: subTrip
inputs.help: Identifies a [[Trip]] that is a subTrip of this Trip.  For example Day 1, Day 2, etc. of a multi-day trip.

WebAPI.name: WebAPI
WebAPI.help: An application programming interface accessible over Web/Internet technologies.

inputs.name: documentation
inputs.help: Further documentation describing the Web API in more detail.

EatAction.name: EatAction
EatAction.help: The act of swallowing solid objects.

Hotel.name: Hotel
Hotel.help:
A hotel is an establishment that provides lodging paid on a short-term basis (Source: Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia, see http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hotel).

See also the dedicated document on the use of schema.org for marking up hotels and other forms of accommodations.

MoneyTransfer.name: MoneyTransfer
MoneyTransfer.help: The act of transferring money from one place to another place. This may occur electronically or physically.

inputs.name: amount
inputs.help: The amount of money.

inputs.name: beneficiaryBank
inputs.help: A bank or bank’s branch, financial institution or international financial institution operating the beneficiary’s bank account or releasing funds for the beneficiary.

Code.name: Code
Code.help: Computer programming source code. Example: Full (compile ready) solutions, code snippet samples, scripts, templates.

ImagingTest.name: ImagingTest
ImagingTest.help: Any medical imaging modality typically used for diagnostic purposes.

inputs.name: imagingTechnique
inputs.help: Imaging technique used.

inputs.name: mapType
inputs.help: Indicates the kind of Map, from the MapCategoryType Enumeration.

Play.name: Play
Play.help: A play is a form of literature, usually consisting of dialogue between characters, intended for theatrical performance rather than just reading. Note: A performance of a Play would be a [[TheaterEvent]] or [[BroadcastEvent]] - the *Play* being the [[workPerformed]].

FoodService.name: FoodService
FoodService.help: A food service, like breakfast, lunch, or dinner.

GovernmentPermit.name: GovernmentPermit
GovernmentPermit.help: A permit issued by a government agency.

OfferForPurchase.name: OfferForPurchase
OfferForPurchase.help:
An [[OfferForPurchase]] in Schema.org represents an [[Offer]] to sell something, i.e. an [[Offer]] whose
  [[businessFunction]] is [sell](http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell.). See [Good Relations](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GoodRelations) for
  background on the underlying concepts.

CriticReview.name: CriticReview
CriticReview.help: A [[CriticReview]] is a more specialized form of Review written or published by a source that is recognized for its reviewing activities. These can include online columns, travel and food guides, TV and radio shows, blogs and other independent Web sites. [[CriticReview]]s are typically more in-depth and professionally written. For simpler, casually written user/visitor/viewer/customer reviews, it is more appropriate to use the [[UserReview]] type. Review aggregator sites such as Metacritic already separate out the site's user reviews from selected critic reviews that originate from third-party sources.

Reservoir.name: Reservoir
Reservoir.help: A reservoir of water, typically an artificially created lake, like the Lake Kariba reservoir.

MeasurementTypeEnumeration.name: MeasurementTypeEnumeration
MeasurementTypeEnumeration.help: Enumeration of common measurement types (or dimensions), for example "chest" for a person, "inseam" for pants, "gauge" for screws, or "wheel" for bicycles.

MedicalImagingTechnique.name: MedicalImagingTechnique
MedicalImagingTechnique.help: Any medical imaging modality typically used for diagnostic purposes. Enumerated type.

HealthPlanFormulary.name: HealthPlanFormulary
HealthPlanFormulary.help: For a given health insurance plan, the specification for costs and coverage of prescription drugs.

inputs.name: healthPlanCostSharing
inputs.help: Whether The costs to the patient for services under this network or formulary.

inputs.name: healthPlanDrugTier
inputs.help: The tier(s) of drugs offered by this formulary or insurance plan.

inputs.name: offersPrescriptionByMail
inputs.help: Whether prescriptions can be delivered by mail.

FollowAction.name: FollowAction
FollowAction.help:
The act of forming a personal connection with someone/something (object) unidirectionally/asymmetrically to get updates polled from.

Related actions:

* [[BefriendAction]]: Unlike BefriendAction, FollowAction implies that the connection is *not* necessarily reciprocal.
* [[SubscribeAction]]: Unlike SubscribeAction, FollowAction implies that the follower acts as an active agent constantly/actively polling for updates.
* [[RegisterAction]]: Unlike RegisterAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in continuing receiving updates from the object.
* [[JoinAction]]: Unlike JoinAction, FollowAction implies that the agent is interested in getting updates from the object.
* [[TrackAction]]: Unlike TrackAction, FollowAction refers to the polling of updates of all aspects of animate objects rather than the location of inanimate objects (e.g. you track a package, but you don't follow it).

inputs.name: followee
inputs.help: A sub property of object. The person or organization being followed.

TouristTrip.name: TouristTrip
TouristTrip.help:
A tourist trip. A created itinerary of visits to one or more places of interest ([[TouristAttraction]]/[[TouristDestination]]) often linked by a similar theme, geographic area, or interest to a particular [[touristType]]. The [UNWTO](http://www2.unwto.org/) defines tourism trip as the Trip taken by visitors.
  (See examples below).

inputs.name: touristType
inputs.help: Attraction suitable for type(s) of tourist. eg. Children, visitors from a particular country, etc.

TVEpisode.name: TVEpisode
TVEpisode.help: A TV episode which can be part of a series or season.

inputs.name: countryOfOrigin
inputs.help:
The country of origin of something, including products as well as creative  works such as movie and TV content.

In the case of TV and movie, this would be the country of the principle offices of the production company or individual responsible for the movie. For other kinds of [[CreativeWork]] it is difficult to provide fully general guidance, and properties such as [[contentLocation]] and [[locationCreated]] may be more applicable.

In the case of products, the country of origin of the product. The exact interpretation of this may vary by context and product type, and cannot be fully enumerated here.

inputs.name: partOfTVSeries
inputs.help: The TV series to which this episode or season belongs.

inputs.name: subtitleLanguage
inputs.help: Languages in which subtitles/captions are available, in [IETF BCP 47 standard format](http://tools.ietf.org/html/bcp47).

inputs.name: titleEIDR
inputs.help:
An [EIDR](https://eidr.org/) (Entertainment Identifier Registry) [[identifier]] representing at the most general/abstract level, a work of film or television.

For example, the motion picture known as "Ghostbusters" has a titleEIDR of  "10.5240/7EC7-228A-510A-053E-CBB8-J". This title (or work) may have several variants, which EIDR calls "edits". See [[editEIDR]].

Since schema.org types like [[Movie]] and [[TVEpisode]] can be used for both works and their multiple expressions, it is possible to use [[titleEIDR]] alone (for a general description), or alongside [[editEIDR]] for a more edit-specific description.

inputs.name: numberOfAccommodationUnits
inputs.help: Indicates the total (available plus unavailable) number of accommodation units in an [[ApartmentComplex]], or the number of accommodation units for a specific [[FloorPlan]] (within its specific [[ApartmentComplex]]). See also [[numberOfAvailableAccommodationUnits]].

inputs.name: numberOfAvailableAccommodationUnits
inputs.help: Indicates the number of available accommodation units in an [[ApartmentComplex]], or the number of accommodation units for a specific [[FloorPlan]] (within its specific [[ApartmentComplex]]). See also [[numberOfAccommodationUnits]].

inputs.name: numberOfBedrooms
inputs.help: The total integer number of bedrooms in a some [[Accommodation]], [[ApartmentComplex]] or [[FloorPlan]].

inputs.name: petsAllowed
inputs.help: Indicates whether pets are allowed to enter the accommodation or lodging business. More detailed information can be put in a text value.

inputs.name: tourBookingPage
inputs.help: A page providing information on how to book a tour of some [[Place]], such as an [[Accommodation]] or [[ApartmentComplex]] in a real estate setting, as well as other kinds of tours as appropriate.

Vessel.name: Vessel
Vessel.help: A component of the human body circulatory system comprised of an intricate network of hollow tubes that transport blood throughout the entire body.

MaximumDoseSchedule.name: MaximumDoseSchedule
MaximumDoseSchedule.help: The maximum dosing schedule considered safe for a drug or supplement as recommended by an authority or by the drug/supplement's manufacturer. Capture the recommending authority in the recognizingAuthority property of MedicalEntity.

inputs.name: screenCount
inputs.help: The number of screens in the movie theater.

PlaceOfWorship.name: PlaceOfWorship
PlaceOfWorship.help: Place of worship, such as a church, synagogue, or mosque.

TelevisionChannel.name: TelevisionChannel
TelevisionChannel.help: A unique instance of a television BroadcastService on a CableOrSatelliteService lineup.

EntryPoint.name: EntryPoint
EntryPoint.help: An entry point, within some Web-based protocol.

inputs.name: actionApplication
inputs.help: An application that can complete the request.

inputs.name: actionPlatform
inputs.help: The high level platform(s) where the Action can be performed for the given URL. To specify a specific application or operating system instance, use actionApplication.

inputs.name: application
inputs.help: An application that can complete the request.

inputs.name: contentType
inputs.help: The supported content type(s) for an EntryPoint response.

inputs.name: encodingType
inputs.help: The supported encoding type(s) for an EntryPoint request.

inputs.name: httpMethod
inputs.help: An HTTP method that specifies the appropriate HTTP method for a request to an HTTP EntryPoint. Values are capitalized strings as used in HTTP.

inputs.name: urlTemplate
inputs.help: An url template (RFC6570) that will be used to construct the target of the execution of the action.

PreventionIndication.name: PreventionIndication
PreventionIndication.help: An indication for preventing an underlying condition, symptom, etc.

BusinessFunction.name: BusinessFunction
BusinessFunction.help:
The business function specifies the type of activity or access (i.e., the bundle of rights) offered by the organization or business person through the offer. Typical are sell, rental or lease, maintenance or repair, manufacture / produce, recycle / dispose, engineering / construction, or installation. Proprietary specifications of access rights are also instances of this class.

Commonly used values:

* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ConstructionInstallation
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Dispose
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#LeaseOut
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Maintain
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#ProvideService
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Repair
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Sell
* http://purl.org/goodrelations/v1#Buy

Schedule.name: Schedule
Schedule.help:
A schedule defines a repeating time period used to describe a regularly occurring [[Event]]. At a minimum a schedule will specify [[repeatFrequency]] which describes the interval between occurences of the event. Additional information can be provided to specify the schedule more precisely.
      This includes identifying the day(s) of the week or month when the recurring event will take place, in addition to its start and end time. Schedules may also
      have start and end dates to indicate when they are active, e.g. to define a limited calendar of events.

inputs.name: byDay
inputs.help: Defines the day(s) of the week on which a recurring [[Event]] takes place. May be specified using either [[DayOfWeek]], or alternatively [[Text]] conforming to iCal's syntax for byDay recurrence rules.

inputs.name: byMonth
inputs.help: Defines the month(s) of the year on which a recurring [[Event]] takes place. Specified as an [[Integer]] between 1-12. January is 1.

inputs.name: byMonthDay
inputs.help: Defines the day(s) of the month on which a recurring [[Event]] takes place. Specified as an [[Integer]] between 1-31.

inputs.name: byMonthWeek
inputs.help: Defines the week(s) of the month on which a recurring Event takes place. Specified as an Integer between 1-5. For clarity, byMonthWeek is best used in conjunction with byDay to indicate concepts like the first and third Mondays of a month.

inputs.name: duration
inputs.help: The duration of the item (movie, audio recording, event, etc.) in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601).

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: endTime
inputs.help: The endTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to end. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from January to *December*. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the end of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

inputs.name: exceptDate
inputs.help:
Defines a [[Date]] or [[DateTime]] during which a scheduled [[Event]] will not take place. The property allows exceptions to
      a [[Schedule]] to be specified. If an exception is specified as a [[DateTime]] then only the event that would have started at that specific date and time
      should be excluded from the schedule. If an exception is specified as a [[Date]] then any event that is scheduled for that 24 hour period should be
      excluded from the schedule. This allows a whole day to be excluded from the schedule without having to itemise every scheduled event.

inputs.name: repeatCount
inputs.help: Defines the number of times a recurring [[Event]] will take place

inputs.name: repeatFrequency
inputs.help:
Defines the frequency at which [[Event]]s will occur according to a schedule [[Schedule]]. The intervals between
      events should be defined as a [[Duration]] of time.

inputs.name: scheduleTimezone
inputs.help: Indicates the timezone for which the time(s) indicated in the [[Schedule]] are given. The value provided should be among those listed in the IANA Time Zone Database.

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: startTime
inputs.help: The startTime of something. For a reserved event or service (e.g. FoodEstablishmentReservation), the time that it is expected to start. For actions that span a period of time, when the action was performed. e.g. John wrote a book from *January* to December. For media, including audio and video, it's the time offset of the start of a clip within a larger file.\n\nNote that Event uses startDate/endDate instead of startTime/endTime, even when describing dates with times. This situation may be clarified in future revisions.

AchieveAction.name: AchieveAction
AchieveAction.help: The act of accomplishing something via previous efforts. It is an instantaneous action rather than an ongoing process.

DeliveryEvent.name: DeliveryEvent
DeliveryEvent.help: An event involving the delivery of an item.

inputs.name: accessCode
inputs.help: Password, PIN, or access code needed for delivery (e.g. from a locker).

inputs.name: availableFrom
inputs.help: When the item is available for pickup from the store, locker, etc.

inputs.name: availableThrough
inputs.help: After this date, the item will no longer be available for pickup.

inputs.name: hasDeliveryMethod
inputs.help: Method used for delivery or shipping.

HowToStep.name: HowToStep
HowToStep.help: A step in the instructions for how to achieve a result. It is an ordered list with HowToDirection and/or HowToTip items.

UserDownloads.name: UserDownloads
UserDownloads.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

RsvpAction.name: RsvpAction
RsvpAction.help: The act of notifying an event organizer as to whether you expect to attend the event.

inputs.name: additionalNumberOfGuests
inputs.help: If responding yes, the number of guests who will attend in addition to the invitee.

inputs.name: comment
inputs.help: Comments, typically from users.

inputs.name: rsvpResponse
inputs.help: The response (yes, no, maybe) to the RSVP.

MonetaryAmount.name: MonetaryAmount
MonetaryAmount.help: A monetary value or range. This type can be used to describe an amount of money such as $50 USD, or a range as in describing a bank account being suitable for a balance between £1,000 and £1,000,000 GBP, or the value of a salary, etc. It is recommended to use [[PriceSpecification]] Types to describe the price of an Offer, Invoice, etc.

inputs.name: currency
inputs.help: The currency in which the monetary amount is expressed.\n\nUse standard formats: [ISO 4217 currency format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_4217) e.g. "USD"; [Ticker symbol](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_cryptocurrencies) for cryptocurrencies e.g. "BTC"; well known names for [Local Exchange Tradings Systems](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Local_exchange_trading_system) (LETS) and other currency types e.g. "Ithaca HOUR".

inputs.name: maxValue
inputs.help: The upper value of some characteristic or property.

inputs.name: minValue
inputs.help: The lower value of some characteristic or property.

inputs.name: validFrom
inputs.help: The date when the item becomes valid.

inputs.name: validThrough
inputs.help: The date after when the item is not valid. For example the end of an offer, salary period, or a period of opening hours.

inputs.name: value
inputs.help:
The value of the quantitative value or property value node.

* For [[QuantitativeValue]] and [[MonetaryAmount]], the recommended type for values is 'Number'.
* For [[PropertyValue]], it can be 'Text;', 'Number', 'Boolean', or 'StructuredValue'.
* Use values from 0123456789 (Unicode 'DIGIT ZERO' (U+0030) to 'DIGIT NINE' (U+0039)) rather than superficially similiar Unicode symbols.
* Use '.' (Unicode 'FULL STOP' (U+002E)) rather than ',' to indicate a decimal point. Avoid using these symbols as a readability separator.

Gene.name: Gene
Gene.help: A discrete unit of inheritance which affects one or more biological traits (Source: [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gene)). Examples include FOXP2 (Forkhead box protein P2), SCARNA21 (small Cajal body-specific RNA 21), A- (agouti genotype).

inputs.name: alternativeOf
inputs.help: Another gene which is a variation of this one.

inputs.name: encodesBioChemEntity
inputs.help: Another BioChemEntity encoded by this one.

inputs.name: expressedIn
inputs.help: Tissue, organ, biological sample, etc in which activity of this gene has been observed experimentally. For example brain, digestive system.

inputs.name: hasBioPolymerSequence
inputs.help: A symbolic representation of a BioChemEnity. For example, a nucleotide sequence of a Gene or an amino acid sequence of a Protein.

ParcelDelivery.name: ParcelDelivery
ParcelDelivery.help: The delivery of a parcel either via the postal service or a commercial service.

inputs.name: carrier
inputs.help: 'carrier' is an out-dated term indicating the 'provider' for parcel delivery and flights.

inputs.name: deliveryAddress
inputs.help: Destination address.

inputs.name: deliveryStatus
inputs.help: New entry added as the package passes through each leg of its journey (from shipment to final delivery).

inputs.name: expectedArrivalFrom
inputs.help: The earliest date the package may arrive.

inputs.name: expectedArrivalUntil
inputs.help: The latest date the package may arrive.

inputs.name: hasDeliveryMethod
inputs.help: Method used for delivery or shipping.

inputs.name: itemShipped
inputs.help: Item(s) being shipped.

inputs.name: originAddress
inputs.help: Shipper's address.

inputs.name: partOfOrder
inputs.help: The overall order the items in this delivery were included in.

inputs.name: provider
inputs.help: The service provider, service operator, or service performer; the goods producer. Another party (a seller) may offer those services or goods on behalf of the provider. A provider may also serve as the seller.

inputs.name: trackingNumber
inputs.help: Shipper tracking number.

inputs.name: trackingUrl
inputs.help: Tracking url for the parcel delivery.

ImageObjectSnapshot.name: ImageObjectSnapshot
ImageObjectSnapshot.help: A specific and exact (byte-for-byte) version of an [[ImageObject]]. Two byte-for-byte identical files, for the purposes of this type, considered identical. If they have different embedded metadata (e.g. XMP, EXIF) the files will differ. Different external facts about the files, e.g. creator or dateCreated that aren't represented in their actual content, do not affect this notion of identity.

LibrarySystem.name: LibrarySystem
LibrarySystem.help: A [[LibrarySystem]] is a collaborative system amongst several libraries.

PaymentChargeSpecification.name: PaymentChargeSpecification
PaymentChargeSpecification.help: The costs of settling the payment using a particular payment method.

inputs.name: appliesToDeliveryMethod
inputs.help: The delivery method(s) to which the delivery charge or payment charge specification applies.

inputs.name: appliesToPaymentMethod
inputs.help: The payment method(s) to which the payment charge specification applies.

inputs.name: awayTeam
inputs.help: The away team in a sports event.

inputs.name: competitor
inputs.help: A competitor in a sports event.

inputs.name: homeTeam
inputs.help: The home team in a sports event.

inputs.name: sport
inputs.help: A type of sport (e.g. Baseball).

ReserveAction.name: ReserveAction
ReserveAction.help:
Reserving a concrete object.

Related actions:

* [[ScheduleAction]]: Unlike ScheduleAction, ReserveAction reserves concrete objects (e.g. a table, a hotel) towards a time slot / spatial allocation.

GameServer.name: GameServer
GameServer.help: Server that provides game interaction in a multiplayer game.

inputs.name: game
inputs.help: Video game which is played on this server.

inputs.name: playersOnline
inputs.help: Number of players on the server.

inputs.name: serverStatus
inputs.help: Status of a game server.

Seat.name: Seat
Seat.help: Used to describe a seat, such as a reserved seat in an event reservation.

inputs.name: seatNumber
inputs.help: The location of the reserved seat (e.g., 27).

inputs.name: seatRow
inputs.help: The row location of the reserved seat (e.g., B).

inputs.name: seatSection
inputs.help: The section location of the reserved seat (e.g. Orchestra).

inputs.name: seatingType
inputs.help: The type/class of the seat.

CreativeWorkSeries.name: CreativeWorkSeries
CreativeWorkSeries.help:
A CreativeWorkSeries in schema.org is a group of related items, typically but not necessarily of the same kind. CreativeWorkSeries are usually organized into some order, often chronological. Unlike [[ItemList]] which is a general purpose data structure for lists of things, the emphasis with CreativeWorkSeries is on published materials (written e.g. books and periodicals, or media such as tv, radio and games).

Specific subtypes are available for describing [[TVSeries]], [[RadioSeries]], [[MovieSeries]], [[BookSeries]], [[Periodical]] and [[VideoGameSeries]]. In each case, the [[hasPart]] / [[isPartOf]] properties can be used to relate the CreativeWorkSeries to its parts. The general CreativeWorkSeries type serves largely just to organize these more specific and practical subtypes.

It is common for properties applicable to an item from the series to be usefully applied to the containing group. Schema.org attempts to anticipate some of these cases, but publishers should be free to apply properties of the series parts to the series as a whole wherever they seem appropriate.

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: issn
inputs.help: The International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) that identifies this serial publication. You can repeat this property to identify different formats of, or the linking ISSN (ISSN-L) for, this serial publication.

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

CreativeWorkSeason.name: CreativeWorkSeason
CreativeWorkSeason.help: A media season e.g. tv, radio, video game etc.

inputs.name: actor
inputs.help: An actor, e.g. in tv, radio, movie, video games etc., or in an event. Actors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: director
inputs.help: A director of e.g. tv, radio, movie, video gaming etc. content, or of an event. Directors can be associated with individual items or with a series, episode, clip.

inputs.name: endDate
inputs.help: The end date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: episode
inputs.help: An episode of a tv, radio or game media within a series or season.

inputs.name: episodes
inputs.help: An episode of a TV/radio series or season.

inputs.name: numberOfEpisodes
inputs.help: The number of episodes in this season or series.

inputs.name: partOfSeries
inputs.help: The series to which this episode or season belongs.

inputs.name: productionCompany
inputs.help: The production company or studio responsible for the item e.g. series, video game, episode etc.

inputs.name: seasonNumber
inputs.help: Position of the season within an ordered group of seasons.

inputs.name: startDate
inputs.help: The start date and time of the item (in [ISO 8601 date format](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601)).

inputs.name: trailer
inputs.help: The trailer of a movie or tv/radio series, season, episode, etc.

GovernmentService.name: GovernmentService
GovernmentService.help: A service provided by a government organization, e.g. food stamps, veterans benefits, etc.

inputs.name: jurisdiction
inputs.help: Indicates a legal jurisdiction, e.g. of some legislation, or where some government service is based.

inputs.name: serviceOperator
inputs.help: The operating organization, if different from the provider.  This enables the representation of services that are provided by an organization, but operated by another organization like a subcontractor.

Project.name: Project
Project.help:
An enterprise (potentially individual but typically collaborative), planned to achieve a particular aim.
Use properties from [[Organization]], [[subOrganization]]/[[parentOrganization]] to indicate project sub-structures.

ListItem.name: ListItem
ListItem.help: An list item, e.g. a step in a checklist or how-to description.

inputs.name: item
inputs.help: An entity represented by an entry in a list or data feed (e.g. an 'artist' in a list of 'artists')’.

inputs.name: nextItem
inputs.help: A link to the ListItem that follows the current one.

inputs.name: position
inputs.help: The position of an item in a series or sequence of items.

inputs.name: previousItem
inputs.help: A link to the ListItem that preceeds the current one.

Landform.name: Landform
Landform.help: A landform or physical feature.  Landform elements include mountains, plains, lakes, rivers, seascape and oceanic waterbody interface features such as bays, peninsulas, seas and so forth, including sub-aqueous terrain features such as submersed mountain ranges, volcanoes, and the great ocean basins.

PhysicalActivityCategory.name: PhysicalActivityCategory
PhysicalActivityCategory.help: Categories of physical activity, organized by physiologic classification.

UserComments.name: UserComments
UserComments.help: UserInteraction and its subtypes is an old way of talking about users interacting with pages. It is generally better to use [[Action]]-based vocabulary, alongside types such as [[Comment]].

inputs.name: commentText
inputs.help: The text of the UserComment.

inputs.name: commentTime
inputs.help: The time at which the UserComment was made.

inputs.name: creator
inputs.help: The creator/author of this CreativeWork. This is the same as the Author property for CreativeWork.

inputs.name: discusses
inputs.help: Specifies the CreativeWork associated with the UserComment.

inputs.name: replyToUrl
inputs.help: The URL at which a reply may be posted to the specified UserComment.

PhotographAction.name: PhotographAction
PhotographAction.help: The act of capturing still images of objects using a camera.

ProductCollection.name: ProductCollection
ProductCollection.help: A set of products (either [[ProductGroup]]s or specific variants) that are listed together e.g. in an [[Offer]].

inputs.name: includesObject
inputs.help: This links to a node or nodes indicating the exact quantity of the products included in  an [[Offer]] or [[ProductCollection]].

ActivateAction.name: ActivateAction
ActivateAction.help: The act of starting or activating a device or application (e.g. starting a timer or turning on a flashlight).

CompoundPriceSpecification.name: CompoundPriceSpecification
CompoundPriceSpecification.help: A compound price specification is one that bundles multiple prices that all apply in combination for different dimensions of consumption. Use the name property of the attached unit price specification for indicating the dimension of a price component (e.g. "electricity" or "final cleaning").

inputs.name: priceComponent
inputs.help: This property links to all [[UnitPriceSpecification]] nodes that apply in parallel for the [[CompoundPriceSpecification]] node.

inputs.name: priceType
inputs.help: Defines the type of a price specified for an offered product, for example a list price, a (temporary) sale price or a manufacturer suggested retail price. If multiple prices are specified for an offer the [[priceType]] property can be used to identify the type of each such specified price. The value of priceType can be specified as a value from enumeration PriceTypeEnumeration or as a free form text string for price types that are not already predefined in PriceTypeEnumeration.

3DModel.name: 3DModel
3DModel.help:
A 3D model represents some kind of 3D content, which may have [[encoding]]s in one or more [[MediaObject]]s. Many 3D formats are available (e.g. see [Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:3D_graphics_file_formats)); specific encoding formats can be represented using the [[encodingFormat]] property applied to the relevant [[MediaObject]]. For the
case of a single file published after Zip compression, the convention of appending '+zip' to the [[encodingFormat]] can be used. Geospatial, AR/VR, artistic/animation, gaming, engineering and scientific content can all be represented using [[3DModel]].

inputs.name: isResizable
inputs.help: Whether the 3DModel allows resizing. For example, room layout applications often do not allow 3DModel elements to be resized to reflect reality.

MedicalTrial.name: MedicalTrial
MedicalTrial.help: A medical trial is a type of medical study that uses scientific process used to compare the safety and efficacy of medical therapies or medical procedures. In general, medical trials are controlled and subjects are allocated at random to the different treatment and/or control groups.

inputs.name: trialDesign
inputs.help: Specifics about the trial design (enumerated).

DataFeed.name: DataFeed
DataFeed.help: A single feed providing structured information about one or more entities or topics.

inputs.name: dataFeedElement
inputs.help: An item within in a data feed. Data feeds may have many elements.

RepositoryCollection.name: RepositoryCollection
RepositoryCollection.help: A Collection is a group of resources. Collections have descriptive metadata, access metadata, and may links to works and/or collections. By default, member works and collections are an

inputs.name: hasMember
inputs.help: Links to a subsidiary Object or Collection. Typically used to link   to component parts, such as a book linking to a page.  Note on transitivity: hasMember is   not defined as transitive, but applications may treat it as transitive as local needs   dictate.

RepositoryObject.name: RepositoryObject
RepositoryObject.help: An Object is an intellectual entity, sometimes called a "work", "digital object", etc. Objects have descriptive metadata, access metadata, may contain files and other Objects as member "components". Each level of a work is therefore represented by an Object instance, and is capable of standing on its own, being linked to from Collections and other Objects. Member Objects can be ordered using the ORE Proxy class.

inputs.name: hasFile
inputs.help: Links to a File contained by this Object.

inputs.name: hasMember
inputs.help: Links to a subsidiary Object or Collection. Typically used to link   to component parts, such as a book linking to a page.  Note on transitivity: hasMember is   not defined as transitive, but applications may treat it as transitive as local needs   dictate.

inputs.name: ComputationalWorkflow#input
inputs.help: An input required to use the computational workflow (eg. Excel spreadsheet, BAM file)

inputs.name: ComputationalWorkflow#output
inputs.help: An output produced by the computational workflow
